[White "Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Repertoire Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

{Welcome to my 2020 updated Caro-Kann course! In our introductory file I would
like to give you an overview of our repertoire. This is not a comprehensive
file of every single line, rather it can serve you as a roadmap as to White's
and Black's options. I will also outline where I present several options for
Black and my thoughts on how you can pick your preferred lines.} 1. e4 c6 {
Here we go! Our idea is to occupy the center with c6-d5 and adopt a light
square strategy. By attacking White's e4 pawn we also strive to give our Bc8 a
home on f5 square, although as we will see we don't always utilize the
possibility.} 2. d4 {Surely the best move for White is to occupy the center
but he also has some other viable options} (2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 {Is a very
popular and sound variation known as the "Two Knights." This variation has
seen a surge of popularity in the last years as it has been recommended in
several White repertoires and new ideas have been found.} dxe4 {Capturing on
e4 seeks to transpose to positions seen in the Tartakower Classical variation 
(see main line) which have been revived with new ideas for Black in recent
years.} (3... Bg4 {is the solid and most popular move. The main line goes} 4.
h3 Bxf3 (4... Bh5 $5 {is a sharper and more ambitious reaction where we look
at some dynamic analysis}) 5. Qxf3 e6 {[%csl Gb7,Gc1,Gc6,Gd5,Ge6,Gf1,Gf7]
Where White is happy to get the bishop pair but Black is very solid and puts
the pawns on the light squares. There have been many setups tried for White
here but I have an offbeat suggestion for Black involving a Kingside
fianchetto:} 6. d3 Nd7 7. Bd2 g6 $5 {Probably White is better in some of these
g6 lines but it is an easy to play setup for Black that will take the fight to
the middlegame. I would recommend this line if you are looking for a shortcut
or as a surprise weapon in addition to the other options.}) (3... Nf6 $5 {
Is arguably the most combatative move that aims to challenge the center
without conceeding the bishop pair (as in 3...Bg4) . This line is more complex
and fighting but in recent years White has discovered a very dangerous idea:}
4. e5 Ne4 5. Ne2 Qb6 6. d4 e6 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 $1 {[%csl Re8]
[%cal Gf1f8] This concept of unconventionally capturing away from the center
gives White very aggressive dynamic opportunities on the Kingside involving
the open f-file. White's results here have been very promising and I actually
found out about the danger's of Black's position in a firsthand brutal loss!
However Black does have defensive resources although the position is tricky.
Therefore 3..Nf6 is not my main recommendation but is still worth checking out,
especially if 9. fxg3! is netraulized further.}) (3... a6 {This little pawn
nudge is roughly 50x less popular than the main move 3..Bg4 so it contains
great surprise value. It also scores 56% for Black! We are making a small
useful waiting move to control the b5 square and considering playing Bg4 at a
more opportune moment. I would recommend having this variation as a surprise
and/or quickplay recommendation at an advanced level.} 4. d4 Bg4) 4. Nxe4 Nf6
5. Qe2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e8] This cheeky move has become White's main
recommendation in past years to keep the play into "Two Knights" territory. I
think White would be a very decent and knowledgeable player to know this line.}
(5. Nxf6+ exf6 {Leads to Tartakower-esque positions where Black's rapid
development compensates for the doubled pawns.}) 5... Nxe4 (5... Na6 $5 {
What the heck is this move? I couldn't resist including it as it has been
played by creative GMs like Rapport and Kovalenko. It is definitely a surprise
weapon if you want to be a bit funny and has brought good results, although
White isn't really complaining about this move}) (5... Nbd7 $4 6. Nd6# {
Hopefully if you see this trick once you will never fall for it!}) (5... Bf5) (
5... Bg4 {Bf5 and Bg4 have been tried by several strong players. White should
have an edge but Black can roll this way from time to time}) 6. Qxe4 Qa5 {
[%cal Gc8f5,Ra5e1] This move scores great for Black! The idea is Bf5 and to
prevent d4.} (6... Nd7 $5 {Used to be considered a positional mistake because
of the "trap"} 7. Bc4 Nf6 8. Ne5 {[%cal Gc4f7]} e6 9. Qe2 {Now Black's Bc8 is
very passive but things are not so clear after} b5 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8b7] As
Black will gain several tempi}) (6... Qd5 {This is the main option for Black
and seems to be ok too. Between these three options I would say Nd7 has the
potential to be the trickiest but they are all solid. For more details refer
to the Two Knights file!})) (2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 (3. d3 {Is a strange KIA-esque
setup that has been tried frequently recently by some very good players and
was also the recommended in an opening article.}) 3... cxd5 4. d4 {is an
offshoot type of Exchange Variation of the Caro. This line is sometimes used
by strong players as a surprise weapon for a game or two (I am guilty of this!)
but is exceptionally popular at the u1800 level and online from my students'
experiences. White goes for simple development but lets Black do the same. The
resulting middgames are give us comfortable play as I will show in the files.})
(2. c4 {is known as the "Pseudo-Panov" and after} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 (4.
d4 {is the Panov}) 4... Nf6 {White has some options to try to cause trouble
before Black collects the pawn back and short castles. With knowledge of a few
key lines Black will emerge in good shape. I would say this line is not really
seen much nowadays and is not popular at club level, although it is completely
respectable.}) (2. d3 {is a "KIA" (Kings Indian Attack) setup which of course
will have it's Kings Indian fans. I've definitely seen it a fair bit online
and several times OTB but we will get a good game by taking over the center} d5
3. Nd2 e5) 2... d5 3. Nc3 {Protecting the pawn with Nc3/Nd2 is known as the
"Classical" variation. Nothing more classical than developing a piece and
protecting the center! This variation remains extremely popular but in my
opinion is not as challenging as the Advance variation (3. e5). Nevertheless
it does enjoy the greatest popularity at club level and many of my students
rated 1400-2000 face this move most frequently. Of course it is still played
on master+ level and has been for centuries.} (3. Nd2 dxe4 {Will transpose to
3. Nc3}) (3. e5 $1 {I believe that the Advance Variation may be the "best"
line at White's disposal. The idea is clear: grab the space! Now the main move
is 3...Bf5, a move that is certainly very adequate and developing. However, I
am rolling with the less popular 3..c5! This has been the move that I've
relied on most throughout the years and my loyalty was even rewarded with the
win that brought me my first GM norm!} c5 $5 4. dxc5 $1 {This greedy move is
considered critical. White grabs the pawn and dares Black to retrieve it!} (4.
c3 {This is a very important move to analyze. Although 4. dxc5! is arguable
most challenging, 4. c3 is roughly 3x more popular at the club level. However
this move is not so tough as it allows Black a version of a "good french".
Something like:} Nc6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 {[%csl Rd4,Gg4][%cal Gd8b6,Gg8h6,
Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Gh6f5] is an example! The position has a French structure (e4 e6
d4 d5 e5 c5) with the key distinction of Black's Bc8 being active on g4! This
is another reason I am happy to recommend 3..c5: many opponents will
unwittingly allow us this juicy continuation.}) (4. c4 $5 {is an aggressive
option} cxd4 5. Nf3 Bg4 (5... e6 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gc5b4] is a
solid approach}) 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qa5 $5 {Goes for a more unbalanced fight}
(7... Bxf3 8. Nxd5 Bxd1 9. Nc7+ Kd7 10. Nxa8 Bc2 {Leads to a forcing variation
which often ends in perpetual}) 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qxd4 Bxf3 11.
gxf3 e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Ge7d5]}) 4... e6 (4... Nc6 $5 {This is the
ambitious way to continue. We refuse to close the Bc8! I think that unless
White has deep theoretical knowledge of the position then Nc6 would be my
choice (and has been vs several master+ players). However White does have some
challenging retorts that we need to deal with.}) 5. a3 $1 {White's best and
most challenging tries have become centered around the idea of playing
a3-b4-Bb2 setups. These approaches from White are very challenging and they
are preferred by strong theoretically prepared opponents! Furthermore White
can also toy with the move order by delaying either a3 or b4. We will need to
have a look at these critical options but my main recommendation is to delay
the development of the Nb8, for example:} (5. Be3 {is the old main line but a3
approaches have been overshadowing it completely. We will continue trying to
get our pawn back and our options are} Nd7 {[%cal Gf8c5]} (5... Nh6 {[%csl Re3]
[%cal Gh6f5,Gf8c5]})) (5. Nf3 {What also makes this variation annoying for us
is that White has multiple move orders that either delay a2-a3 or b2-b4.
Therefore we must learn several key subtleties for our fair share of chances})
5... Bxc5 6. b4 Be7 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb8d7,Gd7c5] is an idea that I've played
to score an important victory in my pursuit of GMs norms. I have left the
nitty gritty details to the main file of the Advance, but I will admit that
this will arguably be one of the more advanced chapters in the course. So in
conclusion if you are playing u2000 opponents you can often expect the
imprecise 4. C3?! which will lessen your burden but if you face masters (or
well prepared amateurs!) will be helpful to know what to do vs dxc5 as well.})
(3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gc2c3,Gb1d2,Gg1f3] This is the "Exchange
Variation" and is a very popular line with Masters and Amateurs alike. It is
also a very frequent guest in online play. The allure of this line for White
is the promise of a simple developmental setup with potential attacking
chances.} (4. c4 {This is the "Panov-Botvinnik Attack." This variation often
gives rise to the famous "IQP" (Isolated Queen's Pawn) structures that has
been debating and analyzed endlessly over the past century. There isn't
anything particularly wrong with this line for White in my view its popularity
has been dwindling. I used to place it in the "Big Four" of Classical, Advance,
and Exchange variations but I think now the Two Knights is more popular.
Anyway, my main recommendation is the g6 fianchetto which can be very
unpleasant for White to face if he is unprepared (a common issue here for club/
amateur players!). My surprise recommendation is one that I've used
successfully myself and will either give you a second option or you can even
make it your main idea!} Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 {My preference. By fianchettoing our
Bf8 we keep the Bc8 open and also seek to put additional pressure onto the d4
pawn.} (5... Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 Ne4 $5 {This line can lead to very dynamic
play after} 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. d5 Ne5 9. Qd4 f6 {Both Kings are stuck in the
center for now but Black hopes to be the one to benefit by sacrificing the e4
pawn for rapid development}) 6... Be6 {Surprise! This quirky move seeks to
resolve the pressure on the d5 pawn and force White to make a decision.} 7. c5
(7. cxd5 Bxd5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e6]}) 7... g6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf8g7,Ge6g4]})
6. Nf3 (6. Qb3 $1 Bg7 7. cxd5 {is the main and critical line. We sacrifice a
pawn but will try to collect it back in the future! Again as I have said about
several of the lines in this overview, this is a line that either a Master or
well prepared opponent will use. Of course I have analyzed this idea deeply to
give you good retorts in either case. Nevertheless if you are facing an
unprepared or amateur opponent then the inferior 6. Nf3?! will be seen more
often!}) 6... Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7d4,
Gc6d4,Gd8d4,Gc8g4,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] is a pleasant anti-IQP position!}) 4... Nc6 5.
c3 Qc7 {[%cal Rc1f4] This main line option prevents Bf4 and has generally
scored very strongly for Black. However in recent years White has discovered a
new idea:} (5... Nf6 6. Bf4 g6 $5 {This was the first line I learned vs the
Exchange I really liked and have shown it to many of my students. The
resulting positions are easy to play and White is often unsure how to meet
them. Definitely recommend this line for u2200 play:} (6... Bg4 {is the
mainest of the main lines so we will take a peek here as well.}) 7. Nd2 Bg7 8.
Ngf3 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 {Black scores 56% here. We will occupy e4
and perhaps use the g-file to attack}) 6. Ne2 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Bg4 7. O-O (7. f3
{is the old main line but scores a pathetic 38% for White!}) 7... e6 8. Qe1 $1
{This funky Queen slide looks to put the Bg4 in trouble and has revived
White's interest in this sector of the Exchange variation. At first Black was
caught unawares and would play suboptimal moves such as Bxe2 and Bd6? However
I will explore much better ideas in the exchange file that lead to a fair
complex battle}) (3. f3 {This is the "Fantasy Variation". This can be a very
unpleasant line to face without preparation as White seeks to have a big
center and attack/squash us.} e6 {Keeping things nice and solid, frustrating
White.} (3... dxe4 {is not bad but kind of gives White what he wants (open
game with attacking chances)}) (3... e5 $5 {This violent counterattacking
gambit is probably not fully sound but can really devastate White! I would
file this as a main weapon for u2200 and a worthy surprise in general.} 4. dxe5
Bc5 {[%csl Re1]}) 4. Nc3 Qb6 $5 {Bringing the queen out early but placing
annoying pressure on the d4/b2 pawns. This move has scored excellently for
Black but is not very popular. That is a perfect repertoire weapon for my
checklist!}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {This variation has been around for a while
but perhaps did not enjoy the best reputation as Black is seemingly doubling
his pawns for no gain. However it is apparent nowadays that such thinking was
too simplistic and Nf6 is enjoying a big surge in popularity. I definitely
think this is the move to learn as your main weapon for u2200 level and it has
brought my students and many other players fantastic results! Furthermore,
this line has been used very sucessfully by Grandmasters (and World Champion
Magnus) so don't be fooled into thinking this is some junky weapon!} (4... Bf5
{This is the main move and is known as the Capablanca variation. This move is
perfectly fine and I have played it myself for many years and many games.
While I don't think 4...Nf6 is better than 4...Bf5 I do think that Bf5 is
tougher to learn as White has more options. Nevertheless you may want to have
two options or just prefer the positions here. I have done a lot of analysis
on these lines so you can be sure that the files here will help you!} 5. Ng3
Bg6 {White actually has a lot of pesky sideline setups here but we will just
overview the main line} 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 e6 $5 {is very interesting and a
modern twist. Black doesn't mind allowing Ne5 and also hopes that the Nb8 may
jump to c6 instead in the future. I think Black is doing fine after Nd7 as
well but White may be less prepared to deal with this modern try; also from a
personal standpoint I've played this way less and so it was more fun for me to
analyze} (7... Nd7 {This is the very well explored "old main line" and often
times the opening moves are blitzed here} 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11.
Bd2 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Qd5 {
While both sides had deviations along the way, this is really the main line
with 750 games played. Again I should say that this "Old Main Line" is fine
for black but has arguably been better trodden than the paths of 7..e6!? or
the earlier 4... Nf6 Tartakower.}) 8. Ne5 (8. h5 Bh7 {If White insists on
playing the "regular moves" then Black will make full use of delaying Nd7 to
play c5-Nc6} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nf6 11. Bd2 Be7 (11... c5 $5) 12. O-O-O c5 $5
(12... O-O 13. Kb1 c5 {There are multiple intrepretations of the c5 idea as
well!})) 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. f4 {The critical approach is to
entrench the centralized knight} (11. Bf4 {Leads to a less complex fight and
often an endgame}) 11... Bb4+ $5 (11... Be7 {is a new idea that is based on
the concrete idea to sacrifice the whole kingside after} 12. Bd2 Nxe5 13. fxe5
Bxh4 14. O-O-O Bxg3 15. Qxg3 Ne7 $1 16. Qxg7 Rg8 17. Qxh6 Qd5 $44) 12. c3 Be7 {
We provoked a small weakness and after further opposite side castling the game
will be very double edged. Will White be able to get in a successful attack
with g4? Probably not if you study the files to see how to defend!}) 5. Nxf6+ {
Really this makes the most sense but of course we will look at alternatives in
the main file.} exf6 $1 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Gb8d7] As mentioned, Black
does get doubled pawns but now development will flow as free as water. Often
times Black will also get attacking chances on the Kingside by pointing his
pieces there and potentially even sacrificing and pawn storming!} 6. c3 {
This move, or rather the setup that follows, has been established as White's
most testing idea. Many experienced players may know this from reviewing their
openings but it is very rare for an unprepared player to play this idea at the
board.} (6. Nf3 {An unprepared opponent is way more likely to develop
naturally as such and the resulting positions will give Black excellent play
and activity. Although I don't think Nf3 is the best move it is still
important to learn and understand the resulting positions for Black.} Bd6 7. h3
O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. O-O Be6 10. Be3 Nd7 11. Qd2 Nf8 12. Rfe1 Qd7 13. Rad1 Bxh3 $1
14. gxh3 Qxh3 $19 {[%cal Ge8e4,Ge4g4] is a taste of how Black can develop and
get an attack. See the files for more!}) 6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2
{Now Black has to make a decision regarding protecting the h7 pawn. This
variation was considered better for White for many years but recently has been
a fertile battle ground for many Grandmasters as Black discovered the idea} h5
$1 {This move was first played in 2014 but did not recieve attention until it
was repeated in 2017 by several Grandmasters. Since then hundreds of games
have tested this move and it is firmly the main line. The idea in a nutshell
is to get the pawn out of harm's way and often times push it to h4. The
subtleties will be further explored in the Tartakower file. Now White has a
choice: castle long or short? With a few key ideas, Black's game will be easy
to handle regardless and I believe this is an excellent repertoire option for
spirited play} (9... g6 {is desirable, but could be dangerous after} 10. h4 $1
{Still, the resulting positions have been successfully championed by strong
players such as the aggressive and creative GM Jobava so it doesn't hurt to
have a look at this option.. perhaps as the occasional surprise or rapid/blitz
idea.}) (9... f5 $5 {This is a rare idea that is very interesting. Several GMs
have tried it for Black and it could be a clever pawn sacrifice if White is
not prepared.}) (9... h6 {is the least assuming move which slightly weakens
our kingside and makes it hard to counter Ng3-Nf5. We will look at it as well
but 9...h5! is really a better version}) *

