{This guide aims to give you a quick and easy Caro guide. Want to hit the
ground running ASAP? Use this file to learn some quick ideas and start testing
them out. Then you can refer to the more detailed files to learn more. I would
also say this is a good repertoire starting point for anyone in the u2000
rating range. Knowing this file will get out of trouble from the opening 90%
of the time} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This version of the
exchange has been very popular in many of students' games. Let's play Nf6 and
Bg4 to develop the kingside and pin the knight. After a further e6-Be7/Bd6
castles and Nc6 we can attack on the queenside (half open c-file and pawn
storm)} Nf6 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8g4,Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} 5. Nc3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,
Gf8e7,Gb8c6,Ge8g8]}) (2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 {Two Knights Variation.} dxe4 4. Nxe4
Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Qe2 {A tricky move that a prepared player would make. Be
careful not to blunder and checkmates on the e-file after Nd6x} Bf5 {[%cal
Ge7e6,Gb8d7]} (5... Nbd7 $4 6. Nd6# {Avoid this!!})) 5... exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,
Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gb8d7] Transposes to the main line Tartakower Variation.}) (2. d3 {
The Kings Indian setup will always have its adverts. We respond by taking over
the center} d5 3. Nd2 e5 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8f6,Gb8d7,Ge8g8]}) (2. c4 {The
Pseudo-Panov is a cousin of the actual Panov.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 {
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gf6d5] Let's prepare a kingside development+fianchetto
and then recover the d pawn} 5. Qa4+ (5. Bb5+ Nbd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg7g6,
Gf8g7]}) 5... Nbd7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]}) 2... d5 3. Nc3 {Classical
Variation} (3. e5 c5 4. c3 {Below master level this is by far the most common
response.} (4. dxc5 {A challenging move if followed up correctly.} Nc6 {
[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7e6,Gf8c5,Gc6e5] Let's develop quickly and maybe get our
pawn back} 5. Nf3 (5. a3 {A strong idea.} e6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Ge8g8]
Preparing Bxc5 and then either a quick f7-f6 or Nge7-Ng6, 0-0 and then f6.} 6.
b4 $6 a5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5,Re5] is too loose for White}) (5. f4 {White crudely
seeks to defend the e5 pawn} Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gc8g4] It's possible to regain the
c5 pawn after e6 Be3 d4 but let's confuse White by playing for rapid
development}) 5... Bg4 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ra4e8,Ge7e6,Gf8c5,Gg8e7] Let's go e6,
bxc5, ne7->f5/g6. Be careful about capturing the e5 pawn as White often has
Nxe5/Bb5+/Qa4 counters.} 6. Bb5 Qa5+ {Useful idea to know} 7. Nc3 e6 {[%csl
Rc5][%cal Gf8c5]}) 4... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Our goals are to develop the Bc8
outside the pawn chain (before e6), pressuring d4 and castling short} 5. Nf3
Bg4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e6,Gd8b6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Further moves: e6,
ne7/nh6, Nf5, Be7, 0-0, Qb6. Look for ways to capture the d4 pawn as White may
defend it inadequately, but don't forget about development either}) (3. exd5
cxd5 4. Bd3 {Exchange Variation. White wants to develop smoothly and attack
our king later. Let's undercut his plans} (4. c4 {Panov-Botvinnik Attack. Not
too popular nowadays but still respected} Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal
Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gb8c6] Let's go for a fianchetto and eventually capture on c4 to
give White an isolated d4 pawn.} 6. Qb3 {The best move, not common u2200 for
sure. We will sacrifice the pawn for now and get it back later} (6. Nf3 Bg7 7.
Be2 dxc4 $1 {We take on c4 when White moves the Bf1 to make him lose a tempo}
8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8c6,Ga8c8] w/bb7 and Nc6 coming}) 6...
Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6]}) 4... Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 g6 $5 7. Nd2
Bg7 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf8g8,Gg8g1,Ge7e6,Gf6e4]
Use the e4 square for the Nf6 and consider a future Kh8-Rg8 idea to get a
kingside attack}) (3. f3 {The "Fantasy Variation."} e5 $5 {A gambit. Let's
show White that f2-f3 is not to be played!} 4. dxe5 Bc5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gg8e7,
Gd8b6] Continue developing quickly with Ne7/Qb6/0-0 as White struggles with
the Ke1}) (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 {is Classical Variation} Nf6) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
Nf6 {Accelerating our development at the cost of doubled pawns.} 5. Nxf6+ (5.
Ng3 h5 $5) 5... exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Gb8d7,Ge8g8] Our setup is: Bd6, 0-0,
Be6, Nd7, Re8, Nf8, Ng6, Qc7/Qd7 and Rad8. Look for ways to potentially attack
the Kingside} *

