{Time to wrap up our Simple Caro journey by looking at some "Miscellaneous"
lines. These lines are not bad, but historically have not been as common as
the Big 4. However the Two Knights has been seeing a surge of action in past
years} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 (2. d4 d5 3. f3 {The Fantasy Variation. White wants to
keep 2 pawns in the center.} e5 $5 {a violent response} (3... e6 {is more solid
} 4. Nc3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gc6c5] Keeping an eye on the b2 & d4 pawns
while preparing a future c6-c5, usually after Nf6 first}) 4. dxe5 (4. exd5 exd4
5. Qxd4 cxd5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gb8c6]}) 4... Bc5 {The point, the Ke1 can't castle
easily and Qb6 is on the agenda} 5. Nc3 Ne7 6. f4 $2 {White should focus on
developing instead of more pawn moves. His move is ambitious though as he
seeks to play Nf3} Qb6 7. Nf3 Bf2+ 8. Ke2 a5 $5 $44 {Now Na4 can be met by Qa7:
0-1 (15) Di Nicolantonio,L (2408)-Loiseau,Q (2470) Paris 2019}) (2. c4 {
This is called the "Pseudo-Panov" It can transpose into the Panov but
sometimes White changes it up.} d5 3. exd5 (3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 {
Transposes}) 3... cxd5 4. cxd5 (4. d4 {Panov}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 (5. Qa4+ Nbd7 {
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gd7b6]}) (5. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Block both checks with the
knight and try to regain the d5 pawn. Develop with g6-Bg7.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Nf3
Nxc3 $5 {a simpler solution here to cut down on theory} (6... Nc6 {Although
developing here is all good. If white doesn't do anything special we can play
g6, fianchetto, castle and pressure the IQP} 7. Bc4 (7. Bb5 e6 8. O-O Be7) (7.
d4 {Although this line could be a bit challenging} g6 $5 8. Qb3 (8. Bc4 Nb6 9.
Bb3 Bg7 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) 8... Nxc3 (8... e6) 9. Bc4 $1 Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+
bxc6 $13) 7... Nb6 8. Bb3 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7]}) 7. bxc3 g6 8. d4 Bg7 {
[%cal Gb8c6,Gb8b6,Gc8b7,Gc6a5,Ga8c8] This is called the "Hanging Pawns"
structure. It's a close cousin of the IQP (the b2 pawn moved to c3). Black's
plan here is: 0-0, Nc6, b6, Bb7, Na5, Rc8 and play on the light squares.}) (2.
Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 {is simplest to continue with Nc6/Bg4, there is
also the option of g6-Bf5 vs Bd3} (4... a6 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gb8c6,Gc8g4,Ge7e6]
Cuts out any Bb5 ideas and prepares to finish development})) (2. d3 d5 3. Nd2
e5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8d6,Gb8d7]} 4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 {
With a board full of pieces but extra space for Black. Further development
with Nbd7 and b6 (a5) Bb7/Ba6 is recommended.}) (2. f4 {allows us to control a
lot of light squares} d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 h5 6. Bd3 Nh6 {planning an
eventual c6-c5}) 2... d5 3. Nf3 {Two Knights: White just gets on with
development and will adjust his plans based on our reply} (3. Qf3 dxe4 {
is simplest and solid} (3... d4 {is an aggressive response} 4. Bc4 e6 5. Nce2
c5 {0-1 (39) Sutton,A (2283)-Grayland,S (2367) ICCF email 2015}) 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {
Looking for normal development}) (3. Qe2 $5 {a rare line I've actually taught
several of my students} e6 {is a solid French style response planning Nf6 next}
(3... d4 4. Nd1 {is White's weird idea to play f4 Nf2 later} e5 5. g3 Nf6 6. d3
Bb4+ $5 {trying to trade dark square bishops} 7. c3 Ba5 8. Bd2 O-O $15 {
0-1 (31) Efanov,N (2399)-Riazantsev,A (2646) Minsk 2015})) (3. d4 dxe4 4. f3 {
The Blackmar-Diemer gambit} exf3 (4... e5 {is a good option if you want to
decline the gambit}) 5. Nxf3 (5. Qxf3 $6 Qxd4 6. Be3 Qb4 7. O-O-O $2 Bg4) 5...
Nf6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. Ne5 Bg6 9. Bg5 Be7 {w/Nd7 coming and huge solidity
with the extra pawn}) 3... dxe4 {Maybe simplest is to offer a transposition to
the Tartakower (Classical Caro). However if you prefer the Capablanca in the
classical then I suggest the alternatives} (3... Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 {
is very solid. a possible idea is to develop with g6-Bg7 but the natural
Nf6-Be7 is also reasonable}) (3... a6 $5 4. d4 Bg4 {is a rarer version of the
Bg4 idea}) 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 $5 {A tricky idea to keep the game in Two
Knights territory. Please watch out for tricky ideas on the e-file such as Nd6
check or checkmate!} (5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. d4 Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gb8d7] Will
be a Tartakower}) 5... Bf5 {Since I want to give a quick solution I will offer
Bf5 although I think there are other good options for Black. Depending on your
taste and results you may want to explore the Two Knights chapters.} 6. Nxf6+ (
6. d3 e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black will continue solidly developing}) 6... gxf6
7. d4 (7. d3 Nd7 8. g3 Ne5 $5 {a funny idea} 9. Nxe5 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Qxe5
fxe5 {0-1 (50) Vachier Lagrave,M (2796)-Anand,V (2786) Leuven 2017}) 7... Qd5
$5 {[%cal Gd5e4,Gb8d7] Potentially looking to trade queens to avoid the Ke8
feeling any pain. If you want to avoid the queen trade check out this game
after 7..e6} (7... e6 8. g3 Nd7 9. Bg2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. c3 Re8
13. f4 f5 14. Be3 Nf6 15. Bf3 Qc7 16. Rac1 a5 17. c4 a4 18. Kg2 Rad8 19. Rfd1
Qa5 20. Bd2 Qa6 21. Be3 Rd7 22. Rc2 Red8 23. Bg1 Qa5 24. Rcd2 Qb4 25. h3 Ne4
26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Be3 f5 28. Nxg6 hxg6 29. h4 Kf7 30. h5 b5 31. hxg6+ Kxg6 32.
Rh1 Rh8 33. cxb5 Qxb5 34. Qd1 Rxh1 35. Kxh1 Rd8 36. Kg1 Bf6 37. g4 fxg4 38.
Qxg4+ Kf7 39. Rg2 Qf5 40. Qd1 Qh3 41. Qe1 Rh8 42. Kf1 Rg8 {0-1 (42) Bulmaga,I 
(2442)-Piorun,K (2643) Douglas 2019}) 8. c4 Qe4 9. Qxe4 Bxe4 10. Nh4 {This
looks strange, I guess White wanted to play f3 and Nxg6} Na6 11. f3 Bc2 $1 {
No Bishop for you!} 12. Be3 e5 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. Rc1 Bg6 15. a3 Bc5 {0-1 (43)
Karthikeyan,M (2585)-Artemiev,V (2697) Moscow 2018} *

