1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5
Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 (11. Bf4 {The old main line has fallen out
favor} Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 $1 13. c3 (13. Ne4 Ngf6 $1 {The Nd6+ is not so scary}
14. Nd6+ Ke7 15. Nc4 (15. Nxb7 Bxd2+ 16. Nxd2 Qb4 {[%cal Rd3a3]} 17. Qb3 Qxd4
18. O-O-O Rab8 {[%cal Gh8c8,Gc6c5,Ge7f8]}) 15... Bxd2+ 16. Nfxd2 Qc7 {[%cal
Gh8d8,Gc6c5]}) 13... Be7 14. c4 Qc7 15. O-O-O Ngf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b5] Black
successfully provoked c4 and will look to counterattack with b5, even at the
cost of a pawn}) 11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 {Prophylaxis. White removes
the king from potential harm and defends a2} (13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qe2
(15. Qd3 $5 {[%cal Gd3b3]} c5 16. Qb5+ Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Nxd7 $11) 15... Qd5 $1 {
[%cal Gd5a2,Gd5e4] An important and common motif for Black} 16. c4 (16. Kb1 {
Can directly transpose to the main line or contain similar ideas after} Qb5 $5
(16... O-O)) 16... Qe4 17. Qxe4 Nxe4 18. Be3 f5 $5 {[%cal Gf5f4,Ge7g5] An
attempt to imbalance the game in order to get counter chances}) (13. Qe2 c5 (
13... O-O 14. Nf1 $5 {[%cal Gg2g4] is dangerous but Black can get counterplay
that has been analyzed to a draw after} c5 $1)) 13... O-O 14. Ne4 (14. Qe2 Qb6
{[%cal Gc6c5]}) 14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Qd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e4]} 17. Be3
$1 {White prevents a queen trade and wants to eventually play g4-g5} (17. Ne5
Qe4 $11 {Leads to an equal endgame. White has more space but black is solid
and can prepare c5}) 17... Qb5 (17... b5 $5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Rc2c4] launches
a counterattack} 18. Ne5 Bd6 19. Nd3 a5 20. g4 a4 $132) 18. c4 Qf5+ {Black's
idea was to provoke this weakening} 19. Ka1 c5 20. Nh4 (20. Ne5 cxd4 21. Bxd4
Rfd8 $11) 20... Qh7 {[%cal Gh7b1] Black has scored well from this position and
the awkward seeming Qh7 actually controls a lot of useful light squares} *

[Event "?"]
