1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 e6 {
[%cal Gc6c5,Gb8c6] By omitting Nd7 Black hopes to develop more actively with
Nc6} 8. Ne5 {The critical try is to exploit the omission} (8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3
Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nf6 11. Bd2 (11. Bf4 Qa5+ (11... Bd6 $5) 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. c3 Be7
14. c4 Qc7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge8g8,Gb7b5] Could transpose to lines with an early
Nd7 in which Black provoked c2-c4 and so can aim for b7-b5 counterplay}) 11...
c5 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Our main idea and there are 3 different ways to implement
it with varying pros and cons} (11... Be7 12. O-O-O c5 $5 (12... O-O {[%cal
Gc6c5,Gb8c6]})) 12. O-O-O (12. Ne4 Nc6) 12... Nc6) 8... Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10.
Qxd3 Nd7 11. f4 {The main and most aggressive move} (11. Bf4 {is solid and may
become more popular} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Qa5+ 13. c3 Nf6 14. O-O Ng4 (14... Be7 {
Is less forcing}) 15. Rad1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Rd8 17. Qxd8+ Qxd8 18. Rxd8+ Kxd8 19.
Rd1+ Kc8 $11 {White is pushing but Black can defend this endgame a few careful
ideas}) 11... Be7 (11... Bb4+ $5 {Looking to provoke weaknesses} 12. c3 (12.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Ngf6 14. O-O-O O-O {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc7b6,Gc6c5,Rh6h5] Black
goes for typical Caro counterplay with the c5 break and may use h6-h5 to lock
the kingside up}) 12... Be7 {With a pawn on c3 White's control of light
squares is weakened and Black may also play Qa5 even if White has a bishop on
d2} 13. Bd2 Ngf6 14. O-O-O c5 $5) 12. Bd2 (12. h5 Ngf6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc6c5]
Black will castle and strike the center}) (12. Nh5 $5 Ngf6 $1 13. Nxg7+ Kf8 14.
Nxe6+ fxe6 {White has enough compensation for the piece in this complex line})
12... Nxe5 $1 13. fxe5 Bxh4 14. O-O-O Bxg3 15. Qxg3 Ne7 16. Qxg7 Rg8 17. Qxh6
Qd5 {There are further nuances in this position but often a combo of
0-0-0+nf5+rxg2 will give Black great piece activity and light square control} *

