1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 (5. Nc5 b6 {is the easy and
solid method} (5... e5 $5 {looks to exploit White's hopping horsey} 6. Nxb7 Qb6
7. Nc5 Bxc5 8. dxc5 Qxc5 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8,Gb8d7]}) 6. Nb3 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,
Gg8e7]}) 5... Bg6 6. h4 (6. Nh3 e6 7. Nf4 Qc7 {[%csl Rf4] puts pressure on Nf4
and prepares to meet h4 with Bd6} (7... Qh4 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gb8d7,Rh2h4] Stops h4
and prepares Nd7+Nf6+bd6 w/e5 ideas}) 8. c3 (8. h4 Bd6) 8... Nf6 {[%cal Gf8d6]}
9. h4 Bd6 10. Qf3 Nbd7 11. h5 Bc2 12. h6 g6 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Qa5 {[%cal
Ga5d5]}) (6. f4 e6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8d6,Gg8e7] Sometimes White tries variations
with f4 but they weaken too many light squares}) (6. Bc4 e6 7. N1e2 Bd6 8. h4 (
8. Nf4 Nf6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd8c7] Black is ready to play Qc7 to challenge the
Nf4 and look for an eventually Nbd7 w/e5}) 8... h6 9. Nf4 Bxf4 10. Bxf4 Nf6 {
White's king will be under pressure on either side of the board since we kept
the Bg6 alive}) (6. Nf3 e6 7. Bd3 {Solid for White and Black has no fears} Nf6
8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) (6. N1e2 e6 {See Nh3}) 6... h6 7.
Nh3 Nf6 {When White doesn't play h4 we delay Nf6 but when h4 and h6 is
included Nf6 is fine} 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4 e6 10. O-O Bd6 11. Re1 (11. Nxe6 $5 {
Famous sacrifice from the Tal Botvinnik Match but Black can defend} fxe6 12.
Bxe6 Nbd7 13. Re1 Qc7 $17 {There is no good discovered check}) 11... O-O 12. c3
Re8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd8c7,Ge6e5] Nd7/Qc7 are common followups and the e5 break is
on the agenda} *

