1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Ng3 {The knight is
hopping around too much so we should seek the intiative with} h5 6. h4 c5) 5...
exf6 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gb8d7,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]
Here we can play our usual setup of Be6-nd7-f8-g6 and look to sacrifice on
with Bxh3 if white plays h3 or else complete development with Rd8 and look for
kingside intiative with pawn advances (f5, g5, h5)}) (6. Bc4 $5 Bd6 7. Qe2+ {
White tries to get the queens off} Qe7 (7... Be7 {is playable but requires
precise development to avoid being tied up}) 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. Ne2 Bf5 {[%cal
Gb8d7,Gh8e8] There still a lot of pieces on the board so the doubled pawns are
not a huge liability. Developing quickly and actively gives Black a fair game}
(9... Be6 {is ok too})) 6... Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 {The main setup for White
as defending h7 is tricky} Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 $1 {Avoiding a potential hook as g6
would create but also hoping to use the h pawn to attack} (9... g6 {is risky
after} 10. h4) (9... h6 {is more passive than h5 but playable}) (9... f5 $5 {
sacrifices a pawn in order to keep White's king in the center after} 10. Bxf5
Bxf5 11. Qxf5 Nd7 {[%cal Ge8e1]} 12. Be3 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gb6c4]}) 10. Be3 (10.
O-O h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h3]} 11. h3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gd6c7,Gd8d6] Aiming to
complete development with nf8 and later Bd7/Be6. An important idea is Bc7 to
play Qd6. g7-g5 is a key idea to attack or take control of the f4 square})
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O {Aggressive but Black gets a good attack here while the
kingside structure is very robust} Nf8 12. Kb1 (12. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4] A logical
idea to start an attack. An important idea to stop White's attack is:} Be6 13.
g4 Bd5 14. Rhg1 h4 15. g5 Bh2 $1) 12... Be6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5]} 13. c4 {
[%cal Rb7b5]} (13. Nf4 $6 Bxf4 14. Bxf4 b5 $15 {[%cal Ge6a2,Ga7a4]}) 13... Rc8
{[%cal Gb7b5,Rc8c2]} 14. Nc3 (14. h3 b5 15. c5 Bb8 16. g4 h4 $13) 14... Bb4
$132 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gb7b5]} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Classical Caro: Capablanca"]
[Black "7..Nd7 Old Main Line"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B19"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "148"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 (3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6
6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 {This position used to
be considered the biggest battleground in all of Caro-Kann. In recent years
Black has come up with other ideas to combat the Classical (see next chapters)
and White in turn has explored other lines such as the Advance, Exchange, and
Two Knights more carefully. Still, this is an important theoretical section.}
11. Bd2 {[%cal Gd8d5,Rd2a5] The more modest bishop development is well
established as the main line. The point is to prevent Qa5+ and prepare 0-0-0} (
11. Bf4 {This move was very popular around a decade ago but not after Black
refined the aggressive approach of short castling.} Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 $1 {
Luring White into weakening the queenside with pawn moves.} 13. c3 {Although
this line has been seen thousands of times it is not really tried anymore as
Black has 54% score in over 2000 databased games.} (13. a3 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Ngf6
{[%csl Ga5] The Qa5 is very well placed as we control the queenside and
kingside (center too!). Plus a3 is a weakness of White's king position} 15.
O-O-O O-O 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Kb1 Rfd8 18. Qe2 c5 {1/2-1/2 (24) Chabris,C (2275)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2488)/NYS Championship 2015} (18... b5 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Ga7a5]})
) (13. Ne4 $5 {I've played this way before with moderate success. At first
Black had some trouble dealing with this move but once the shocking solution
was found all he could do is hope this line appears on the board!} Ngf6 $1 14.
Nd6+ Ke7 {It turns out White can't do anything about the lost castling rights!}
15. Nc4 (15. Nxb7 {This looks aggressive but Black regains the pawn and will
enjoy the open files} Bxd2+ 16. Nxd2 Qb4 17. Qb3 Qxd4 18. O-O-O Rab8 19. Qa3+
c5 20. Na5 Rhc8 21. f3 (21. Ndc4 {This position has been seen in corr. chess
without Black experiencing any trouble, although the position is relatively
sharp.} Qxf2 22. Rdf1 Qe2 23. Qg3 Kf8 24. Nd6 Qa6 25. Nxc8 Rxc8 $44) 21... Qb4
