(27) Predojevic,B (2626)-Saric,I (2692) Germany 2018  Summary: 8. Ne5 can lead
to some very critical lines as White seeks to actively punish us for
neglecting to play Nd7. Our focus here has been on the modern Be7 to attack h4.
If h5 then we castle and break with c5 while Nh5!? is a legitimate and
interesting piece sacrifice that leads to a dynamically even game. In the main
line we sacrifice our whole kingside in order to gain light square control I
have attached analysis and game fragments that are good examples of how Black
equalizes or even overtakes White. While some move orders are definitely
subtle and not easy to track, I think knowing some keys such as Qd5/Rxg2/Ke7!
combined with playing through the excerpts will be sufficient to play these
lines with confidence} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Classical Caro: Capablanca"]
[Black "All Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B18"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "98"]
[EventDate "2012.12.01"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCategory "21"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

{This section deals with White's sidelines in the Capablanca Variation. This
was a tricky section because several of these variations are quite respectable
and interesting, yet are very rarely played (judging from my games and my
students' games). Therefore we have a dilemma: on one hand the lines are good
enough to require study but on the other hand we don't want to burn too much
time studying a line we may only see once every few years. I've made this file
pretty comprehensive but I must stress most of it is not necessary at all to
memorize! I will of course provide the key points that will be sufficient to
remember for the games} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 (5.
Nc5 {Is an interesting option where White is basically looking for a quick
exit from theory. I think this move is pretty interesting! It has been used by
some very strong GMs and I've faced 5 times (including from a GM and IM). I
will keep the suggestions here simple:} b6 {This is the most popular and most
no-nonsense approach. Ignore White's flailing and just develop. Play here
tends to be quiet:} (5... e5 $5 {This is a more aggressive option looking to
spice up the play and "punish" White. It is also principled (take the
intiative while White moves the same piece over and over in the opening)} 6.
Nxb7 Qb6 7. Nc5 Bxc5 $5 {A rare but risky option. Going for piece activity at
the cost of the bishop pair and pawn structure.} 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9. c3 Nf6 10. Nf3
(10. Be3 Qe7 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Ng3 Rd8 13. Qc1 Bg6 14. Bc4 Nbd7 15. O-O Nb6 {
1/2-1/2 (54) Ivanchuk,V (2738)-Navara,D (2737) Prague 2017}) 10... O-O 11. Be3
Qe7 12. Bc4 Nbd7 13. O-O Rfd8 14. Qe2 h6 15. Rad1 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4] As
mentioned in this line we have a shattered queenside and White has the two
bishops, but in turn we control the center with our pawn majority and enjoy
active play. In this GM battle White was unable to cope with Black's
intiative! 0-1 (24) Godena,M (2519)-Brunello,S (2557)/Rome ITA 2016/}) 6. Nb3
e6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. g3 $1 {[%cal Gf1g2,Rg2a8]} Ne7 $5 9. Bg2 h6 10. O-O Nd7 {
1/2-1/2 (24) Kokarev,D (2624)-Riazantsev,A (2678)/Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2014/})
5... Bg6 6. Nf3 (6. h4 h6 7. Nh3 {This is a very respectable variation for
White but is not very popular. Actually it is a bit tricky to deal with the
"Nf4 setups" for White since he can reach them in many different orders: via
e2 or h3, with h4 or without, and with Bc4 or without!} (7. Nf3 Nd7 8. Bd3 Bxd3
9. Qxd3 e6 10. Bd2 {White can try to play the Capablanca Variation with the
pawn on h4. On one hand the pawn isn't as much of a target but on the other
hand it also looks a little out of place. White does not have any great
benefit from playing this way. I would like to include a win of mine where I
showcased the drawback of leaving the pawn on h4 in a clever way:} Ngf6 11.
O-O-O Be7 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qe2 Qd5 15. c4 Qe4 {Standard} 16. Rhe1
Qxe2 17. Rxe2 Rc8 18. Bc3 O-O 19. b3 (19. d5 $2 cxd5 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Rxd5
Rxc3+ 22. bxc3 Ba3+ 23. Kc2 exd5) 19... Rfd8 20. Ne5 {A standard Caro Endgame.
We should know that White has a "hidden" weakness on d4. How to target it...}
h5 $3 {I really liked this idea. Grabbing space (preventing g4) while also
carving out some light squares for our position. Specifically:} 21. Kb2 Ne8 $1
22. g3 Nd6 23. Ba5 b6 24. Bc3 Bf6 25. Re3 Nf5 26. Red3 {[%csl Rd4]} g6 27. f4
$2 {[%csl Gf5,Rg3,Gg4]} Bg7 28. b4 $2 f6 29. Nxg6 Kf7 30. g4 hxg4 31. h5 Nd6
32. Kb3 b5 33. c5 Ne4 34. Be1 Rd5 35. Re3 f5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6,Gc8,Gd5,Ge4,Ge6,
Gf5,Gf7,Gg4]} 36. Bh4 Rc7 37. h6 Kxg6 38. hxg7 Rxg7 39. a4 a6 40. axb5 axb5 41.
Re2 Rh7 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6,Gd5,Ge4,Ge6,Gf5,Gg4,Gg6,Gh7] Perfect light-square
harmony!: 0-1 (54) Moon,K (2059)-Ostrovskiy,A(2535)/State Scholastics 2014/}) (
7. Bc4 e6 {will transpose to 7. Nh3 or 6. Bc4}) (7. N1e2 e6 {will transpose
elsewhere, likely 6. Bc4}) (7. f4 {is similar to 6. f4 but a little better as
White aims to castle queenside and weakened our kingside a little more with 6.
h4} e6 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. h5 Bh7 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Ngf6 12. Bd2 Qc7 13. O-O-O c5
$1 {Opening the c and d files for our heavy pieces} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Ne4 O-O-O
16. Kb1 $2 (16. Nxc5 Nxc5 $11 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gc5e4]}) 16... Ne5 $1 17. Qe2 (17.
fxe5 Rxd3 18. cxd3 Nxe4 19. dxe4 Kb8 {0-1 (36) Brustman,A (2383) -Volzhin,A 
(2569)/Stockholm 2000/}) 17... Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Ng4 {A surprising trap as White
can't stop the fork!}) 7... e6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4 {The most aggresive approach
from White! He is trying to make sacrifice work on e6. However as long as we
develop accurately we have NOTHING TO FEAR! Be armed with the confidence that
no sac on e6 will be strong provided you safeguard your game! Otherwise our
pieces will glide to natural posts and White may regret aggressive moves like
h4.} (9. Bd3 $6 {is an interesting rare gambit. I was able to play a novelty
to refute it} Qxd4 10. Be3 Qd6 11. Nxe6 Qxe6 12. Bxh7 Rxh7 13. Qd3 g6 $1 $146 {
[%cal Gh7a7]} 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Bc5 (15. Rhe1 Nd7) 15... Qd5 16. Rhe1 Qxd3 17.
