23. Rd2 Nf4 24. Rhd1 c4 25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26. Be4 Rxd1+ 27. Kxd1 f5 28. Bc2 Nxg2
$19 {0-1 (50) Nakar,E (2435)-Riazantsev,A (2688)/Jerusalem ISR 2015/}) (6. f4 {
is aggressive and looks strong but has significant drawbacks: The Bc1 is
restricted and the light squares are weakened. It was already shown a century
ago how to exploit this!} e6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 $1 {Completely shutting out
f4-f5 and securing some light squares. Now White's position does not look bad
but watch how the Cuban genius makes f4 look completely out of place!} 9. O-O
Nd7 10. Kh1 Qc7 11. Ne5 Rd8 12. Qe2 Bxd3 13. Nxd3 O-O 14. Bd2 c5 $1 15. Ne4 Nf5
16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Ndxc5 Bxc5 18. Bc3 Bd4 19. Rad1 Bxc3 20. Nxc3 Rxd1 {[%cal
Gc7f4] The seemingly aggresive f4 has only proved to be a target and a
weakening of White's kingside! Capablanca went on to score a clean technical
win} 21. Nxd1 Rd8 $15 {0-1 (50) Marshall,F-Capablanca,J/New York 1927/HCL (50)}
) 6... Nd7 7. Bd3 {I am making this quiet variation the main line for this
section because out of all the lines we examine here I have faced this one the
most! White is content with simple development and hoping for a small space
edge in the upcoming middlegame. Meanwhile we are very solid and have no bad
pieces. Players are quick to label this line as "drawish" but do not confuse
"drawn" with "nonconfrontational!" All the pieces are on the board and either
side can try to pose problems and generate winning chances! In fact I have
recommended this system for several of my students as WHITE and they have been
successful in scoring many upset wins. The reason for their success is simple:
opponents get frustrated and go nuts because they think the game is "drawn." I
will show you how to avoid this mindset!} Ngf6 (7... e6 {is perhaps a tiny bit
more precise because the Ng8 can still go to e7. It would be rare for that
development to occur but still it is nice to keep flexibility just in case.})
8. O-O e6 9. b3 (9. Bg5 {is another possible development. Like I said, both
sides are not breaking any rules and are happy to get pieces out to nice
looking squares.} Be7 10. Re1 Qc7 $5 {Improving my queen slightly and toying
with the idea of 0-0-0. In these positions castling long is NOT recommended
unless White weakens his kingside somehow. The reason is simple: the c6 pawn
is a great hook for White's storm (b4-b5) while we have no target in return.}
11. Qe2 Bxd3 {I decide to castle short. I like to keep the tension between the
Bg6 and Bd3 for as long as possible because if my opponent exchanges on g6
then my Rh8 will be activated and I can strongly consider playing 0-0-0.
However if I am going to castle short then I will trade on d3 to avoid doubled
pawns.} 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Ne4 Rad8 14. Rad1 Rfe8 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 {
Pretty boring so far...but once again I am trying to play the best moves and
bring all my pieces out. By no means was I satisfied with a draw here.} 17. Qb3
b5 $1 {A sign of life! I am fighting for space and light squares. The game is
won by slowly accumulating small advantages and giving the opponent chances to
make mistakes:} 18. c3 Rd5 19. Re5 a6 20. Rde1 Red8 21. a4 h6 22. h3 Rb8 23.
Rxd5 cxd5 24. axb5 Rxb5 25. Qc2 Qb6 {The position has never swayed from
equality but the terrain is changing. Now I have a target on b2 and a slightly
more compact center. Again I am keeping the game going, improving my position,
and trying to cause problems.} 26. Re2 Qa5 27. Ne5 Rb7 28. Nd3 Ne4 29. f3 {
[%csl Ye3,Yf2,Yg3,Yh2]} Ng3 30. Re1 Qb5 31. Nc5 Rb6 32. b3 Nf5 33. Qe2 Qa5 34.
Qb2 $4 {A simple blunder from a strong player! Of course this won't always
happen but it can be explained: for the past 10 moves I have been constantly
poking and probing his position and now where White's guard is a bit lowered
he instantly misses a winning shot} Nxd4 35. Ra1 Qxc5 $6 (35... Nxf3+) 36. cxd4
Qb4 37. Ra3 h5 38. Qa1 h4 39. Kh1 Qd2 40. Rxa6 Rxb3 41. Ra2 Qb4 42. Ra8+ Kh7
43. Kh2 Rb1 {0-1 (43) Plotkin,V (2418)-Ostrovskiy,A (2488)/NYS Championship
2015}) 9... Be7 10. Bb2 O-O (10... Bxd3 {As outlined above I would prefer not
to double my pawns when I castle short.}) 11. Bxg6 hxg6 12. c4 a5 $1 {A
standard move for this type of structure. I gain a little bit of space and
increase the pressure on the queenside. Perhaps I will play a4 in the future.
In general pushing rook pawns down the board is a risk-free way to put some
pressure on your opponent} 13. Qc2 Qb6 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. a3 Rac8 16. Ne2 Qa6 $1
{[%cal Gb7b5] Going from a plan we've seen many times in the main lines of the
Capablanca! At it's core the Caro is an opening with a foundation on the
light-squares and the present plan is a perfect example.} 17. Nf4 b5 18. Ng5
Nf8 19. Rac1 a4 $1 {White's queenside is under heavy pressure and structural
damage is unavoidable. The unaware would be hard pressed to imagine White can
fall into trouble so quickly in such a "safe" variation!} 20. Nf3 axb3 21. Qxb3
Rb8 22. c5 Nd5 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4,Gd5] Black has a permanent position edge due to
the d5 outpost, the backwards d4 pawn, and the bad Bb2} 23. Nxd5 Rxd5 24. Ne5
Nh7 {[%cal Gh7f6,Gf6d5]} 25. Nd3 Qb7 26. Nb4 Rd7 27. Rc2 Nf6 28. Re2 Nd5 29.
Bc1 Rbd8 30. Bb2 Nxb4 31. axb4 Bf6 32. Red2 Rd5 33. g3 $6 g5 {[%cal Gg5g4]} 34.
h3 Qd7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 35. f4 gxf4 36. gxf4 g6 37. Kh2 Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gd8h8,
Gd5h5]} 38. Qg3 Rh8 39. Kg2 Rdh5 40. Rh1 Qd5+ 41. Kg1 Qxh1+ 42. Kxh1 Rxh3+ 43.
Qh2 Rxh2+ 44. Rxh2 Rd8 45. Rd2 Ra8 46. Bc3 Ra3 47. Rd3 Rb3 48. Kg2 Kf8 49. Kf2
Rxc3 {0-1 Crump, A (2051)-Ostrovskiy, A (2387)/4 Rated Games Tonight! 2012/  
Summary: The two key lines from this file are 1. White doesn't play h4 and 2.
White goes for Nf4. The first line is not dangerous but is common and the
correct approach to tackle it is to continuously improve your position whilst
creating small chances and imbalances (such as a5 against b3). The 2nd
variation is dangerous and theoretical, but not very popular. When White plays
an early h4 remember to safeguard against e6 sacrifices and be confident in
the knowledge they don't work after normal development (Bd6, Nf6, Nd7, 0-0,
Re8). When White does not play h4 look for the chance to meet Nf4 with the
disruptive Qh4!} *

