{We begin our exploration of the Tartakower variation against the Classical
Nc3/Nd2. In the Tartakower, we endure a slight positional concession (doubled
pawns) but in return we gain free and easy development. The Tartakower has
been enjoying both a spike in popularity and results due to new analysis that
supports Black's cause. In the past there was a prevalent worry that the
doubled pawns would be a long term weakness that would sink Black's chances in
the endgame. However in the middle game, these pawns provide strong cover for
our kingside and can often even be advanced forward to create an attack.} 1. e4
c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {Transposition}) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
Nf6 5. Nxf6+ {White really has to take} ({It's hard to come up with a more
logical move for White than taking on f6. Maybe this is one:} 5. Ng3 h5 $1 {
Aiming to push h4 and maybe h3!} 6. h4 Bg4 {is sensible} (6... c5 $5 {[%cal
Gb8c6,Gc8g4] the computer's top recommendation is to strike the center})) (5.
Ng5 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gh7h6] is solid and equal for Black} (5... c5 $5 {Looks
to punish White's horse-hopping})) 5... exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Gd8c7,
Gh8e8,Ga8d8,Gb8d7]} 6. Nf3 {This move is very natural, common, yet also not
challenging. Nevertheless it remains very popular as it seems like the most
logical developing move. This setup does nothing to impede our development.
The more challenging Bc4 and C3 get their coverage in the next files} (6. Bf4 {
White has tried developing the queenside first. This has decent logic behind
it since we aim to play Bd6 and now White challenges the diagonal} Bd6 {
We want to be careful not to make too many trades but developing with tempo
makes up for it} (6... Qb6 $5 {is a good try as attacking b2 is disruptive and
thematic when the Bc1 heads out early. According to the computer White's best
defense (otherwise he will need to really contort himself) is to play} 7. Qe2+
Be6 8. c3 {but of course Black is doing fine after the normal Nd7 or slightly
fancy Na6}) 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. c3 O-O 9. Bd3 Re8+ {As usual in the Tartakower we
have seamless development.} 10. Ne2 Bg4 $5 {Not manadatory but the 2600+ GM
looks to create imbalances to increase his winning chances} 11. f3 Be6 12. Qc2
g6 {Black can continue with Nd7 and either Re7-Re8 or Rad8. After mobilization
pawn thrusts such as h5/f5/c5 should be considered/prepared} 13. O-O Nd7 {
1/2-1/2 (45) Drazic,S (2370)-Bluebaum,M (2616) Skopje 2019}) (6. Be3 Qb6 $5 {
Similar to 6. Bf4 above this annoying jab makes White's coordination tricky} (
6... Bd6 {is normal and will probably transpose to some similar positions we
are going to analyze elsewhere}) 7. Qc1 Be6 (7... c5 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8f5]
similar to the game quoted. This computer suggested novelty is aiming for
maximum confrontation before White coordinates}) 8. Bd3 c5 $5 9. Ne2 Nc6 10.
dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. O-O O-O 13. Nf4 Bf5 14. a3 a5 (14... Nd4 $15) 15.
Re1 Rac8 (15... Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Qd5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gc6d4]}) 16. c3 Bxd3 17.
Nxd3 Qf5 18. Qe3 g6 19. Qg3 Rcd8 20. Re3 Rfe8 21. Rf3 Qg5 (21... Qb5 $17) 22.
b4 Qd2 $19 {0-1 (31) Agrest,I (2235)-Hoang,T (2269) Tromsoe 2014}) 6... Bd6 {
White has different move orders and development schemes here and I don't think
there is a particular point memorizing all of them. Furthermore our basic plan
of development remains pretty consistent: Be6/Bg4, 0-0, Re8, Nd7->f8->g6. With
our bishops aiming at the Kingside we can often start some active play,
notably through a Bxh3 sacrifice. I have attached some exemplary games from
Black that showcase thematic motifs} 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 (8... Bg4 {
I usually prefer to put the bishop on e6 but this move active looking pinning
developer is definitely possible.} 9. c3 Re8 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bc2 Na6 $5 {
The knight commonly routes to Nd7-f8 but Na6-Nc7-Nd5/Ne6 is also a useful trek}
12. Qd3 Bg6 13. Qd1 {White is not showing a lot of ambition here. Likely as
the lower rated player he did not mind a repetition and really wanted to break
the h5-d1 pin} Nc7 14. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Gf6,Gf7,Gg6,Gg7][%cal Gg6g5,Gf6f5] The
"box" formation is quite strong for Black as the pawns provide impeccable
protection while having strong push potential} 15. Nd2 Ne6 16. Nc4 Bc7 17. Qb3
Qd7 (17... b5 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge6g5,Gd8d6]}) 18. Bd2 b5 19. Ne3 Nf4 20.
Rfe1 Re4 (20... Nxh3+ $1 {is not a forced win but the computer sees Black's
compensation as overwhelming} 21. gxh3 Qxh3 22. Nf1 Qg4+ 23. Kh1 Re4 $19 {
[%cal Ga8e8,Ge4h4,Gf6f5]}) 21. Nc2 Nxh3+ 22. Kf1 Qf5 23. f3 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Qd3+
25. Re2 Ng1 {0-1 (25) Sarakauskas,G (2384)-Howell,D (2679) Solihull 2018}) 9.
h3 {Both sides are developing normally and Black is putting his pieces on our
designated squares.} Nd7 10. Be3 Nf8 11. c4 Be6 12. Rc1 {So far everything is
standard....but Black comes up with an aggressive (and strong!) idea!} Qd7 $1 {
There wasn't much for the queen to attack on the b8-h2 diagonal (with Qc7) so
Black takes aim at a REAL target: h3!} 13. Qc2 Bxh3 $1 14. gxh3 Qxh3 15. Qd1 {
Black has blown White's king cover and now just needs to bring pieces into the
attack.} f5 {[%cal Ge8e6,Ge6g6]} (15... Ng6 {[%cal Gg6h4]} 16. Bxg6 hxg6 {
[%cal Ge8e4,Ge4g4]}) 16. Re1 Re6 17. Ng5 Rg6 {0-1 (17) Zsigmond,K (2117)-Kral,
P (2221)/Hungary 2007/ A surprising finish! This idea is definitely not rare,
keep it in mind!}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. c4 (9. c3 Nd7 10. Re1 Nf8 11. Be3 Ng6
12. Qc2 Qc7 13. h3 Be6 {The Chinese Super-GM Li Chao has played this structure
twice and displayed a model performance} 14. c4 a5 (14... Rad8 {is a normal
completion of our development}) 15. a3 Qd7 {[%cal Ge6h3]} 16. Bf1 Bf5 17. Qc3
a4 18. Rad1 Bc7 $5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gd6h2]} 19. Qc1 Qd6 20. c5 {A positionally
risky move. White was feeling the pressure building against his kingside and
hurries to remove the dangerous Q+B battery. However if he doesn't act quickly
then the d5 square will be a powerful base of operations for Black's pieces}
Qd8 21. d5 $1 {Continuing with energy before Ne7-d5 arrives (or Be6/Be4)} cxd5
22. Nd4 $6 (22. Bb5 $44) 22... Bd7 23. Nb5 Bc6 24. Nxc7 Qxc7 25. Qc3 Nh4 26.
Bc1 Re6 27. Rxe6 fxe6 28. Qb4 Ng6 {0-1 (38) Cawdery,D (2434)-Li,C (2720)
Fufeng 2017}) (9. Re1 Nd7 10. Bf1 Rxe1 11. Nxe1 Nf8 12. Nd3 Bf5 {Not the usual
square (e6) but why not?} 13. Be3 Qd7 14. Qd2 h5 $5 {Grabbing some space and
hinting at later aggressive possibilities (h4-h3)} 15. Bf4 Be7 (15... Ne6 16.
Bxd6 Qxd6 17. c3 c5 {Trying to wrest the intiative away. In general c6-c5 is
in really in Black's interest unless it gives active piece play}) 16. Re1 Ne6
17. c3 Rd8 18. Rd1 h4 19. Be3 Qc7 20. Qe2 g5 $5 {I don't want to give the
impression that such a plan is always best or even mandatory but when it
suceeds it is a thing of beauty. Of course you cannot blindly pawn storm from
your king and need to make sure your pieces are active enough to support the
advance/cover the weaknesses} 21. Nc5 Ng7 22. h3 Bg6 23. Re1 Re8 24. Qd2 b6 25.
Nd3 Bd6 26. Be2 Be4 27. Qd1 Qe7 28. Bf3 f5 29. Ne5 Bxe5 30. dxe5 Bxf3 31. Qxf3
f4 32. Bc1 Qc5 33. Qe4 f6 34. Rd1 Rxe5 35. Rd8+ Kf7 36. Qh7 Re1+ 37. Kh2 Qxf2
38. Rd7+ Ke8 {0-1 (38) Wu,X (2203)-Li,C (2698) Daqing 2019}) 9... Nd7 10. Bd3
Nf8 11. h3 Ng6 12. Qc2 Qa5 $5 {[%cal Ga5h5] The World Champion comes up with a
new take on an old plan. While Be6-Qd7 is a standard maneuver to target the h3
pawn, Black aims for Qa5-Qh5!} (12... Be6 {[%cal Gd8d7] is "normal" and works
as well as ever} 13. Rd1 Qd7 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Ge6h3]} 14. Bf1 Bf5 15. Qc3 Rad8
{Although being outrated by 260 points Black completely dominates the game til
the finish by using thematic kingside aggression} 16. b4 Bb8 {[%csl Rg1][%cal
Gd7c7]} 17. Be3 Qc7 18. g3 h5 19. h4 Bg4 20. Bg2 f5 $1 21. Bg5 f6 22. Bd2 f4
23. Be1 Ne7 24. Qb3 fxg3 25. d5 cxd5 26. cxd5 Kh8 27. Nd4 gxf2+ 28. Bxf2 Qh2+
29. Kf1 Ng6 30. Nf3 Qd6 31. Re1 Nf4 32. Bg3 Qxd5 33. Bxf4 Qb5+ 34. Kg1 Bxf4 35.
a4 Qb6+ 36. Kh1 Qf2 {0-1 (36) Nitin,S (2427)-Pranavananda,V (2163) Chennai 2017
}) 13. c5 {Nepomniatchi rules out all possibilities of Qh5 but as we have seen
before, c4-c5 is a positionally very demanding option as the long term
weakness of d5 is troublesome.} Bb8 14. Bd2 Qd8 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. Bc4 Nf8 17.
Rad1 Bc7 {Optically it seems like White's moves have been more active than
Black's but this is just an illusion. Black's position is extremely robust and
Carlsen is preparing to unwind and take over the central outpost.} 18. Qb3 Bxc4
19. Qxc4 Qd7 20. b4 {Nepomniatchi logically begins some kind of active play
before Carlsen consolidates. However the queenside expansion doesn't really
have any targets} Ng6 21. a4 Ne7 22. b5 Nd5 23. bxc6 bxc6 24. Qa6 g5 $1 {
If you have studied the games in this chapter carefully this move should not
be a surprise. Beautifully executed as Black fully unraveled before launching
the attack. Carlsen unsurprisingly uses his intiative with pure precision} 25.
Nh2 Bxh2+ 26. Kxh2 Kg7 27. Kg1 Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Rb8 29. Qd3 Rb2 30. a5 h6 31. Bc1
Ra2 32. Bd2 Qb7 33. Re8 Qb2 34. Be1 Nf4 35. Qa6 Qxd4 36. Qc8 Ng6 37. Qxc6 Ra1
38. Qe4 Qxc5 39. Kh2 h5 40. Qe3 Qc6 41. Bc3 Ra4 42. f3 Ra2 43. Kh1 Rc2 44. Be1
Qb5 45. Bg3 h4 46. Bh2 Qb1+ 47. Bg1 Qf1 {0-1 (47) Nepomniachtchi,I (2767)
-Carlsen,M (2840) Doha 2016  Summary: We have mostly analyzed 6. Nf3 in this
file. If you master and understand Black's maneuvers in the example games then
you will be very happy to see Nf3, I know I am! Our usual setup is Bd6/Be6/0-0/
Re8/Nd7-Nf8-Ng6. Some aggressive ideas include Bxh3 and h5/g5/f5 storms that
prove our pawn mass is not a weakness but a phlanax!} *

