1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {Transposition}) 3... dxe4 4.
Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Gd8c7,Gh8e8,Ga8d8,Gb8d7]} 6.
Bc4 $5 {To be honest I did not really know about this move until I started
analyzing the Tartakower with total scrutiny. However, this is quite a
dangerous and annoying move. First off, our idea of Be6 is now tougher to
achieve. Second, White has an annoying idea to follow up with Qe2+ and either
damage our coordination or go into an endgame. Furthermore, if you choose to
meets the Two Knights caro with 3..dxe4 you can find yourself in this
variation as well.} Bd6 (6... Be7 {I was surprised to find this passive move
tried by 2600+ GM Svane but he must have been desperate to avoid Qe2+} 7. Ne2
O-O 8. O-O Na6 {Although Black later won the game, I was not a fan of his
opening setup} 9. c3 Nc7 {0-1 (54) Friedrich,N (2320) -Svane,R (2610) Zuerich
2019}) 7. Qe2+ {This is the main point of the 6. Bc4 move order. Otherwise
let's us complete development sensibly} (7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Bg4 $11) (7. Ne2 O-O
8. O-O Qc7 9. h3 Nd7 10. a4 Rd8 11. c3 Nf8 12. Be3 Ng6 13. Qc2 Bd7 14. Rfe1 Re8
15. Kh1 Re7 16. Ng1 Rae8 {0-1 (55) Zierk,S (2510)-Zhao,J (2610) chess.com INT
2019}) 7... Qe7 {Although the doubled pawns could be an issue in the endgame
there are still many pieces left on the board after the queen exchange.} (7...
Be7 {is obviously a concession but seeks to keep Queens on the board. It looks
funny but several strong GMs have successfully tried it.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Bd6
{White annoyingly prevents many of our usual moves here such as Be6 or Re8 or
even Bg4} (9... Bg4 $6 {is surprisingly a mistake. An old classic game showed
how a rapid destruction of Black's kingside} 10. Re1 Bd6 11. Qe4 Bh5 12. Nh4 $1
Nd7 13. Qf5 Nb6 14. Qxh5 Nxc4 15. Bh6 $3 Qd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nf5+ Kh8 18. Re4
Bxh2+ 19. Kh1 {1-0 (19) Ragozin, V-Boleslavsky,I Sverdlovsk 1942}) 10. c3 (10.
Re1 Na6 $5 {0-1 (53) Turner,M (2522) -Howell,D (2693) England 2019} (10... Nd7
$2 11. Bd3 $1 {Makes it very hard to move anything} Nb6 12. c4 $16) 11. h3 (11.
Nh4 Nc7 12. Qh5 Be6 13. Bd3 g6 14. Qf3 f5 15. g3 Be7 {0-1 (26) Nielsen,A (2260)
-Andersen,A (2256) Norway 2019}) 11... Nc7 12. Bd2 a5 13. a4 Nd5 14. c3 Be6 15.
Bd3 Re8 {Black successfully solved all development issues and has an equal
share of the chances: 1/2-1/2 (32) Adams,M (2703)-Howell,D (2696) London 2018})
10... Na6 $5 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Nd2 Nc7 13. Bd3 g6 14. Ne4 Bf8 15. Bd2 f5 16. Ng3
Nd5 17. Rfe1 Be6 18. Nf1 Bd6 19. h3 Nf4 20. Bxf4 Bxf4 21. Nd2 Bd5 22. Rxe8+
Qxe8 23. c4 Be6 24. Nf3 Qd7 25. Rd1 Rd8 26. Qa4 a6 27. Qb4 Bb8 28. Be2 Qc7 29.
b3 g5 30. Qd2 f6 31. g3 f4 32. g4 h5 33. Qd3 hxg4 34. Nxg5 Bc8 35. Ne4 f3 36.
Bxf3 gxf3 37. Nxf6+ Kh8 38. Kf1 Bxh3+ 39. Ke1 Qe7+ 40. Kd2 Qxf6 41. Kc1 Bf4+
42. Kb2 Rxd4 43. Qc3 Rd2+ {0-1 (43) Karjakin,S (2773) -Navara,D (2737) Saint
Louis 2017}) 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. Ne2 $1 {The key idea to prepare Bf4 and continue
exchanging pieces. Other moves are too soft} (9. Bd2 Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11.
O-O-O c5 {1/2-1/2 (21) Naroditsky,D (2616)-Wang,Y (2684) chess.com INT 2019}) (
9. Nf3 Bf5 10. c3 Re8 11. Be3 (11. O-O Kf8 12. Be3 Nd7 13. Rfe1 b5 14. Bf1 Nb6
15. b3 a5 16. Bd2 Be4 17. c4 bxc4 18. bxc4 {1/2-1/2 (18) Quesada Perez,Y (2582)
-Dragun,K (2614) Greensboro 2019}) 11... Nd7 12. Nh4 Be6 13. Bd3 Kf8 14. O-O
Nb6 15. g3 g6 16. Ng2 Nd5 17. Bd2 b5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (158) Jumabayev,R (2633)
-Harsha,B (2486) Biel 2019}) 9... Bf5 {Be6 is also fine for Black but if White
doesn't want to trade after Be6 perhaps we should develop more actively with
the computer approved Bf5} (9... Be6 10. Bd3 $1 {This is a trade White will
avoid, not fixing our pawns} (10. Bxe6 fxe6) 10... Nd7 11. Bf4 Nb6 {I can't
help but include this game as Black showed amazing creativity in winning this
endgame} (11... Rhe8 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Rhe1 Nd5 14. Bxd6+ {Was roughly equal
in a 2600+ GM battle but White should strong technique and resillience to
eventually grind out a slightly better endgame.} Kxd6 {1-0 (50) Abdusattorov,N
(2608)-Piorun,K (2643) Douglas 2019}) 12. Bxd6+ Kxd6 13. O-O a5 14. Ng3 Nd5 15.
c3 a4 16. a3 Nf4 17. Bc2 h5 18. Rfe1 Ra5 {Not necessarily objectively the best
idea but Black aims to create strange threats and attacks to confuse the
opponent. Keep an eye on his rooks!} 19. Ne4+ Kc7 20. Nc5 b6 21. Nxe6+ Nxe6 22.
Bd3 Kd6 23. Rad1 h4 24. Rd2 Rg5 25. f3 b5 26. Bb1 Rh6 27. Bc2 Rhh5 28. Bd1 Rh8
29. Bc2 Rh6 30. Re3 f5 31. Re5 Rhh5 32. b3 axb3 33. Bxb3 h3 34. Bxe6 fxe6 35.
a4 bxa4 36. Ra5 f4 37. Rxa4 Rg6 38. Kf1 Rg3 $1 39. c4 hxg2+ 40. Rxg2 Rxf3+ 41.
Ke2 Rb3 42. Ra7 f3+ {0-1 (42) Van Malder,D (2178)-Maerevoet,S (2321) Borne 2019
}) 10. c3 (10. Bb3 a5) 10... Re8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7f8]} 11. Bf4 Bxf4 12. Nxf4
Kf8+ 13. Kd2 c5 $1 {Striving for counterplay before White finishes developing
and can start squeezing the better structure. This move was played twice by
~2400s and seems to give Black adequate intiative} 14. Nd5 (14. dxc5 Nc6 {
[%cal Ga8d8,Gc6e5]} 15. Rae1 Ne5 16. Bb5 Rec8 17. c6 bxc6 18. Be2 c5 $146 {
[%cal Gc5c4,Ga8b8]} (18... Rcb8 {1/2-1/2 (36) Tashkhodzhaev,A (2123)-Ni,S 
(2409) Abu Dhabi 2019})) 14... Be6 15. b3 Na6 16. Bxa6 (16. Ne3 cxd4 17. cxd4
Nc7) 16... Bxd5 17. Bb5 Red8 18. f3 a6 19. Be2 cxd4 20. cxd4 Bc6 21. Ke3 Re8+ (
21... Rd6 22. Rhd1 Re8+ 23. Kf2 Red8 24. Ke3 f5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg7g5,
Gf5f4]}) 22. Kf2 Rad8 23. Rhd1 Rd6 24. Rac1 Red8 25. Ke3 Re8+ 26. Kf2 Red8 27.
Ke3 Re8+ 28. Kf2 Red8 29. Ke3 {½-½ (29) Spasov,V (2492)-Salimova,N (2378)
Sofia 2020  Summary: 6. Bc4 combined with Qe2+ is a dangerous try from White
that aims for a technical game based on converting the superior pawn structure.
In response we can try the "aggressive" 7.. Be7 which needs to be followed
with precise development such as Howell's Na6!? or the straightforward 7..Qe7.
The resulting endgame is a bit better for White but our active play keeps us a
moment's notice from equality, particularly after the Bf5+c5! idea.} *

