1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {Transposition}) 3... dxe4 4.
Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Gd8c7,Gh8e8,Ga8d8,Gb8d7]} 6. c3
{The most popular and critical setup for White. Still I would observe this
continuation is much rarer at the u2000 level} Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 {This is
White's whole idea. Defending h7 may lead us to making concessions} Re8+ 9. Ne2
(9. Be3 {will be similar or transpose to the main lines} h5 $5 10. O-O-O Qa5 $5
{I included this excerpt to showcase a different idea from Black} (10... Nd7 {
[%cal Gd7f8] is standard}) 11. Kb1 Be6 12. c4 Na6 13. Bd2 Nb4 14. Qb3 b5 $1 $19
{0-1 (47) Stevic,H (2589)-Cheparinov,I (2711) Zagreb 2018}) 9... h5 $1 {
Although this move was first played in 2014 (and gained prominence only in
2017) it has single handedly exploded the popularity of the Tartakower and is
now the main line here with ~400 games. In the next file we will check out
alternatives to h5 but for now we can see if White goes 0-0 then Black can use
the h-pawn with h4! Meanwhile if White castles long then we can go for a
queenside attack without giving White too many targets on the kingside} 10. Be3
{White has a major choice: Castle short or long? After Be3 we will analyize
long castle primarily while 10. 0-0 will deal with the "safer" approach} (10.
Bd2 {is less popular as the Be3 is more active than on d2. White still needs
to go short or long} Nd7 11. O-O-O (11. O-O {TR to 0-0 type games}) 11... Nf8 {
We will see very similar positions except the Bd2 will be on e3. I will attach
an interesting excerpt:} 12. h3 Ng6 (12... Be6 {is normal and good}) 13. Ng3
Nf4 14. Bxf4 Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 h4 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Qd5 18. f3 Bg3 19. Bh7+ Kf8
20. Be4 Qd6 21. c4 Rad8 22. c5 Qe6 23. Bf5 Qe3 24. Qc3 Qf4 25. Bc2 Bf2 26. Qb3
Bxd4 {0-1 (58) Andriasian,Z (2585)-Vidit,S (2718) chess.com INT 2018}) 10...
Nd7 11. O-O-O {White castles long to try to take advantage of the h5 thrust,
but as I showed in the DVD black can get strong queenside counterplay as well:}
(11. O-O {TR 10. 0-0}) (11. Ng3 {2nd most popular move and an interesting
wrinkle} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gh5h4] very precise to take advantage of White's
king caught in the center for an extra move} (11... h4 12. Nf5 Nb6 {[%cal
Gb6d5] is a novelty suggested by the computer}) 12. Nxh5 Nd5 13. O-O Bg4 14.
Ng3 Bxg3 15. hxg3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rxe3 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Bjerre,J (2368)-Thybo,J
(2479) Aarhus 2018}) 11... Nf8 {Our typical knight maneuver except in this
case it's primarily defensive. We are ready to complete development with Be6
and attack with b5+a5. White will often try a kingside attack with moves like
h3-g4. Our doubled pawns are very robust in taking away squares and
penetrations from the opponent} 12. Kb1 {Typical prophylactic to get the King
safer while defending a2} (12. Ng3 g6 (12... Be6 $5 13. Nxh5 $6 Qa5) 13. Rhe1 (
13. Ne4 Be7 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gc8e6,Ge7f6]}) 13... Be6 14. Kb1 f5 15. Bc1 Bd5 16. f3
Rxe1 17. Rxe1 Qh4 18. Qf2 b5 {Black has completely taken over the light
squares and the board in: 0-1 (35) Papakonstantinou,D (2308)-Fridman,D (2633)
Skopje 2018}) (12. h3 Be6 (12... h4 {may be ok here too}) 13. g4 h4 (13... Bd5
14. Rhg1 h4 {[%cal Gd5f3,Gd6h2] We see a very similar position with the
inclusion of Kb1 in the main line}) 14. Kb1 (14. c4 Rc8 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 14...
b5 15. Rhg1 a5 (15... Bd5 {[%cal Gd6h2]}) 16. g5 a4 17. gxf6 Qxf6 18. Bg5 Qf3
$13 {1/2-1/2 (61) Smirnov,A (2567)-Xiong,J (2679) chess.com INT 2019}) (12. c4
Be6 13. Nc3 (13. Kb1 {TR 12. Kb1}) 13... Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gb7b5] As played by
leading Caro expert GM V. Artemiev. Black aims to force through b5} (13... b5
$5 $146 14. cxb5 cxb5 $44 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b1,Gb8c8,Gc8c1]}) 14. Ne4 Qa5 (14...
b5) 15. a3 Be7 16. Rhe1 b5 $132 (16... f5 {1/2-1/2 (55) Savchenko,B (2562)
-Artemiev,V (2706) Sochi 2018})) 12... Be6 13. c4 {White's most popular option
in the 50+ games reached, showing a concern for b7-b5} (13. Nf4 $2 Bxf4 14.
Bxf4 b5 $1 {Securing the light squares gives Black a surprisingly strong attack
} 15. Be4 Bd5 (15... Qd7 16. h3 Ng6 17. Bc1 h4 18. Rhe1 a5 {Also led to a
model win:} 19. Ka1 Ne7 20. g3 hxg3 21. Rg1 Bf5 22. Rxg3 Bxe4 23. Qxe4 Nf5 24.
Qg4 Qd5 25. Rf3 g6 26. Rg1 Kf8 27. Rf4 Re6 28. h4 Ng7 29. Rf3 Rae8 30. Re3 Qh5
31. Qf4 Nf5 32. Rxe6 Rxe6 33. Rh1 Kg7 34. Be3 Ne7 35. Rg1 Nd5 36. Qg3 Re4 37.
Rh1 a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5,Gc6,Gd5]} 38. a3 f5 39. Bg5 f4 40. Qh3 f6 41. Qd7+ Ne7
42. Bxf4 Qf3 43. Rg1 Qxf4 44. h5 Qxf2 45. Rxg6+ Kf7 46. Ka2 Re2 {0-1 (46) Sinz,
B (2377)-Kvetny,M (2421) Illertissen 2018}) 16. Rhe1 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Ne6 18. Rde1
a5 19. Bc1 a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb5,Gc6]} 20. f4 Qd5 $17 {This was the original game
that showed the chess world the power of 9..h5! Black went on to convert the
light square bind and surperior minor piece advantage in 0-1 (52) Abrahamyan,T
(2364)-Krush,I (2444)/Saint Louis USA 2017/}) (13. h3 Bd5 (13... b5 14. g4 h4
15. Rhg1 Bd5 {[%cal Gd6h2]}) 14. Rhg1 (14. Rdg1 b5 15. Nf4 Bxf4 {It is usually
better to keep the light square bishop than the dark square one in the
structure} 16. Bxf4 Ne6 17. Be3 Qd6 18. f3 Re7 19. Re1 Rae8 20. Re2 a5 21. Rhe1
a4 $15 {1/2-1/2 (26) Khanin,S (2477)-Oparin,G (2584) Sochi 2018}) 14... b5 15.
g4 h4 {Keeping the situation locked up} 16. g5 Bh2 $1 17. Rg4 Bf3 18. Rxh4 fxg5
19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Be4+ gxh4 21. Bxf3 Qf6 $17 {1/2-1/2 (71) Gutenev,A (2456)
-Cheparinov,I (2709) St Petersburg 2018}) 13... Rc8 {[%cal Rc8c1,Gb7b5]} 14.
Nc3 (14. h3 b5 (14... h4 $5 15. Rdg1 b5 16. c5 Bb8 $15 {1/2-1/2 (45) Saric,I 
(2669)-Howell,D (2676) Riadh 2017}) 15. c5 (15. g4 bxc4 {Black jumps at the
opportunity to open more lines} 16. Bxc4 h4 {0-1 (56) Pikula,D (2471)-Sedlak,N
(2608) Jahorina 2018}) 15... Bb8 16. g4 h4 17. Rhg1 Bh2 $146 (17... b4 $146 {
[%cal Ga7a5,Re2c3,Ga5a4,Gd8d5] leads to an attacking race}) 18. Rh1 Bb8 19.
Rhe1 (19. Rhg1 Bh2 $11) 19... Ng6 (19... Qd7) (19... b4)) 14... Bb4 $5 {
We saw this idea earlier in a game by Artemiev, we want to take on c3 and push
b5} (14... Ng6 15. Ne4 b5 16. Nc5 Bxc4 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. Qxc4 Ne7 19. Bd2 Bxc5
20. dxc5 Qd7 21. f3 Nd5 $15 {0-1 (36) Uzumcu,A (2201)-Korpa,B (2523) Paracin
2019}) 15. a3 (15. Ne4 Be7 16. Rhe1 b5 17. c5 f5 (17... g6) 18. Nc3 b4 19. Ne2
Bg5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. g3 Rb8 22. Qa4 Qf6 23. b3 Bd5 24. Qxa7 Ne6 25. Bc2 Bf3
26. Rc1 Ra8 27. Qb7 Reb8 28. Qd7 Bxe2 29. Rxe2 Nxd4 30. Re3 Rd8 {0-1 (30)
Cumming,R (2162)-Hansen,T (2408) London 2017}) 15... Bxc3 16. Qxc3 b5 $1 {
b5 has been accomplished and now Black gets great counterplay} 17. Rhe1 bxc4
18. Bxc4 Bd5 19. g3 Ne6 20. Be2 g6 21. Ba6 Rb8 22. Bc4 Re7 23. Bc1 Reb7 24. f4
f5 25. Re5 Qd6 26. Bxd5 cxd5 27. Rde1 Rb3 28. Qa5 Rxa3 29. Qxd5 Qa6 30. Rxe6
Qd3# {0-1 (30) Litwak,A (2365)-Svane,R Playchess.com INT 2020  Summary:
White's long castling try signals aggressive intentions but Black is
definitely holding his own. The kingside formation offers ample protection and
counterattacking ideas such as Be6+b5 give us good play. There also more
subtle ideas such as Rc8 w/Bb4 vs Nc3 to facilitate b5 as well as the nifty
Bd5+Bh2 bishop combo to counter White's Rg1+g4 ideas} *

