1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {Transposition}) 3... dxe4 4.
Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8e6,Ge8g8,Gd8c7,Gh8e8,Ga8d8,Gb8d7]} 6. c3
{The most popular and critical setup for White. Still I would observe this
continuation is much rarer at the u2000 level} Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 {This is
White's whole idea. Defending h7 may lead us to making concessions} (8. Ne2 Re8
9. O-O {Has the tendancy to transpose elsewhere} (9. Qc2 {TR}) 9... Qc7 (9...
Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8g6] is standard}) (9... Na6 $5 {[%cal Ga6c7]}) 10. Ng3 g6
$5 {Restricting the Ng3} 11. c4 f5 $1 {Causing trouble and getting active!
Black wants to play f4.. . but also ideas of Nd7-Nf6 are possible.} 12. f4 $2 {
White decides that f4 is too annoying to allow by now leaves the e4 square for
Black's taking. Meanwhile the e5 square can be easily secured with f6. The
doubled pawns are helpful!} Nd7 13. Bd2 Nf6 {Black is already better! The
light squares in White's position are fragile.} 14. Qf3 Bd7 15. Kh1 Rad8 {
Black continues to enjoy the benefits of free development. All his pieces are
out and enjoy good posts. Next up: h5 or b5! Remember that the Caro is
primarily focused on light squares and it is no coincidence that we see Black
try to besiege certain light squares in different variations.} 16. Bc3 Ng4 $1 {
[%cal Ge8e3]} 17. Rae1 Rxe1 18. Bxe1 Re8 19. Bd2 h5 $1 {Cementing the Ng4,
preparing a potential h4 push.} 20. d5 {White tries to make a passed pawn...
but the pawn is completely blockaded and isn't going anywhere. Instead, Black
gains many entry-ways and diagonals for his Queen+Bishops.} cxd5 21. cxd5 Qc5
22. b4 Qd4 {Black has completely taken over the board!} 23. Ne2 Qb2 24. Bc3 Qa3
25. Bd4 Ne3 26. Nc3 Nxf1 27. Qxf1 Qxb4 28. Qf2 b6 29. Qd2 Bf8 30. a3 Qxa3 31.
h3 Bg7 32. Bxg7 Kxg7 33. d6 Qa1+ {0-1 (33) Umudova,N (2239)-Seger,R (2429)/
Pardubice 2010/}) 8... Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 $1 {Although this move was first played
in 2014 (and gained prominence only in 2017) it has single handedly exploded
the popularity of the Tartakower and is now the main line here with ~400 games.
In the next file we will check out alternatives to h5 but for now we can see
if White goes 0-0 then Black can use the h-pawn with h4! Meanwhile if White
castles long then we can go for a queenside attack without giving White too
many targets on the kingside} 10. O-O h4 $1 {Preventing Ng3 while menacing h3}
11. h3 {Logiacally preventing h3 but also creating potential hook} (11. Bf4 Na6
$5 12. h3 Nc7 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rfe1 Ne6 {[%cal Ge6g5,Gc8d7] 1/2-1/2 (49)
Handke,F (2536)-Grandelius,N (2655) Porto Carras 2018}) (11. Nf4 $5 {The third
