1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 $5 {Quickly undermining the center and trying to
get an improved French structure without the Bc8 being locked in} 4. dxc5 $1 {
Best is grabbing the pawn} (4. c3 $6 {Too complacent as we get the good French
for example:} Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5]}) (4. Nf3 {
Will transpose to either 4. c4 or 4..Nc6 variations} Bg4 (4... Nc6) (4... cxd4)
) (4. c4 $5 {A very sharp approach where I have 3 suggestions} cxd4 (4... Nc6 {
Keeps the play confined to c4 territory} 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e6 7. Nc3 {
[%cal Gf8c5,Gc5b4] A more solid approach from Black. Here Bc5 and Bb4 are both
possible followed by Nge7}) 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qa5 $5 {is less
forcing and after} (7... Bxf3 8. Nxd5 Bxd1 {Leads to a long sharped line that
has resulted in many draws}) 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qxd4 Bxf3 11. gxf3
e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Ge7d5] Both sides have weaknesses so the game remains
complex}) 4... e6 (4... Nc6 $5 {Ambitious but I am concerned about f4 here} 5.
Nf3 (5. Bb5 {The old main line gives us the bishop pair often after} e6 6. Be3
Nge7 7. c3 Bd7 {[%cal Ge7f5]}) (5. a3 $5 Nxe5 (5... e6 {TR to 4..e6}) 6. b4 g6
$5 {Leads to very messy positions but Black has good counterplay}) (5. f4 Nh6 {
[%cal Gc8g4,Gh6f5,Gg7g5] Going for quick development instead of trying to
collect the pawn. A key pawn break is the surprising g5!? to get some files
open}) 5... Bg4 {Is the type of game we want with out bishop active} 6. c3 {
[%cal Gb2b4]} (6. Bb5 Qa5+ $1 {stops b4 or c3-b4} 7. Nc3 e6 {[%csl Rc5]} 8. Be3
Nge7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Ge7f5]}) 6... e6 7. Be3 (7. b4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg7a1]
prepares to use the weakened diagonal}) 7... a6 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5] Stops bb5+
ideas and prepares to collect the pawn with an unbalanced middlegame}) 5. a3 $1
(5. Be3 {The old main line is not so scary after} Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5] The old
main line is solved by the neat pawn sac after} (5... Nd7 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gh8e7,
Ge7f5] More solid to pick up the pawn}) 6. c3 Nf5 7. Bd4 Bd7 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. a3
b6 $1 10. cxb6 Ncxd4 11. cxd4 Qxb6 $44) (5. Qg4 $5 {is always an annoying move
but we can harrass the queen with} h5 6. Qg3 h4 7. Qg4 Nh6) 5... Bxc5 6. b4 (6.
Nf3 {White can be cagey and delay a3-b4} Ne7 7. Bd3 (7. b4 Bb6 {[%cal Ge7g6,
Ge8g8,Ga7a5]}) 7... Ng6 8. O-O O-O 9. Ng5 (9. b4 Be7 {[%cal Ga7a5] gives us
good counterplay after a5. A key idea here is to delay Nc6 so we can play
Nd7-c5}) 9... Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gc7h7] A neat defensive resource based on the
awesome tactic} 10. Qh5 h6 11. Nxf7 Qxf7 12. Bxg6 Qxf2+ $1 13. Rxf2 Rxf2 $15)
6... Be7 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb8d7,Gf7f6] Preparing both a5 and f6 with counterplay
} *

