1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 Nc6 $5 {An alternative to the French style
4...e6!? This is a more ambitious setup for Black since we can still develop
the Bc8. However White has a new and rarer idea that is extremely challenging 
(5. f4!).} 5. Nf3 (5. Bb5 {Used to be the most popular option but has fallen
out of favor.} e6 6. Be3 (6. Nf3 Bxc5 {Poses no issue and we develop normally.
The Bb5 is misplaced} 7. O-O Nge7 $11) (6. Qg4 {Tries to tie down our Bf8} Bd7
(6... h5 {is a typical reaction} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qa4 Qc7 9. Be3 Nh6 10. c3 $2
Ng4 {White must have forgotten this knight isn't just aiming at f5! 0-1 (51)
Szalanczy,E (2234)-Kojima,S (2368)/Budapest HUN 2013/}) 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Nf3 h5
9. Qd4 Ne7 10. Bg5 Qc7 (10... Nf5 11. Bxd8 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Kxd8 13. b4 a5 14. c3
Bd7 {[%cal Gb7b6]} 15. O-O g5 16. a3 Bg7 17. Re1 axb4 18. cxb4 f6 $44) 11. b4
b6 $44) (6. b4 Bd7 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 {[%cal Gb7b6,Ga7a5] The
queenside is loose and Black has the 2 bishops. Often in this line we will see
that attempts for White to hold onto the extra material tend to backfire since
he makes so many concessions!} 8. Nf3 a5 9. c3 axb4 10. cxb4 b6 11. O-O bxc5
12. bxc5 Bxc5 13. Nd4 Ne7 14. Be3 Bxd4 15. Bxd4 O-O 16. Nd2 Ra4 $15 {0-1 (33)
Borge,N (2410)-Hansen,L (2530)/Espergarde 1992/}) 6... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5]} 7.
c3 (7. Nf3 $6 Nf5 8. Bd4 Nfxd4 9. Qxd4 (9. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 {regains the pawn with
a bishop pair advantage.}) 9... Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Qxb5 $1 {The resulting endgame is
great for Black:} 11. Nxb5 Nxd4 12. Nfxd4 Bxc5 13. Nb3 (13. Nc7+ $2 Kd7 14.
Nxa8 Bxd4 $19 {The Na8 will drop}) 13... Bb6 14. a4 a6 15. a5 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2
axb5 17. Ke3 {White has compensation for the pawn due to the dark square
control but Black unravels easily:} f6 18. Kd4 Ke7 19. Rhe1 Rf8 20. Kc5 fxe5
$146 (20... Bd7 $15 {0-1 (29) Beikert,G (2470)-Khenkin,I (2644)/Saarbruecken
2009/}) 21. Rxe5 Rf4 $1 $19 {The Kc5 is in grave danger with ideas of Ra6/Bd7/
Rc4 in the air}) 7... Bd7 {[%cal Gc6e5]} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 {We have the long term
advantage of the LSB which can be activated in the future via b5. We are
likely not getting back our pawn but will make sure White makes more
concessions (such as queenside weaknesses) in order to hold on} (8... Nxc6 {
is worth a try because White can go VERY wrong here:} 9. Nf3 $6 (9. f4 g5 $5 {
An undermining move typically seen in the French. The positions here are very
sharp as we sacrifice a pawn to blow up the center:} 10. fxg5 h6 $5 {[%cal
Gd8h4]} 11. Nf3 (11. gxh6 $2 {0-1 (18) Greet,A (2266)-Arkell,K (2481)/
Millfield 2000/} Qh4+ 12. g3 Qe4 13. Qf3 Nxe5 14. Qxe4 dxe4 $19) 11... Qc7 $44)
9... Qc7 $1 10. Bd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 b6 $1 {This thematic break works perfectly
as Black gets the usual queenside pressure+2 bishops for the pawn.} 12. cxb6
Qxb6 13. Qb3 Qa6 $1 {Now White can't even castle. Black played very
energetically this game to seal the deal:} 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Qc2 Rb8 16. Rb1 Bb4
17. a3 Ba4 18. Qc1 Bxc3+ 19. bxc3 O-O 20. Kd2 Qc4 21. Rb4 Rxb4 22. cxb4 Qa2+
23. Ke3 f6 24. exf6 Rxf6 25. Qc8+ Rf8 26. Qc3 e5 27. dxe5 d4+ 28. Qxd4 Bb5 29.
Re1 Qb3+ 30. Kd2 Qa2+ 31. Ke3 Qxa3+ 32. Kd2 Qa2+ 33. Ke3 Qb3+ 34. Kd2 Qa2+ 35.
Ke3 Qb3+ 36. Kd2 Rc8 37. Rc1 Qa2+ 38. Ke3 Rxc1 39. Qd8+ Kf7 40. e6+ Qxe6+ 41.
Kd2 Qc8 42. Ng5+ Kg6 43. Qd6+ Kh5 44. g4+ Qxg4 45. Kxc1 Qxg5+ 46. f4 Qg1+ 47.
Kb2 Qxh2+ 48. Ka3 Qg3+ {0-1 (48) Kaminski,M (2525)-Timoscenko,G (2530)/Yerevan
1996/}) 9. Nf3 (9. Bd4 Nf5 10. Nf3 {TR}) 9... Nf5 10. Bd4 a5 {is popular. We
are aiming for a Nxd4-b6 combo at an opportune moment.} (10... Qc7 $5 {[%cal
Gc7c5] A tricky move order that aims to improve on 10...Nxd4} 11. a4 {designed
to prevent Bb5 for good but Black pivots:} (11. O-O Bb5 12. Re1 Bxc5 {is the
idea}) (11. b4 b6 12. cxb6 axb6 13. O-O Be7 {With obvious compensation on the
queenside and the bishop pair (we can capture d4 at any moment)}) (11. Qe2 {
White tried to prevent Bb5 and add protection to e5} a5 12. O-O Be7 13. a4 O-O
{[%cal Gf8c8] Black plays slowly confident in White's elasticity. White
decides to spice things up:} 14. Na3 $5 Bxa4 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. Qxb5 {
Sacrificing the pawn back but removing our bishop pair} Rfc8 17. b4 axb4 18.
Qxb4 $6 {White wants b-file pressure} Rab8 $1 19. g4 Nh6 20. h3 Bxc5 $15 {
0-1 (51) Trjapishko,A (2471)-Rozum,I (2559)/Minsk BLR 2015/}) 11... Bd7 $1 {
[%cal Gf8c5]} 12. b4 b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14. O-O Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Rxa4 16. Nbd2 Be7
17. Rxa4 Bxa4 18. c4 dxc4 19. Nxc4 O-O 20. Nxb6 $2 Bb5 21. Ra1 Rd8 22. Qe3 Qb7
{[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd8b8] The knight is trapped!} 23. h4 Rb8 {0-1 (24) Longson,A
(2328)-Hawkins,J (2511)/Leeds ENG 2013/}) (10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qc7 12. b4 b6
13. cxb6 axb6 {is similar to 10...Qc7}) 11. O-O (11. a4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 (12. cxd4
$6 b6 $1 {works even better since white weakens the dark squares on the
queenside} 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Qc2 Be7 15. O-O O-O 16. Nc3 Rab8 17. Rfb1 Rfc8 18.
Qd3 Bb7 $5 19. Qe3 Ba6 20. Nd2 Qa7 21. b3 h6 22. Rc1 Rb4 23. Na2 $2 {Black is
exerting a lot of pressure on the center/ queenside and White unsurprisingly
caves in} Rxc1+ 24. Rxc1 Bg5 $1 25. f4 Qxd4 {The point, Qe3 is now unprotected
(no time for Nxb4)} 26. Qxd4 Rxd4 27. Nf3 Rxf4 {0-1 (36) Kosteniuk,A (2523)
-Lalic,B (2514)/Paris 2008/}) 12... Be7 {White's queenside structure is very
inflexible. We are just planning to play slowly and castle, bring the rooks to
the queenside, and either regain c5 or blast through with b6. Examples (no
memorization necessary, just some good play from Black)} 13. O-O (13. b4 axb4
14. cxb4 Bxa4 {White decides if he has to lose a pawn it rather be the rook
pawn than the advanced c5 pawn} 15. Nc3 Bd7 16. O-O O-O 17. Qe3 b6 $1 18. cxb6
Bxb4 $146 (18... Rb8 $2 {0-1 (49) Shirov,A (2702)-Bernadskiy,V (2541)/Chisinau
MDA 2014/}) 19. Na2 Ra3 20. Qd4 Ba5 21. Qb2 Rxf3 22. gxf3 Bxb6) 13... O-O 14.
Qe3 Qd7 15. b3 Rfc8 16. Nbd2 Qe8 17. h3 Bd7 18. b4 {Again we see White
choosing to give up a4 rather than c5} Bxa4 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Rfb1 Qd8 21. bxa5
$2 Rxc5 22. Rxb7 Qc8 23. Rab1 Rcxa5 24. Kh2 Ra3 $17 {A long defense for White
in the face of the powerful bishop and the weak c3 pawn. 0-1 (50) Movsesian,S 
(2628)-Zelcic,R (2514)/Neum 2005/}) (11. b4 $6 axb4 12. cxb4 b6 $1 13. O-O Ba4
14. Qd2 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 bxc5 16. bxc5 Qa5 17. Rc1 Rc8 18. Nc3 Bd7 19. Qg4 Rxc5
20. Ne2 Rxc1+ 21. Rxc1 Qxa2 22. Ng3 Qb2 23. Rd1 g6 24. Qg5 h6 25. Qf6 Rg8 26.
Qf4 Bc5 {0-1 (50) French,A (2103) -Chapman,T (2242)/Sheffield 2011/}) 11...
Nxd4 12. cxd4 (12. Qxd4 a4 $1 {Putting an end to b4 ideas} 13. Nbd2 Ra5 {
Black scores 95% here!} 14. b4 axb3 15. Nxb3 (15. axb3 {Regaining the pawn
with the bishop pair advantage} Bxc5 16. Qg4 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 $15 O-O) 15... Ra4
16. Qd3 Qc7 17. Nfd4 Qxe5 18. f4 Qc7 19. f5 e5 20. Qg3 Kd8 21. Nxc6+ bxc6 22.
f6 g6 23. Rae1 e4 24. Qf2 h5 $13 {0-1 (45) Zawadzki,S (2415)-Urban,K (2489)/
Legnica 2007}) 12... b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 {The same story: Queenside pressure+
bishops+d4 target gives Black sufficient compensation. This was tested in a GM
game:} 14. Qd2 Be7 15. Nc3 a4 16. Rfc1 O-O 17. Rc2 Rfb8 $44 {1/2-1/2 (53)
Karjakin,S (2732)-Asrian,K (2630)/Dagomys 2008/}) (5. a3 $5 {See the file on
a3 approaches}) 5... Bg4 6. c3 (6. Bb5 {is now known to be good for Black:}
Qa5+ $1 {preventing c3-b4 ideas} 7. Nc3 e6 8. Be3 (8. Bd2 $5 {Leads to
original and unbalanced positions after} Qc7 9. b4 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxe5+ 11. Qe2
Qxe2+ 12. Nxe2 (12. Kxe2 $146 g6 $13 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf8g7]}) 12... a6 13. Ba4 Be7
$13 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gg8e7] Since g6 is met by Bc3 we take a different route}) 8...
Nge7 9. a3 O-O-O (9... Qc7 $5 {also makes sense to escape the b4 tempo} 10.
Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. Bf4 Bxc5 $19 {0-1 (23) Kocheev,A (2345)-Stupak,K (2558) Police
2016}) 10. b4 Bxf3 $1 11. gxf3 (11. Qxf3 $2 Nxb4) 11... Qc7 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 {
White has the extra pawn but as is common his position is tatters to get to
this point.} 13. Bf4 (13. Bd4 a6 {[%cal Rc3b5]} 14. f4 g5 $1 {We've seen this
idea earlier in the notes above! The center is undermined} 15. fxg5 h6 $15 16.
g6 fxg6 17. O-O g5 18. Re1 Rh7 $5 {[%cal Gh7f7,Gf7f4] 0-1 (47) Nordquelle,D 
(2143) -Ostrovskiy,A (2381) Oslo 2017}) 13... a6 {[%cal Rc3b5]} 14. Bg3 g5 $1
15. O-O (15. Qd2 h5 $15 {[%cal Gf8g7] 1/2 (58)-1/2 (58) Tiglon,B (2385)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2391) Charlotte 2018}) 15... h5 16. b5 h4 17. bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qd3
Bxc5 $19 {0-1 (53) Edouard,R (2607)-Fridman,D (2653)/Plovdiv 2012/}) 6... e6 7.
Be3 (7. b4 g6 $5 {is a very rare surprising option that has been used by
several GMs. The Bg7 will be perfectly placed to exert pressure on e5 and
later the c3 pawn.} (7... a6 {A rare idea was recently used by superGM Naka} 8.
Nbd2 Nxe5 9. Qa4+ (9. Be2 Nc6) 9... Nd7 10. Ne5 Ngf6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 11. c4 a5
12. Nb3 axb4 13. Qb5 Be7 {0-1 (53) Topalov,V (2760)-Nakamura,H (2779)/London
ENG 2016/}) 8. Bb5 (8. Nbd2 Bg7 9. Qa4 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Nge7) 8... Bxf3 (8... Bg7
{[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8]}) 9. Qxf3 Bg7 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qe2 a5 12. a3 f6 $5 {
Playing purely for compensation, the queenside pressure will be aided by the
long diagonal strike} (12... Qb8 13. f4 Ne7 $44) 13. Bf4 Nh6 14. O-O Nf7 15.
Nd2 (15. exf6 Qxf6 {would make it difficult for White to develop his queenside
so he elects to just give the pawn back}) 15... fxe5 16. Bg3 O-O {Very
succesful opening as Black dominates the center} 17. Rad1 axb4 18. axb4 Ra2 19.
Qg4 Qf6 20. Nb3 h5 21. Qh4 $2 Qxh4 22. Bxh4 g5 {0-1 (34) Fedoseev,V (2670)
-Fridman,D (2620)/Liepaja LAT 2016/}) 7... a6 $1 {Now we want to capture Ne5
and meet Qa4 with Qd7.} 8. Nbd2 (8. Qb3 $5 {A sophisticated computer option
that leads to irrational positions:} Bxf3 9. Qxb7 (9. gxf3 Qc7 10. f4 Nge7 $13
{[%cal Ge7f5,Gg7g5]} (10... Nh6 11. Bh3 $16 {1-0 (32) Kryvoruchko,Y (2706)
-Zubarev,A (2588) Lvov 2014})) 9... Na5 {This position has been debated in
Corr. Chess} (9... Nge7 $5 {A computer suggested idea after:} 10. gxf3 Ra7 11.
Qb6 Qa8 $44 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gh8b8]}) 10. Qb4 d4 $1 {[%cal Gf3d5,Gd5c6]
} 11. gxf3 dxe3 12. Qa4+ Qd7 $1 13. Qxa5 Qc6 14. fxe3 Bxc5 15. Nd2 Bxe3 16.
O-O-O Ne7 $44) 8... Nxe5 9. Be2 (9. h3 Bxf3 (9... Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3
Be7 {Interesting setup:} (11... Ne7 12. Bd3 Nc6 13. O-O g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7]})
12. Bd3 Bf6 13. O-O Ne7 14. Rad1 O-O {0-1 (63) Shevchenko,K (2502)-Antipov,M 
(2580) Biel 2017}) 10. Nxf3 Nc6 {I like keeping this knight on the board as
it's well placed on c6 to confront the center} (10... Nxf3+ {TR}) 11. Be2 Nf6
12. b4 Ne4 (12... g6 $146 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) 13. Qb3 Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6]} 14. O-O
O-O 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. c4 Bf6 17. Rac1 Rad8 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Nd4 Rfe8 $11 {
All our pieces are out and active. Chances are balanced. 0-1 (59) Dragnev,V 
(2339)-Hawkins,J (2554)/Vienna AUT 2015/}) (9. Qa4+ Qd7) 9... Nc6 $1 10. Qa4 (
10. O-O Nf6) 10... Nf6 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nd7 $1 {Forcing a weakness from
White} 13. Nb3 Be7 14. O-O Bg5 15. Bxg5 Qxg5 {Black has played very
purposefully and forced the bishop pair off the board while restricting the
remaining bishop. Now c5 is tough to hold and Black has a central development}
16. c4 Qf4 17. Be2 O-O 18. Rfe1 Nde5 $15 {0-1 (26) Markgraf,A (2523)-Braun,A 
(2579)/Hamburg GER 2016/  Summary: 4...Nc6 is a more combatative option as it
allows the Bc8 to go to g4 in several lines. We examined the historically
popular options of Nf3 and Bb5, although in my view f4 and a3 are more
challenging (see next files). After 5. Bb5 we play e6-Nge7 to target the
incoming Be3. Several variations result in us being down a pawn for the bishop
pair and queenside files. 5. Nf3 allows Bg4 when White has a choice between
Bb5 (met by the key Qa5+!) and c3! Then another fork: b4 is met by the rare
g6! to get pressure on the long diagonal while the main line of 7. Be3 is
diffused with a6! to control the b5 square. After we regain the e5 pawn we
will have a complex battle of center vs queenside majorities} *

