1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 Nc6 $5 {An alternative to the French style
4...e6!? This is a more ambitious setup for Black since we can still develop
the Bc8. However White has a new and rarer idea that is extremely challenging 
(5. f4!).} 5. f4 $1 {This is a very dangerous idea from White that I had to
learn about the hard way when I played a GM.} Nh6 $5 {I focused my efforts on
making this dynamic idea work although with best play White keeps an edge} (
5... e6 6. Be3 $1 d4 (6... Nh6) 7. Bf2 Bxc5 {White doesn't mind Black
regaining the pawn because he will be able to use the light squares very
effectively for his piece development} 8. Nd2 Nge7 9. Qf3 (9. a3 $14) 9... b6
10. Bd3 Bb7 11. a3 $14 {1-0 (34) Kadric,D (2502)-Ostrovskiy,A (2391) Charlotte
2018}) 6. c3 (6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Be3 {This move has been played GMs but is
inaccurate} (7. Bd3 $146 {cuts out the Nf3 idea} f6 $5 (7... e6 {may be best
afterall} 8. Be3 d4 9. Bf2 Bxc5 10. h3 Qa5+ 11. Nbd2 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Bb4 {
With some strange maneuvers perhaps Black can fight for a draw from a tough
position} 13. Rd1 (13. Qe2 g5 $5) 13... Qxa2 14. O-O Bxd2 15. Rxd2 Nf5 16. b3
O-O 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. Rfd1 a5 $14 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 8. O-O (8. exf6 $2 exf6 9.
Be3 Qe7 10. Kf2 Bh5 11. h3 O-O-O) (8. Be3 $1 $16 {I tried to examine ideas of
g6/e6/d4 but White comes out on top}) 8... fxe5 9. fxe5 e6 10. Be3 Qa5 $11 {
[%cal Gf8c5]}) 7... Nf5 8. Bf2 g5 $1 $146 9. fxg5 e6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd8a5]}) 6...
e6 7. Be3 {I look at three approaches here: The developing method (Be7), the
positional gambit (b6) and my favorite, the wild gambit (g5!)} (7. b4 $6 {
is too loose} a5 8. b5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5]} (8... Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7]})) 7... Be7 (
7... b6 {has been tried in correspondance but Black's compensation for the
pawn is not sufficient} 8. cxb6 axb6 9. Nf3 Bc5 10. Nd4 Bd7 11. Nd2 O-O 12.
N2f3 Ng4 (12... f6 13. Bd3 Qc7 $146 (13... fxe5 {1/2 (33)-1/2 (33) Krebs,J 
(2048)-Raupach,F (2270) GER email 2013}) 14. exf6 Rxf6 15. h3 (15. O-O $2 Ng4)
15... Rxf4 16. O-O (16. Bxf4 Qxf4 17. Qd2 Qg3+ 18. Kd1 e5 $44 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20.
Bb5 Bb7) 16... Rff8) 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bd4 Ne3 15. Qd2 Nxf1 16. Kxf1 {Black
actually ended up drawing this fairly comfortably by controlling the light
squares} f6 17. g3 Be8 $1 18. Kg2 Bg6 19. exf6 gxf6 20. Rhf1 Be4 21. Kg1 Qc7
22. Qe3 Rfc8 23. Rf2 Ra4 24. h3 h6 25. a3 Kh7 26. Re1 Rg8 27. Kh2 Qg7 28. Rg1
Qc7 29. Nd2 Bxd4 30. cxd4 f5 31. g4 Qg7 32. b4 Ra7 33. Nxe4 dxe4 34. Rfg2 Qf6
35. Rc1 Rd8 36. Rd2 {1/2-1/2 (36) Geissler,W (2352)-Tazelaar,H (2373) ICCF
email 2017}) (7... g5 $5 {This is the idea we really want to make work for
Black and is likely the best option to get a messy game} 8. fxg5 Nf5 9. Bf4
Bxc5 10. Nf3 Qb6 (10... h6 $146 11. gxh6 Nxh6 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gh6g4]}) 11. Qb3
Bf2+ 12. Kd1 Qc7 13. Bd3 Ne3+ (13... Be3 14. g3 Bxf4 15. gxf4 Ne3+ 16. Kd2 Ng2
$44) 14. Bxe3 Bxe3 15. Re1 Bc5 16. Nbd2 Bd7 $44 {1/2 (72)-1/2 (72) Zawadzka,J 
(2422)-Lyell,M (2216) Arad 2019}) 8. Nf3 f6 $5 {Trying to soften up White's
center} 9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Bd3 O-O (10... Ng4) 11. O-O Ng4 12. Bd4 $2 (12. Qd2 e5
$13) 12... Bxd4+ (12... Nxd4 $2 13. cxd4 Ne3 14. Bxh7+ {1-0 (33) Saric,I (2621)
-Kucuksari,K (2301) Helsingor 2017}) 13. Nxd4 (13. cxd4 Ne3 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15.
Qe2 Nxf1 {[%cal Gd8f6]}) 13... e5 $1 {Summary: I must admit that the modern 5.
f4 poses a huge challenge to the Nc6 line and so I tried to examine multiple
setups against it. I focused on the rarer 5..Nh6 (e6 regains the pawn but
White does get some nice squares in return). Likely the best options at our
disposal are to look for g5! strikes or develop w/Be7 and counter with f6. For
now I like White's chances in this variation if he is well prepared but there
may be new developments coming!} *

