1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 $5 {This move often flows in and out of fashion
depending on the theoretical status of 3...Bf5. We want to undermine White's
center immediaetly and the position tends to have French Defense style
characteristics. Our hope is to make use of the omitted French e7-e6 to get
our Bc8 out} 4. dxc5 $1 {In the French Defense this capture is often ill
advised since White surrenders his center. However in the present case White
wants us to really work to get our pawn back! Not only does he hope to keep
the pawn, but also wishes to give it back only in the best of circumstances
where we have already made some compromises to our position.} e6 {Now the
position does have a French Defense character.} 5. Be3 {The old main line;
White holds the pawn!} (5. Qg4 {Is an option I've faced a couple of times and
is also seen in the French. White wants to disturb our development.} h5 $5 {
Harrassing the queen while potentially expanding on the kingside.} 6. Qg3 {
[%cal Rg3g7] This is most in the spirit of the opening as White prevents Bxc5.}
(6. Qf4 Bxc5 {Gives Black an easy French-type position but the pawn on h5 is a
bit strange. However it could be used to play on the kingside with future
ideas like g5 or Nh6} 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nf3 f6 $1 {This thematic French strike has
been tested recently in a GM game and is computer approved} (8... Nb4 {[%cal
Rb4d3,Gg8h6,Gh6f5] has been most popular}) 9. Qg3 (9. Bg6+ Kf8 $15 {[%cal
Gg8e7,Gd8c7]}) 9... Kf8 10. h4 $6 {maybe White wanted to prepare Bf4 without
allowing g5 (also stops h4) but now light squares are weak} (10. exf6 gxf6 $13)
10... Nh6 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh6g4] 1/2-1/2 (27) Perez Ponsa,F (2562)
-Henriquez Villagra,C (2543) Montevideo 2019}) 6... h4 7. Qg4 Nh6 8. Bxh6 (8.
Qf4 Bxc5 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. a3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gh6f7,Gg7g5] was a better version of
my kingside activity} (10... g5 {1-0 (34) Indjic,A (2618)-Ostrovskiy,A (2425)
chess.com INT 2020}) 11. exf6 Qxf6 $17) 8... Rxh6 {Forcing White to concede
the bishop to maintain his queen positioning.} 9. Nf3 f5 $1 $15) (5. Bd3 $5 {
This might be a sophisticated move since White keeps options open of playing
both a3-b4 and Qg4} Nd7 $5 {Trying to not commit our setup and take advantage
of the Bd3} 6. Nf3 Nxc5 7. O-O Ne7 8. Nc3 {The position is very French-like
now. A good example was} Nc6 9. Re1 Nxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 11. Nb5 (11. Ne2 Bd7 12.
Ned4 O-O 13. c3 Na5 14. Bf4 Rc8 15. Re2 a6 16. Rd1 Nc4 17. Bc1 b5 18. h3 a5 $11
{0-1 (49) Onoprienko,V (2370)-Guliev,S (2495) Kazan 1995}) 11... O-O 12. Bf4
Qb6 13. a3 Bd7 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bc5 16. Be3 Qc7 17. f4 f6 $1 18. exf6
Rxf6 19. g3 e5 $1 20. fxe5 Qxe5 21. c3 Rg6 22. Bf2 Qh5 23. Qe2 Bg4 24. Qe5 Rg5
25. Qc7 Bb6 26. Qe7 Rf8 27. Be3 Re5 28. Qb4 Bf3 29. Qd6 Bxd4 {0-1 (29) Zhu,J 
(2507)-Li,Y (2289) New Delhi 2019}) 5... Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5] This move looks
shocking but is actually commonplace. The simple idea is Nf5.} (5... Nd7 $5 {
I used this idea as well recently} 6. Bb5 (6. Nf3 Bxc5 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 {[%cal
Gc8d7,Gd8b6,Ga8c8] White sometimes tries for this endgame but Black has good
play on the c-file and with f6} 8. Qd4 Qb6 9. Nbd2 Ne7 10. Nb3 Nxb3 11. axb3
Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Ng6 13. Nf3 f6 14. exf6 gxf6 15. g3 e5 16. Bg2 Be6 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(28) Costa Trillo,V (2325)-Woodard,D (2404) ICCF email 2016}) 6... Ne7 7. c3 (
7. Nf3 Nf5 8. b4 Nxe3 9. fxe3 a5 10. c3 Be7 11. O-O O-O $44 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3,Rc5,
Re5][%cal Gd8c7] Has been seen in some high level correspondance games with
positive results for Black}) 7... a6 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. Nf3 Nf5 10. Bd4 Rc8 11.
Nbd2 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Rxc5 13. Nb3 Rc8 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Qg5 $15 {1-0 (48)
Grigoriants,S (2542)-Ostrovskiy,A (2425) chess.com INT 2020}) 6. c3 {The old
main line is good for Black here} (6. Nf3 $5 {This rarer option actually seems
to be quite dangerous and I saw it recommended recently in a repertoire work
for White} Nc6 (6... Nf5 7. Bg5 Qc7 8. Nc3 Bxc5 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bc1 $1 {Is not
an easy French type of position for Black}) 7. Bxh6 (7. c3 Nf5 8. Bd4 Bd7 {
TR main line}) 7... gxh6 8. Bb5 Bxc5 $13 {White does boast a better structure
but the stronger dark square bishop is no joke either}) (6. Bxh6 $6 {is not
worth it! True, White ruins our pawn structure. However we get the bishop pair
(the DSB will be very powerful!) and White loses a tempo in the opening.} gxh6
7. Nf3 Bxc5 $13) 6... Nf5 7. Bd4 Bd7 $1 {A necessary developing move to
activate Black's queenside and to deal with potential issues on the e8-a4
diagonal. It is also a high-level waiting move that sets up the "trick" shown
in the notes below.} 8. Nf3 (8. Bd3 $6 {is a very natural move but is actually
a mistake!} Nxd4 $1 {A shocking move because it completely rectifies White's
structure. However we will be quick to destroy the imposing pawn chain} 9. cxd4
b6 $1 (9... Nc6 {is more accurate at first, but transposes} 10. Nf3 b6 11. cxb6
Qxb6) 10. cxb6 Qxb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6d4] Now Black will regain the pawn back
with the two bishops and queenside intiative.} 11. Nf3 Nc6 $1 {Not rushing to
collect the flank pawn but going for the more valuble central commodity.} 12.
Nbd2 Nxd4 $17 {0-1 (35) L, Zepeda (2200)-Ostrovskiy,A (2289)/ World Open
Philadelphia 2010/}) 8... Nc6 9. a3 $1 {A very critical idea! White is getting
ready to play b4 and build a super-pawn chain. I was not very inspired by
Black's main tries in this variation and searched for a different solution.} (
9. Be2 {This is White's 2nd most popular move. I've also faced it on 3
occasions. Fortunately our usual formula gives us a great game:} Nfxd4 10. cxd4
b6 $1 11. cxb6 Qxb6 {White is in real dilemna on how to defend the b2 pawn} 12.
Qd2 (12. Nc3 $5 {worried me the most during the game. White tries to cause
some trouble while we regain our pawn and bring our queen out early} Qxb2 13.
Nb5 Qb4+ $1 (13... Bb4+ 14. Kf1 {This looks effective but concedes a draw after
} O-O 15. Rb1 Qxa2 16. Ra1 Qb2) 14. Qd2 Rb8 $1 $15 {Black will have 2 bishops
and a queenside intiative in the endgame. Plus the d4 pawn will be a target}) (
12. b3 Bb4+ 13. Kf1 {Keeps the pawn but concedes dark squares and also loses
castling rights!} O-O {[%cal Gf7f6] is an effective idea, preparing to blow up
the center for the benefit of the bishops and the detriment of the Kf1.} (13...
a5 $5 {Black can even play on the queenside and restrict/target the pawns.}))
12... Rb8 {After this simple move White's game is very difficult! He will lose
his extra pawn and have a positional disadvantage.} 13. Nc3 {I remember my
opponent thought for a long time here but could find nothing better than give
up his pawn. The opening has already been a tremendous success.} (13. b3 $2 Bb4
14. Nc3 Qa5 15. Rc1 Ne7 {[%cal Gb8c8,Rb4e1]}) 13... Qxb2 14. Qxb2 (14. Rb1 $2
Qxb1+ 15. Nxb1 Rxb1+ 16. Bd1 Bb4) 14... Rxb2 {[%cal Gf8b4] The threat of Bb4
is very difficult to deal with and also prevents White from castling short.}
15. Nd1 Rb4 $1 {The d4 pawn is sort of backwards in these structures and as
we've seen a bit in this variation, a great target. Here it just drops!} 16.
O-O Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxd4 18. Nc3 Bc5 19. Nb5 Rd2 20. Rfc1 Bb6 21. Re1 Ke7 22. a4
Rc8 23. Kf1 Rcc2 24. Na3 Ra2 25. Rxa2 Rxa2 {0-1 (25) Ashumen,F (2076)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2468)/MCC June FIDE Open 2013/}) (9. Qd2 $5 {This move is
designed to prevent our main plan of exchanging on d4. However if we recognize
White's trick, we will simply change course!} f6 $1 {Blowing up the center and
getting rid of the space advantage. We can always gain the advantage of the
bishop pair here which will be very useful on the open board} (9... Nfxd4 $2
10. cxd4 b6 11. b4 $1 {is not advisable}) 10. exf6 (10. b4 Nfxd4 11. cxd4 fxe5
12. dxe5 Qc7 13. Qb2 a6 $15 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Rg7a1]} (13... a5 {was also
successfuly in a game} 14. b5 Nd8 15. Bd3 Qxc5)) 10... gxf6 11. Be3 Qe7 $1 {
[%cal Ge7c5]} 12. b4 a5) (9. Bd3 $6 {walks right into our idea:} Nfxd4 10. cxd4
b6 $1 {I have caught a couple of players in this move order as well} 11. O-O
bxc5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $15 {0-1 (46) Paredes, A (2051)-Ostrovskiy, A (2225)/NYC
Scholastic Champs 2010/}) 9... b6 $1 {The idea that we have consistently seen
as very effective works here as well! Surprisingly, it is a very very rare
move here.} (9... g5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gh7h5,Gg5g4]}) 10. cxb6 (10. b4 $6 {
White is unable to hold the fort and has to concece to the usual structure} a5
11. cxb6 Nfxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxb6 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. b5 Qc7 15. f4 a4 $1 $17 {
I like this illustrative variation: White does everything in his power to hold
onto material but in the process has completely ruined his position. There are
pawn and square weaknesses all throughout the queenside (c3, b5, a3 are weak
and b3, c4 are juicy) while the kingside is unsafe as well after a future Bc5
and f6. The Bc5 will rule the board!}) 10... Ncxd4 11. cxd4 Qxb6 {As we have
already seen, these types of positions are promising for Black due to the
weakness of b2 and d4. The bishop pair is also a long term asset. Black has
good compensation here but to my surprise, I found a recurring idea for Black
based on Kingside play!} 12. Qd2 (12. b4 $2 {is very weakening} a5 $15) (12.
Ra2 Rc8 $1 {Developing and setting up potential tactics on c1} 13. Nc3 (13. Be2
$2 g5 $1 14. h3 Nxd4 $3 15. Nxd4 Bc5 16. Nf3 Bxf2+ 17. Kf1 Bg3) 13... h5 $1 14.
Be2 (14. h4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gf8h6]}) 14... g5 $5 {[%cal Gg5g4]}) 12... h5 $1 {
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8h6]} 13. Nc3 g6 {[%cal Gf8h6]} 14. Nd1 Rc8 15. Be2 Bh6 {The key
idea. The Bh6 has no opponent and dominates the h6-c1 diagonal. White
desperately tries to clog its route but the pin on e3 ends up costing him} 16.
Ne3 O-O 17. O-O Nxe3 18. fxe3 Qb3 $1 $17 {[%cal Gh6d2] 0-1 (35) Guskov,V (2301)
-Parrilla,A (2015)/IECG email 2006/  Summary: After 4..e6 we play a more
French like structure where we hope to regain c5 and later break with f6.
Other than the most dangerous option of a3 (next file) White can try the
disruptive Qg4 or the greedy Be3. After Qg4 we can play h5 and perhaps Nh6 to
destabilize the Queen. There are several occasions where f6/f5 is a key
resources. Meanwhile after 5. Be3 we can play the solid Nd7 or the fancy Nh6.
The older main line after Nh6 is c3-Bd4 which allows us to look for the key
b6! sacrifice.} *

