Sevian,S (2660)-Predojevic,B (2601) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 10... h5 11. Qg3 Nd4
12. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 {0-1 (40) Lobanov,S (2513)-Motylev,A (2650) Sochi 2019}) 10.
exf6 Qxf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Qh5 Nd7 13. Ra2 Qf7 {1/2-1/2 (33) Savic,M (2503)
-Sedlak,N (2583) Tuzla 2019}) 7... Ne7 {could transpose to lines already
examined}) 7. Nf3 (7. Qg4 {is annoying as usual. Here we can't play Ne7 so we
are forced to weaken the kingside} g6 8. Bd3 a5 $1 {The usual way to gain
squares and counterplay} 9. b5 Nd7 10. Nf3 h5 11. Qf4 Nh6 12. O-O Nc5 13. Nc3
b6 {Black develops comfortably. A corr game went:} 14. Nd4 Bb7 15. Nc6 Bxc6 16.
bxc6 Qc7 17. a4 Nf5 18. Ba3 Kf8 19. Rfd1 Qxc6 20. Bxf5 gxf5 {1/2-1/2 (20)
Colin,S (2437)-Ruefenacht,M (2510) ICCF email 2016}) 7... a5 (7... Nd7 {
[%cal Ga7a5,Gf7f6] is another move order that is a bit more flexible since we
may also play f6} 8. Bd3 a5 9. b5 f6 {TR}) 8. b5 Nd7 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gd7c5]} 9.
Bd3 (9. Be2 f6 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Ra2 {0-1 (95) Yoo,C (2416)-Ostrovskiy,A (2436)
Charlotte 2019} Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7c5,Gd7b6,Gb7b6,Gc8b7]}) (9. c4 {
led to some strange positions. I faced a similiar pawn push vs Chris Yoo so
maybe it's even more precise to play 7..Nd7} Qc7 10. Bf4 dxc4 11. Nbd2 c3 12.
Nc4 Nb6 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. exd6 Qd8 15. Bd3 Nf6 16. Be5 O-O 17. Bc2 Nfd5 18. Qd3
g6 19. h4 f6 20. h5 fxe5 21. hxg6 Qf6 22. Rxh7 Nf4 23. Qe4 Nxg2+ 24. Kf1 Qxf3
25. Rh8+ Kg7 26. Rh7+ Kg8 {1/2-1/2 (26) Freeman,M (2523)-Gburek,J (2503) GER
email 2016}) 9... f6 $1 10. Bb2 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f7]} 11. O-O (11. Nbd2 Nf7 12.
exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. c4 {was seen in corr. and is a typical idea here
but Black comfortably develops after} Nc5 15. Bc2 b6 16. cxd5 exd5 17. O-O a4
18. Rb1 O-O $11 {1/2-1/2 (23) Ovaskainen,J (2303)-Crielesi,G (2328) ICCF email
2018}) 11... Nf7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 (13. Nc3 Nc5 14. Re1 O-O 15. Rb1 {
0-1 (77) Abdumalik,Z (2464)-Ushenina,A (2442) Hengshui 2019} b6 $17) 13... Qxf6
$15 {Black's strategy has worked perfectly as White's queenside is weak while
e5 is on the agenda} 14. Nbd2 e5 15. Be2 e4 16. Ne1 {1-0 (51) Degraeve,J (2570)
-Hansen,T (2410) chess.com INT 2018} Nc5 $17 {Summary: a3 approaches after
dxc5 are very critical and we have devoted a whole section to them. White's
idea is to grab space and control e5 with a3-b4-Bb2. Another annoying factor
is that White may play around with move orders by using Nf3 w/a3 or Bd3 first.
Key ideas for us: Delay Nc6 to have the idea of a5-Nd7. The Bc5 can often
retreat to e7 to support both c5 and f6. Make sure to also watch out for Qg4
and know when to play for the g7 pawn sacrifice. There are additional details
such Qc7! defense vs Ng5-Qh5 assaults. Lastly, "older" setups with Nc6 are
still viable where we can continue with Nf4+f6. However a very well prepared
opponent can apply pressure and get us to defend some worse endgames.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Advance Caro"]
[Black "3...c5 White Move 4 Alts"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B12"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

{This is chapter deals with White's deviations on move 4 so it is vital to
study the lines here regardless if you play e6 or Nc6 against 4...dxc5. The
insipid 5. c3?! leads to a great French-Style game for Black while the cousins
4. Nf3 and c4 are more dangerous but have been neutralized with accurate play 
(memorization required!)} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 $5 4. c4 $5 {A violent
central confrontation! In truth this line has been analyzed to a draw but I
will also offer some lines to play for a win.} (4. c3 $6 {Very natural...
defending the center...like in the French....but that is what we want! Since
we have not played e6 we will strive to reach a position with the bishop
outside the pawn chain (preferably g4) to put pressure on the d4 pawn} Nc6 5.
Nf3 {White is being very accomodating allowing us the nice Bg4 pin, but this
is what most of my opponents did!} (5. Be3 Nh6 $5 {tempting to support Bg4/Nf5
ideas} (5... Bf5 {is thematic})) (5. a3 {I faced this idea from a GM once but
now} Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 {Gets a good setup. Here is an example of a nice maneuver:}
7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nge7 9. Be2 Nc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8b6,Gf8e7] 0-1 (53) Ivanov,R 
(2247)-Burmakin,V (2593) St Petersburg 2010}) 5... Bg4 {Black's plan here is
easy: e6, Ne7, Nf5 to pressure the d4 pawn. Usually he also plays Qb6+Be7+0-0.
The d4 pawn is a huge target and White will struggle to defend it. Very often
he just loses this pawn!} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 {I think it's a good idea to do
this first so that White can't go dxc5 himself. In the games below, the IDEAS
are MORE IMPORTANT than moves!}) 6. Be3 (6. Be2 e6 7. O-O Bxf3 $5 8. Bxf3 cxd4
9. cxd4 Qb6 10. Be3 Qxb2 {A risky decision since Black isn't developed, but he
gets away with it!} (10... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5]}) 11. Nd2 Bb4 12. Nb3 Qa3 13. Be2
a6 14. Qd3 Nge7 15. Bc1 Qa4 16. Bd1 Qb5 17. Qh3 Nf5 18. Bb2 Qb6 {0-1 (25)
Ambarcumova,K (2274)-Nesterov,J (2485) /Moscow 2009/}) (6. Nbd2 e6 7. Be2 Nge7
8. O-O Qb6 9. Nb3 cxd4 10. Nfxd4 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 {In this
example White plays decent and does not blunder any central (or b2) pawns.
That is already an achievement! I want to go over this game since it shows
Black's ideas in the resulting pawn structure: attack on the queenside!} 13.
Nb3 a5 $5 14. Be3 Qa6 15. Qxa6 Rxa6 16. f4 a4 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Bxc5 Ra5 19. Be3
Rb5 20. Rab1 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 21. b3 axb3 22. axb3 Kd7 23. b4 Nc4 {[%csl Rc3,
Gc4,Re3]} 24. Rfe1 Nxe3 {A transformation of advantages. White trades his
awesome knight to get at the weak queenside pawns and break them up with d4!}
25. Rxe3 Rc8 26. Ra1 Rc4 27. g3 d4 28. Rd1 Rd5 29. Rxd4 Rdxd4 30. cxd4 Rxd4 $17
{0-1 (46) Eynon,D (2050)-Arkell,K (2480)/ Edinburgh 1997/}) 6... e6 7. Nbd2
cxd4 8. cxd4 Nge7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be2 Nf5 {White is developing normally, but so
is Black! Now White makes a big mistake (not uncommon) and loses the whole
center!} 11. Bf4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 (12. Nxf3 Qb6 {wins d4 anyway!}) 12... Nfxd4 {
0-1 (29) Gardner,A-Rogers,I (2580)/Gold Coast 1996/}) (4. Nf3 {often
transposes somewhere} Bg4 (4... Nc6 5. dxc5 {TR to Nc6 vs dxc5}) (4... cxd4 {
Tries to avoid the transpositions to dxc5 chapters} 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. c4 (6. Nxc6
{Leads to French like structures} bxc6 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Qe2 e6 9. Nd2 c5 {[%cal
Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Ge7c6]} (9... Bc5 10. Nf3 Ne7 {0-1 (61) Ten Hertog,H (2475)
-Sandipan,C (2548) Leiden 2018})) 6... e6 {See 4.. Nc6}) 5. c4 (5. dxc5 Nc6 {
Presents a move order issue for those who want to meet 4. dxc5 with e6,
although I think this is a good line for Black}) 5... cxd4 {TR Below}) 4...
cxd4 (4... Nc6 $5 {Another popular option and I am offering it as you can
transpose to with 4..cxd4 if you wish to avoid the lines with dxc5+Nc6} 5. Nf3
cxd4 6. Nxd4 e6 7. Nc3 Bc5 (7... Bb4 {is also possible and critical line runs}
8. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8]} 9. Qa4 {White tries to provoke some kind of
concession before Black develops and castles} a5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Qxb4 axb4
12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Be3 {This endgame has been reached often in corr. chess and
Black has often held it although it is dangerous. The key here is to be as
active as possible} f6 14. f4 Bf5 15. Be2 (15. Bc5 Kd7 16. Bxb4 fxe5 17. fxe5
Nh6 18. Be2 Rhb8 19. Bc3 c5 $44 {1/2-1/2 (29) Grabove,M-Lackey,R ICCF email
2014}) 15... Kd7 16. Bc5 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nh6 18. O-O Rhe8 19. Bxb4 Rxe5 20. Bf3
Bd3 21. Rf2 Nf5 {½-½ (40) Staroske,U (2514)-Gburek,J (2503) GER email 2016
and ½-½ (38) Habermehl,T (2476)-Gburek,J (2503) GER email 2016}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6
{Again if Black can play moves like Ne7-Ng6 0-0 he will be fine so White tries
to get aggressive} 9. cxd5 (9. Qg4 $5 Ne7 10. Qxg7 Ng6 (10... Rg8 $5 11. Qxh7
Rb8 $44) 11. Be2 Bf8 12. Qf6 Be7 13. Qf3 d4 14. Ne4 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qxe5 16. O-O
O-O 17. Bd3 Rb8 18. b3 f5 19. Ng5 Qg7 20. Qh5 e5 21. f3 c5 $15 {0-1 (33)
Tokhirjonova,G (2446)-Vaibhav,S (2590) Caleta 2019}) 9... cxd5 {Positionally
desirable but allows} (9... exd5 10. Bd3 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5] is also playable})
10. b4 $5 Be7 11. a3 a5 {A high level correspondance game here went:} 12. bxa5
Qxa5 13. Bd2 Bg5 14. Rb1 Ne7 15. Bb5+ Bd7 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. f4 Bxf4 18. Rb7+
Kd8 19. Nb5 Bxd2+ 20. Qxd2 Nc6 21. Qxa5+ Nxa5 22. Rxf7 Rb8 23. a4 Rb7 24. O-O
Re8 25. Rxb7 Nxb7 26. Rc1 Na5 27. Rc5 Ke7 28. Rc7+ Kf8 29. Nd4 Nc4 30. Ra7 Nxe5
31. a5 Nd3 32. a6 Nc5 33. Nc6 e5 34. Nb4 e4 35. Kf1 Rb8 36. Nxd5 Rb1+ 37. Kf2
Rb2+ 38. Ke3 Nxa6 39. Rxa6 {1/2-1/2 (39) Velilla Velasco,F (2550)-Holroyd,K 
(2508) ICCF email 2016}) 5. Nf3 (5. Qxd4 $6 {Brings the queen out early and
allows us a simple intiative based on developing with tempi} Nc6 6. Qxd5 Bf5 7.
Nf3 e6 8. Qb5 $2 (8. Qxd8+ {is preferable but Black has a development lead
while White's queenside is riddled with weak squares. I would prefer Black}
Rxd8 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 9. a3 Nge7 {[%cal Ge7g6]}) 8... Bc2 $1 9. Nfd2 {[%cal
Gb7f3] Giving the queen an escape square compared to the line above} (9. Nc3 $2
a6 10. Qxb7 Na5 {[%csl Rb7]}) 9... Qc7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga7a6]} 10. c5 Qxe5+
11. Be2 O-O-O {0-1 (25) Tate,A (2170)-Zatonskih,A (2462)/ Gibraltar 2009/})
5... Bg4 6. cxd5 (6. Qxd4 $6 {Again bringing the queen out brings no luck as
per the note above} Bxf3 7. gxf3 Nc6 8. Qxd5 e6 (8... Qc7 $5 9. Bf4 e6 10. Qe4
O-O-O 11. Nc3 Bb4 12. Be2 Nge7 13. O-O Rd4 {0-1 (35) Saravana,K (2312)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2425) chess.com INT 2020}) 9. Qe4 (9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. f4 Nh6 {
[%csl Rc2,Re5,Rf4][%cal Gh6f5,Gf5d4,Gc6d4,Gc6b4]}) 9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11.
Nxd2 Qa5 $1 12. f4 (12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. f4 Qxa2 {0-1 (44) Hector,J (2551)
-Khenkin,I (2647)/Germany 2008/}) 12... O-O-O {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5]}) (6. Qa4+
Bd7 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 e6 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. O-O Bc5 $11 {[%cal
Gg8e7,Ge8g8]}) 6... Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qa5 $5 {7...Bxf3 is likely a forced draw 
(amazing!) but this keeps pieces on the board} (7... Bxf3 {This is an exciting
endgame variation that has been computer analyzed to a draw. Here are the
games to prove it!} 8. Nxd5 Bxd1 9. Nc7+ Kd7 10. Nxa8 Bc2 11. Bd2 (11. e6+ $6
Kxe6 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. Kd2 Bg6 14. Bb5 Kd7 15. Be5 Nf6 16. Rac1 e6 17. Nc7 Bb4+
18. Ke2 d3+ 19. Kf3 Bh5+ 20. Kg3 Ne4+ 21. Kh4 Be2 22. f3 Be7+ 23. Kh5 Nf6+ 24.
Bxf6 gxf6 25. Na6 d2 26. Rxc6 Bxb5 27. Rc7+ Kd6 28. Rd1 Bxa6 29. Rc3 e5 30.
Rxd2+ Ke6 {0-1 (30) Robson,R (2455)-Khairullin,I (2574)/Moscow 2009/}) 11...
Nc6 12. Rc1 d3 13. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gf1d3]} e6 14. Rh3 Nge7 15. Bxd3 Bxd3 16.
Rxd3+ Nd5 17. b4 b5 18. a4 bxa4 19. b5 Nxe5 20. Rc7+ Kd8 21. Rxd5+ (21. Rd4 Bd6
22. Rxa7 Bc5 23. Ba5+ Kc8 24. Rxd5 exd5 25. Nb6+ Bxb6 26. Bxb6 Re8 27. Kd1 Nc4
28. Bd4 Re4 29. Bxg7 Rxh4 30. Rxf7 Rg4 31. Bf8 a3 32. Ra7 Rxg2 $15 {1/2-1/2 
(58) Kosteniuk,A (2491)-Girya,O (2463)/Geneva SUI 2013/}) 21... exd5 22. Rxa7
Nc4 23. Nb6 Nxb6 24. Ba5 Kc8 25. Bxb6 Bb4+ 26. Kd1 a3 $1 27. Ra8+ Kb7 28. Rxh8
Bc3 $1 29. Ba5 Bf6 30. Rf8 a2 31. Rxf7+ Kb8 32. Rf8+ Kb7 33. Rf7+ Kb8 34. Rf8+
Kb7 {Basically a game between two computers, a perfect game! There are some
deviations possible along the way (I included some that show White getting in
trouble!) 1/2-1/2 (34) Najer,E (2655)-Khairullin,I (2650)/Loo RUS 2014/}) 8.
Bb5+ (8. Qxd4 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Nc6 10. Bb5 Qxb5 11. Nxb5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 e6 {White
has a ruined structure but a queenside intiative due to a lead in development.
He uses it to win a pawn:} (12... a6 $1 {[%cal Rd4b5]}) 13. Nb5 Rd8 $1 14. Nxa7
Rd5 15. f4 Bc5 16. Be3 g5 $1 17. Nb5 Bb4+ 18. Nc3 gxf4 19. Bxf4 Ne7 20. Rd1 Kd7
21. Rxd5+ exd5 22. Bd2 Bxc3 23. Bxc3 {Black is down a pawn and has a knight vs
bishop (typically good for the bishop in the endgame with pawns on all flanks..
.) but acutally is not doing bad at all! Black's piece activity and light
square control are top-notch and the Knight is actually superior since there
are so many juicy squares White can't push it out of. Knights love it when the
opponent's pawns are all scrambled!} Rg8 24. Ke2 Ke6 25. Ke3 Rg4 26. Kf3 Rh4
27. Bd2 Nc6 28. Bf4 Kf5 29. Bg3 Rd4 30. Ke3 h5 31. f3 Ra4 32. a3 h4 33. Be1 d4+
{0-1 (33) Halvax,G (2304)-Antal,G (2515)/Jenbach AUT 2013/}) 8... Nc6 9. Bxc6+
(9. Qxd4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qxb5 {TR above}) 9... bxc6 10. Qxd4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e6 {
An unbalanced game. Both sides have tattered pawns but Black's structure is a
bit better since the Ng8 can use the f5/d5 squares and the open queenside
files caused by the fractured pawns can be useful for the heavy pieces. But
first thing is first, White is ahead in development. The position is still not
fully explored in practice so I will showcase a couple of success stories for
Black.} 12. Be3 (12. Bg5 Ne7 13. O-O Nf5 14. Qe4 Rc8 15. Rfd1 Be7 16. Bxe7 Nxe7
17. b4 Qc7 18. Rac1 Qb8 19. Na4 {White is playing purposefully and
aggressively but Black always has counterchances due to the weak kingside.} O-O
20. Rd7 Ng6 21. Nc5 Rfd8 22. Rb7 Qa8 {Very peculiar. Optically White is
crushing but the threat of Rd5 is difficult to meet (attacking e5 and Rxc5!)}
23. f4 Rd5 24. Rd7 Rd8 25. Rxd5 Rxd5 26. Qf3 Qd8 {White's activity has yielded
nothing and now Black takes over. There is no rectifying the kingside pawn
structure.} 27. Nb7 Qe7 28. Na5 Nxe5 29. Qc3 Nd3 30. Nxc6 Qh4 31. Rf1 Qg4+ 32.
Kh1 Nxf2+ 33. Rxf2 Rd1+ {0-1 (33) Chigaev,M (2494)-Bernadskiy,V (2556)/Yerevan
ARM 2015/}) 12... Ne7 13. O-O-O Nd5 {This move was tested in two high level
correspondance games and held up for Black} (13... Qc7 {Preparing to install a
knight on d5 after which Black can look forward to develping with Rb8-Bb4 etc.}
14. Qc4 (14. Ne4 Nf5 15. Qc3 $14 {seems to give White an edge}) 14... Nf5 {
Having been denied the D5 square the knight heads to f5. That is OK since the
vulnerable d6 square is covered as well as the kingside (like g7)} 15. Nb5 Qb7
16. Nd4 Rb8 17. Qc2 Nxe3 $1 18. fxe3 Bc5 $1 {Black was only complicit in
trading his beautiful knight in such a way because he foresaw he could get
both minors off the board. Now White can't mount any activity on the d6/c5
outposts as his own king and pawns are in danger} 19. Rd3 Bxd4 20. exd4 O-O 21.
Rhd1 Qd7 22. Rc3 Rb4 23. Qe4 Rfb8 24. Qxc6 Qxc6 25. Rxc6 Rxb2 26. Rc8+ Rxc8+
27. Kxb2 Kf8 $11 {1/2 (48)-1/2 (48) Vallejo Pons,F (2697)-Delchev,A (2623)/
Plovdiv 2010/}) 14. Qc4 Rc8 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Qg4 Rb8 17. e6 f6 18. Kb1 Bd6 19.
Rd2 (19. Qxg7 Rxb2+ $1 20. Kxb2 Qb4+ 21. Kc2 Qc4+ $11) 19... Rb7 (19... g6 20.
Rc1 Be5 21. Rcc2 O-O 22. e7 Rfe8 23. Qd7 Kf7 24. Qxc6 d4 25. Qc4+ Kg7 26. Bxd4
Bxd4 27. Qxd4 Rxe7 28. b3 Rbb7 29. Kb2 Qf5 30. f4 Rbd7 31. Qb4 Qh5 32. Rxd7
Rxd7 33. Qe4 Qxh2 34. Qe6 Rf7 35. Qe3 Qh1 36. f5 g5 37. f4 g4 38. Qe8 Qd5 39.
Rc8 Qd4+ 40. Kc2 Qd7 41. Qg8+ Kh6 42. Kb2 Qd2+ 43. Rc2 {1/2-1/2 (43) Stoeckert,
M (2459)-Mercadal Benejam,J (2415) ICCF email 2017}) 20. Rc1 Qb5 21. f4 O-O 22.
Qe2 Qxe2 23. Rxe2 Rc7 24. f5 c5 25. h4 Rfc8 26. Kc2 h5 27. Kd3 a5 28. f4 a4 29.
Rd1 Rd8 30. Bc1 Kf8 {½-½ (30) Belka,W (2494)-Gburek,J (2503) GER email 2016 
Summary: White's deviations to dxc5 include two completely different c-pawn
moves: c3 or c4. C3 is what we want to see since we get an improved French
structure by bringing the Bc8 to hopefully g4 or f5. C4 or Nf3 w/c4 is very
sharp and requires percise knowledge. One idea is to play with nc6/cxd4 and e6
which keeps our center solid. A more thematic idea is to play the pinning Bg4
after which we have a choice: memorize a forcing sequence to get a draw with
Bxf3 or go for the more ambitious and unbalanced Qa5!?. Needless to say the
variations in this file require great strength and knowledge from White to
play correctly.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Caro"]
[Black "Main Ideas"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 {White aims for a setup with Bd3/Bf4/Nd2/
Nf3 and then a later Ne5 and kingside attack. Simple but dangerous} Nc6 5. c3
Qc7 $5 {Preventing Bf4 and disrupting White's setup} (5... Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 (6...
g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Going for a fianchetto to block the Bd3 and later play Bf5 to
gain control of the center and open the g-file}) 7. Qb3 Qd7 (7... Qc8 {
possible but passive}) 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 $1 {The b7 pawn is not a worry}
10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O (11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qa6 O-O $44 {Key ideas here are
Rb6-Rxb2 and if White is trying too hard to keep b2 and not castle then there
may be an e5 break}) 11... O-O 12. Rae1 Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Gg4h5,Gh5g6,
Gg4f5] Going for a minority attack counterplay (b5-b4). Defensive ideas
include Bh5-g6 or Bf5 to block the dangerous Bd3} (12... Bxf3 {Black often
opts for this trade to avoid the bishop being harrassed} 13. Nxf3 Rab8) (12...
Nd7 {[%csl Re5] controls e5})) (5... g6 {[%cal Gg8h6] Has the original idea of
going for Nh6-Nf5 or f6/Nf7}) 6. Ne2 {White insists on Bf4 but compromises the
setup} (6. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6,Gg8f6,Gg4h5,Gh5g6] is too easy. Next is
e6-Bd6-Nf6/Ne7 and later Bh5-bg6 with perhaps b5-b4 minority attack}) 6... Bg4
7. O-O (7. f3 {The old main line is pretty junky since f3 weakens so many dark
squares} Bd7 8. Bf4 e5 $1 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] A
comfortable IQP structure. Simplest is Nf6/0-0 and rooks to the center}) 7...
e6 (7... Nf6 8. Qe1 Bh5 {[%cal Gh5g6] Another idea to save the bishop}) 8. Qe1
$1 {A weird looking idea but White is planning either f3-Qh4 or Ng3 and the
Bg4 starts feeling weird} Be7 $5 {[%cal Re1h4] Preventing Qh4 and blocking the
g-file. The Bg4 can be saved creatively after} (8... Nf6 9. f3 Bh5 10. Qh4 Rg8
$5 (10... h6 $5 {Two computerish ideas that serve to avoid major kingside
weaknesses and perhaps even gain a counterattack})) (8... g6 {[%cal Gg4f5]}) 9.
Ng3 g6 $1 {[%cal Gg4f5]} *

