{I will now focus on my main recommendation against the Exchange Caro: an
approach involving a disruptive Qc7. This setup prevents White from developing
in his preferred manner. We will also check out the main option of Nf6} 1. e4
c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 (4. Nf3 {An early Nf3 is innocous as it allows
us an easy pin with Bg4. Nevertheless the following example transposes to Qc7
ideas seen below:} Nf6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. c3 Qc7 {[%cal Rc7f4] The queen will be
well placed her to exert kingside pressure while preventing white from
developing with Bf4 and installing a knight on e5} 7. O-O Bg4 8. Re1 e6 9. Nbd2
Bd6 10. Nf1 O-O-O $5 {I chose this adventurous option in my game and based my
play on a kingside expansion/central strike} (10... O-O {This prudent option
was likely the best. The plan here is a queenside minority attack with b5-b4}
11. Bg5 (11. Ng3 Rfe8 12. h3 $6 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e5 $1 {is an instructive example
of black's potential to play in the center.}) 11... Nd7 12. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4g3]}
Bh5 {[%cal Gh5g6]} 13. Bg3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Ng3 b5 $1 17. a3
a5 $15 {[%cal Gb5b4] See the game Bryant-Ostrovskiy below for more information
how to handle the minority attack}) 11. b4 Kb8 (11... Nh5 $5 {[%cal Gh5f4]} 12.
h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nf4 14. Bc2 g5 15. g3 Nxh3+ 16. Kg2 h5 {0-1 Knorr Jarillo,J 
(2218) -Izeta Txabarri,F (2470)/Vitoria 2003/}) 12. Bd2 e5 $1 $15 13. dxe5 Nxe5
14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Ne4 17. Red1 Be5 18. Rac1 Nxd2 19. Nxd2
Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Be5 $17 {0-1 (52) Pattard,T (2183)-Ostrovskiy,A (2408)/National
Chess Congress 2011/}) 4... Nc6 5. c3 (5. Nf3 Bg4 6. c3 Qc7 7. Bg5 e6 8. Nbd2
Bd6 9. Bh4 Nge7 $5 {[%cal Ge7f5,Rf7f6,Re6e5]} 10. Bg3 Bxg3 11. hxg3 O-O-O {
As you can see from excerpts in this file, I have often been fond of castling
long when possible!} 12. Qc2 e5 $5 {Trying to take advantage of white's
uncastled king} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 15. Kf1 Nc6 16. Nf3 Qf6 17. Rh4 h5
18. Nh2 g5 19. Nxg4 hxg4 20. Rxh8 Rxh8 21. Rd1 Qe6 22. Kg1 Qh6 $17 {[%cal
Gh6h1] 0-1 (53) Kelemen,A (2203)-Ostrovskiy,A (2448) /Parsippany 2013/}) 5...
Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gc7f4] Before continuing with our own development we prevent Bf4}
6. Ne2 {[%cal Gc1f4] White's main line as he tries to force thru Bf4 with tempo
} (6. h3 Nf6 7. Nf3 (7. Ne2 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. O-O
Bc5 12. Bf4 Ng6 13. Nd2 h6 14. Nf3 Nxf4 15. Nxf4 O-O 16. Nd3 Bb6 {1/2-1/2 (40)
Looshnikov,N (2469)-Kryakvin,D (2601) Tyumen 2014}) 7... g6 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5]
Borrowing the idea from the g6 Exchange Caro file.} 8. O-O Bf5 9. Re1 (9. Bxf5
gxf5 10. Ne1 e6 11. Nd3 Bd6) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Nbd2 Bg7 12. Nb3 O-O $11
{0-1 (68) Zvjaginsev,V (2660)-Aronian,L (2784) Berlin 2015}) (6. Nf3 Bg4 {TR})
(6. Bg5 {White tries to impede our development...} Nf6 $1 {But we proceed
without a hitch!} 7. Nd2 (7. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gh8g8]}) 7... Bg4 8.
Ngf3 e6 9. Bh4 Bd6 10. Bg3 Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g6] An idea seen from above. We
are going to completely neutralize any White play on the kingside after
trading bishops.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Re1 Rab8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 14.
a4 Qc7 15. Qb1 a6 16. Ne5 Rfe8 17. h3 Bg6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Qd3 Nxe5 20. dxe5
Nd7 21. Qd4 Rec8 22. Re3 Qb6 $1 {After the queen trade White has no kingside
attack and Black will go for a queenside pawn storm: 0-1 (40) Illescas Cordoba,
M (2590)-Anand,V (2715)/Linares 1994/}) (6. Na3 {A slightly sophisticated
continuation} a6 7. Nc2 (7. Ne2 Bg4 8. Nc2 {I faced this weird once where
White contorts to get the bishop pair} e6 9. Qd2 Bh5 10. Nf4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6
12. g3 Bd6 13. Qe2 O-O-O $11) 7... Nf6 8. h3 e6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]}) 6... Bg4
7. O-O $5 {By far the main idea nowadays} (7. h3 Bxe2 (7... Bh5 {[%cal Gh5g6]})
8. Bxe2 (8. Qxe2 $2 Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Gc7c1] I've caught several players in this
sneaky trap! This is just a free pawn} 9. Qd1 Nc6 10. O-O e6 11. Be3 Nf6 12.
Nd2 Nd7 13. Rc1 g6 14. Bb1 Bg7 15. Nf3 O-O $17 {0-1 (58) Fan,Y (2190)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2336)/Philadelphia Open 2011 (58)}) 8... e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Nd2
f5 $5 {Again going for my "trademark" long castling approach! It's a bit
needlessly risky here but I don't mind a more exciting game against a lower
rated player!} (10... Nf6) 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. Bd3 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 13. Re1 Ne4
14. c4 O-O-O 15. c5 Be7 16. Bb5 Bf6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qa4 g5 19. Bd2 Rdg8 20.
Ba5 Qb7 21. Re3 g4 22. hxg4 Rxg4 23. Rb3 Qa6 24. Qb4 Kd7 25. Qb7+ Qxb7 26.
Rxb7+ Kc8 27. Rc7+ Kb8 28. Rxc6 Rhg8 29. Ne1 Bxd4 {0-1 (42) West,J (2200)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2500) /MCC Masters 2013 (42)}) (7. Bf4 {isn't too effective now:
} Qxf4 8. Nxf4 Bxd1 9. Kxd1 Nf6 10. Bb5 e6 11. Nd2 Bd6 12. Nd3 Nd7 {[%csl Gd5,
Ge6,Gf7] Great harmony and central control in Black's camp:} 13. a4 a6 14. Bxc6
bxc6 15. b4 f6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 16. Nb3 Bc7 {[%cal Rb3a5]} 17. Ndc5 Nxc5 18. Nxc5
Kf7 19. Kc2 e5 {0-1 (41) Coraretti,B-Ostrovskiy, A/Philadelphia Open 2013 (41)}
) (7. Na3 a6 8. Nc2 e6 9. Qd2 Bh5 10. Nf4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. g3 Bd6 13. Qe2
O-O-O) (7. f3 Bd7 8. Bf4 e5 $1 9. dxe5 Nxe5 {White finally got his bishop out
to f4 but at the price of playing f3 which creates dark square weaknesses. We
have a very good IQP position where the pawn on d5 is not under any pressure
but it does control the center quite well. I think Black is doing very well
here and I've won all my games from this position} 10. O-O (10. Bc2 {[%cal
Gd1d5,Gc2b3] I've faced this move the most. Some of my examples:} Nf6 11. O-O (
11. Nd4 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Nd2 Nh5 $1 {Suddenly White's dark square problems
are very apparent.} 14. Be3 $2 (14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Rfe8 $17 {is relatively
best but gives up a key bishop}) 14... Nc4 (14... Ng4 $1 {is even better!} 15.
fxg4 Bxh2+ 16. Kf2 (16. Kh1 Ng3+) 16... Qg3+ 17. Ke2 Rae8 {[%cal Gd7g4,Ge8e3,
Gg3g2]}) 15. Nxc4 Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 dxc4 17. f4 Nxf4 18. Qf3 Ng6 {0-1 (55) Karp,J 
(2088) -Ostrovskiy,A (2402)/4 Rated Games Tonight! 2011 (55)}) 11... Bd6 12.
Nd2 O-O 13. Nb3 Nc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4b2,Gc4e3]} 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qd4 Nxb2 16. Rab1
Nc4 $17 {0-1 (23) Wong, Brandon (2034)-Ostrovskiy-A (2505)/MCC Insanity 2015/})
10... Bd6 {[%cal Gd6h2] Key to break the pin and establish more dark square
control} 11. Bc2 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge7c6,Ge7f5]} (11... Nf6 {is perfectly fine})
12. Ba4 O-O-O {I have used a setup with Ne7 and 0-0-0 quite often. The idea of
Ne7 is to keep the kingside pawns free to move such as f6-g5. However I think
playing with Nf6 and 0-0 is a better option. It could be a matter of taste as
both options are good, but objectively Nf6 and 0-0 is more risk free.} 13.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Nd2 Rhg8 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 15. b4 g5 16. Be3 Kb8 17. Nb3 Nc4 18.
Bc5 Be5 19. Qd3 Qc7 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. a4 Qc7 22. g3 h5 23. Nbd4 h4 $19 {
0-1 (54) Martinez,I (2020)-Ostrovskiy, A (2342)/K-12 Championship 2011}) 7...
e6 (7... Nf6 8. Qe1 $1 {as we see in the main line this is White's idea:
unpinning the Ne2 to play Ng3/Nf4 and chase down the Bg4} Bh5 $5 {An OTB idea
I came up with} 9. Bf4 (9. Nf4 Bg6) (9. f4 $5 {most aggressive!} e6 10. Ng3 (
10. f5 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 e5 {1/2-1/2 (50) Bachmann,A (2631)-Margvelashvili,G (2530)
chess.com INT 2019}) 10... Bd6 11. Nxh5 Nxh5 {White has grabs the bishop pair
but also is a bit soft on the light squares due to the dark squared structure}
12. g3 Nf6 13. Nd2 h5 14. Nf3 Kf8 15. Qe2 Ne7 $1 {A nice regrouping: g6-Kg7-Nf5
} 16. Bd2 g6 17. b3 Nf5 18. c4 Kg7 19. Rac1 Qd8 20. c5 Bc7 21. Be1 Ng4 22. Bc3
h4 $5 23. Nxh4 Rxh4 24. gxh4 Qxh4 $44 25. Bxf5 exf5 26. Be1 Qh8 27. Bg3 Re8 28.
Qd3 Re3 29. Qd2 Ba5 30. Qb2 Rd3 31. Be1 Rd2 {0-1 (31) Yudin,S (2507)-Tokarev,I
(2318) Kazan 2019}) 9... Qd7 10. Nd2 e6 11. Bg3 Bg6 $11 {1-0 (49) Zierk,S 
(2476) -Ostrovskiy,A (2414) Charlotte 2018}) 8. Qe1 $1 {A key position for
this variation. White wants the bishop pair and Black needs to figure out
which way to surrender the Bg4... or try to save it!} Be7 $5 {A slightly
unusual idea to prevent f3-Qh4 ideas} (8... Nf6 {This is the main line} 9. f3
Bh5 10. Qh4 h6 (10... Rg8 $5 {prepares Bg6 and avoids the h-file pin}) 11. Qh3
(11. Ng3 Bg6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Qh3 e5) 11... e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bb5+ Nc6 14.
Re1 Bc5+ 15. Nd4+ Kf8 {[%cal Gg8h7,Gf8g8]}) (8... g6 $5 {Was another one of my
ideas} 9. f3 (9. Bf4 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Gg4f5]}) (9. Ng3 Be7 {TR 8..Be7})
9... Bf5 {the point!} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Bf4 Qb6 (11... Bd6) 12. Nd2 Nge7 13. a4
Ng6 14. Kh1 a5 15. Rb1 h5 16. Bg5 Be7 17. Bxe7 Ncxe7 18. f4 Qc7 19. Nf3 f6 20.
Qd2 Nc8 21. Qe3 Kf7 22. Nc1 Nd6 23. Nd3 Ne4 $15 {0-1 (45) Zeman,M (2275)
-Ostrovskiy, A (2453) Pardubice 2019}) (8... Bd6 $2 {falls for a very sneaky
trap!} 9. f3 Bh5 10. Qh4 Bg6 11. Bxg6 fxg6 $16) (8... Bxe2 $6 {is a bit too
simple after} 9. Qxe2 Bd6 10. g3 {White is happy with the bishops. I guess if
you want a short cut you can try this line after} h5 $14) 9. Bf4 (9. Ng3 g6 10.
f3 Bf5 11. Nxf5 gxf5 {I tried to get the bishop pair but found my position
very unpleasant due to Black's kingside pressure} 12. a4 Bd6 13. Qh4 Nce7 14.
Na3 a6 15. g3 Ng6 16. Qh3 h5 $17 {1-0 (33) Ostrovskiy,A (2436)-Jacobson,B 
(2503) Charlotte 2019}) 9... Qb6 10. Nd2 Nf6 (10... Bh5 11. Rb1 Nf6 12. Nc1 Bg6
13. Qe3 Nh5 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bh4 e5 $132 {1-0 (38) Bruedigam, M (2395)
-Ostrovskiy,A (2453) Pardubice 2019}) 11. Rb1 O-O 12. Ng3 g6 13. f3 Bf5 14.
Nxf5 exf5 15. Bg5 Rfe8 16. Qh4 Nd7 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Rfd1 Rae8 $15 {0-1 (39)
Blomqvist,E (2488)-Andreikin,D (2725) Astana 2019  Summary: The exchange
variation has gained popularity in recent years as White has a simple setup
that gives him potential attacking chances in the middlegame. Against my
recommend of Qc7 White has found the new and challenge idea of 7. 0-0 and 8.
Qe1! That seeks to gain the bishop pair. The positions are very playable for
both sides though. One idea is the e6-Bh5 (Bg6) move order; otherwise Nf6 and
Be7!? is a rarer approach to the decent 8.. Nf6.} *

