1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 {The most popular option:
continue developing!} 6. Bf4 (6. h3 $5 {prevents Bg4 ideas} Qc7 (6... e5 {
goes for an IQP and tries to play actively since White delayed development}) (
6... g6 {prepares Bf5}) 7. Ne2 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11.
O-O Bc5 $11) (6. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7] is not White's best move order
since we get the bishop pin}) 6... Bg4 7. Qb3 {White tries to be disruptive
and take advantage of the Bc8's abscence} (7. Nf3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8]
is playable but not theoretically challenging. We can continue with Bd6 and
prepare a queenside minority attack}) 7... Qd7 (7... Qc8 {is more passive but
aims to avoid any potential Ne5/Bb5 ideas} 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5 {
[%cal Gh5g6] A typical maneuver to safeguard the kingside} 11. Rae1 {This is a
strange situation for the variation. White has several similar looking options,
Rfe1/Rae1/Ne5 and attack on the Kingside. Black in turn is quite solid and
hopes to complete development and counter on the queenside} (11. Ne5 Nxe5 12.
Bxe5 O-O) (11. Rfe1 Bg6 (11... O-O)) 11... Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. h4 $5 {
White is preparing for Black's short castle to launch an attack} a6 {[%cal
Gb7b5]} 14. c4 (14. a4 Na5 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 14... a5 15. a3 a4 16. Qd3 O-O 17.
c5 b6 18. cxb6 Qb7 19. Bc7 Nd7 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. b4 axb3 22. Qxb3 Bxa3 23. Rc3
Be7 24. Rfc1 Nb4 25. Ne5 Nxe5 26. Bxe5 Rxc3 27. Qxc3 Qxb6 $17 {0-1 (71)
Kramnik,V (2803)-Ivanchuk,V (2728) Tbilisi 2017}) 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 $1 {
It's important to know that Qxb7 isn't too dangerous} 10. Bxd6 (10. Ne5 Qc7 11.
Nxg4 (11. O-O Nd7) 11... Bxf4 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 $11) 10... Qxd6 11. O-O (11. Qxb7
Rb8 12. Qa6 O-O 13. Bb5 (13. O-O Rb6 14. Qa3 (14. Qa4 Rxb2) 14... Qxa3 15. bxa3
Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Rc8 17. Rfc1 Na5 $44 {0-1 (47) Ritviz,P (2243)-Kathmale,S (2357)
Hyderabad 2018}) (13. Rb1 {Allows us to attack before White castles} Rb6 14.
Qa4 $2 e5 $17) 13... Rb6 14. Qa4 Ne7 $1 15. Ne5 (15. b3 Ng6 16. O-O a6 17. Be2
Ne4 $17 {0-1 (28) Vidit,S (2711)-Le,Q (2715) chess.com INT 2018}) (15. O-O {
White should accept the pawn loss} Rfb8) 15... Ng6 16. Nxg4 Nxg4 17. h3 Nf6 (
17... Nxf2 $1 18. Kxf2 Rfb8 $19 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gd6f4]}) 18. Nb3 Rfb8 $19 {
[%cal Gg6f4,Ge6e5]} (18... e5 {0-1 (35) Aronian,L (2767)-Caruana,F (2822)
Saint Louis 2018})) 11... O-O {White's approach has gained a fair amount of
popularity in recent years. The idea is to play Re1, Ne5 and launch a kingside
attack! The simplicity of this plan made this variation a particular popular
weapon at rapid time controls.} 12. Rae1 (12. Rfe1 Nd7 (12... Rab8 13. Ne5 Bh5
14. a4 Bg6 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Re3 Nd7 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Nf3 Na5 (18... f6 $2 {
1/2-1/2 (40) Aronian,L (2752)-Mamedyarov,S (2774) Stavanger 2019})) (12... Bxf3
13. Nxf3 Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b5] Has scored reasonably for Black although White
enjoys the strong light square bishop} 14. a4 Nd7 15. Qc2 g6 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6,
Gf7,Gg6,Gh7] Thematically setting up along the light squares to negate the Bd3}
16. Qe2 a6 17. g3 Rfe8 {0-1 (70) Risting,E (2279)-Melkumyan,H (2633) London
2017}) 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Rab8 15. Qc2 h6 (15... g6 {[%cal Gg8g7]}) 16. Qe2
a6 17. a4 Rfc8 18. Ne5 Ncxe5 19. dxe5 Qe7 20. Qg4 Qg5 21. Qxg5 hxg5 22. Kh2 b5
{Black launches a minority attack on the queenside to create pawn weaknesses,
a thematic way to get (counter)play in the Carlsbad structure} 23. axb5 axb5
24. Ra7 Nc5 25. Bc2 b4 $15 {0-1 (41) Sudakova,I (2288)-Girya,O (2476) Sochi
2019}) 12... Rab8 (12... Nd7) (12... Bxf3 {Black often resorted in practice to
give up the bishop. White should be a bit better but it's very solid} 13. Nxf3
Rab8 14. Ne5 Qc7 15. f4 b5 16. a3 a5 17. Qc2 Rfc8 18. Qf2 b4 19. axb4 axb4 20.
f5 bxc3 21. bxc3 Re8 22. Qg3 exf5 (22... Nxe5 23. dxe5 Ne4 (23... Nh5 $2 {
1/2-1/2 (30) Aravindh,C (2599)-Andreikin,D (2725) Astana 2019}) 24. Bxe4 dxe4
25. f6 Qc5+ 26. Kh1 g6) 23. Rxf5 Re6 24. Ref1 Nxe5 25. Rxf6 Rxf6 26. Rxf6 Qa7
27. Bf1 Ng6 $11) 13. Ne5 Rfc8 (13... Bh5 14. f4 b5) 14. f4 b5 15. a3 a5 16. h3
Bf5 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. Nxc6 Rxc6 19. Re5 g6 20. Rf3 b4 $19 {0-1 (48) Rodi,L 
(2265)-Campora,D (2515) Buenos Aires 1991  Conclusion: The popular option of 5.
.Nf6 allows us to follow up with Bg4. White's critical approach is Qb3 where
we have a choice: Qc8 keeps more pieces on the board while Qd7 is more popular
to trade bishops with Bd6. It's important to know that Qxb7 ideas aren't
dangerous due to our lead in development The resulting middlegame is equal but
White has a clear and aggressive plan of checkmating us on the Kingside after
a rook goes to e1 and knight to e5. I have attached several examples where
Black survived all of this by timely trading and countering with b5-b4} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
