1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 {I decided to name this variation as the
"Pseudo-Exchange" since White wants to go for similar structures as in the
Exchange Variation. The difference here is that White develops with Nf3 first
in order to play a quick Ne5. Sometimes inexpierenced players will play Nf3
without the proper follow up and this gives us the opportunity with quick and
active development with Bg4} 4. d4 (4. Ne5 $5 {The immediate knight jump is
also possible but perhaps premature} Nc6 5. Bb5 (5. d4 {TR ML}) 5... Bd7 6.
Nxd7 {White's idea was to grab the bishop pair} (6. Bxc6 {Has been tried as
well in order to keep the Ne5 powerful} Bxc6 7. d4 (7. O-O Nf6 (7... e6 {
[%cal Gf8d6] See 7. d4}) 8. d4 e6 9. c3 Be7 10. Bg5 O-O {1/2-1/2 (38) Karjakin,
S (2754)-Shimanov,A (2587) Moscow 2019}) 7... e6 8. O-O Bd6 $5 {[%cal Gg8e7]
Keep options open of both Ne7 and Nf6} 9. Qg4 (9. Re1 Ne7 {gives ideas of Ng6/
f6}) 9... Qf6 10. Bg5 $2 h5 11. Qh4 Qf5 $17 {[%cal Gf7f6] 0-1 (57) Hamdouchi,A
(2308)-Sulskis,S (2518) Calvia 2006}) 6... Qxd7 7. d4 a6 8. Be2 {White wants
this bishop on d3 so he is investing several tempi into this whole two bishops
idea} e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. c3 Nf6 (10... Qc7 11. g3 Nf6 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Nf3 b5 14.
a4 b4 15. c4 dxc4 16. Bxc4 Rfd8 17. Qe2 Qb7 18. Bg5 Be7 19. Rad1 Nd5 20. Bc1
Bf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (62) Santos Latasa,J (2549)-Kuzubov,Y (2689) Batumi 2018}) (
10... f5 $5 {[%cal Gg8f6] is similar to the main game attached below, trying
to go for a Stonewall style setup}) 11. Nd2 O-O 12. a4 e5 $5 {Black accepts an
IQP structure for more active play} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3 h6 15. Be3 Rfe8 16.
Bd4 Qc7 17. g3 Re6 18. Re1 Rae8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (55) So,W (2780)-Vidit,S (2718)
chess.com INT 2018}) 4... Nc6 (4... a6 $5 {a rare idea designed to cut out any
Bb5 ideas} 5. c4 $1 {Transposing into a weird panov} (5. Bd3 Nc6 6. c3 Bg4 {
The early positioning of the Nf3 allows the pin} 7. O-O e6 8. Bf4 Bd6 $11 {
[%cal Gg8e7]} (8... g5 {Mamedyarov goes a bit wild vs his lower rated opponent}
9. Be3 Be7 10. Re1 Qc7 11. Be2 h6 12. Ne5 Bxe2 13. Rxe2 Bd6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15.
Kh1 Ne7 {0-1 (38) Rosenthal,N (2156)-Mamedyarov,S (2766) chess.com INT 2017}))
(5. h3 Bf5) 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 (6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Bc4 (8. Bd3 Bg4) 8...
Be6 9. Bb3 Na5) 6... Nc6 7. Bg5 Be6) 5. Ne5 (5. Bb5 Qa5+ $1 {A key idea to
force Nc3. The Nc3 is a bit misplaced as it prevents c3/c4} 6. Nc3 Bg4 7. Bd2
Rc8 8. a4 Qd8 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e6 11. Ne2 a6 12. Bxc6+ (12. Bd3 Nb4 {
0-1 (54) Hovhannisyan,R (2625)-Petrosyan,M (2551) Yerevan 2018}) 12... Rxc6 13.
c3 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gg8e7,Gd8f6] A little more flexible} (13... Nf6 {1/2-1/2 
(51) Yoo, C (2406)-Ostrovskiy, A (2450) Southwest Class 2019})) (5. Bd3 Bg4 $11
) (5. Nc3 $6 Bg4 $11) (5. c4 $5 {Likely forces us into the Panov after} Nf6 6.
Nc3 Be6) 5... Nf6 {The simplest move although it does allow White to proceed
with his main idea} (5... a6 $5 {Cuts across White's plans} 6. c3 (6. c4 {
Has been tried by Carlsen and other top GMs. But Black seemed very comfortable
with normal development after} e6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Be2 Ne7 10. Bg5
O-O 11. Qd2 Rb8 {0-1 (50) Bellahcene,B (2501)-Donchenko,A (2614) Manavgat 2018}
) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 10. O-O Qc7 11. Re1 Bc5 12. Nd2
Ne7 $11 {0-1 (64) Chigaev,M (2589)-Fedoseev,V (2678) chess.com INT 2020}) (5...
e6 $5 {I have a surprising novelty here} 6. Bb5 (6. c3 $6 Bd6 {[%cal Gg8e7]
After Nge7 and a later f6 Black is very happy}) 6... a6 $5 $146 7. Bxc6+ (7.
Nxc6 Qc7 8. Ne5+ (8. Na7+ Bd7 $1) 8... axb5) 7... bxc6 8. Nxc6 Qc7 9. Ne5 Bd6
10. O-O Ne7 11. Nf3 O-O $44 {The two bishops, open files, and the plan of
f6-e5 seem to give Black fair compensation}) 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 {
Compared to 4. Ne5 White has an improved version since the Bb5 can return to d3
} e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Nd2 Qc7 11. Nf3 (11. g3 {is a move order that tries to
deter our Ne4 idea} O-O 12. Bd3 {With this move order White controls the e4
square for longer} Rae8 $146 {Preparing e5} (12... e5 {is a bit premature but
held} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ (14... Nc4) (14... Rfe8) 15. Qxf3 Rfe8 16.
Be3 Bc5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (30) Adams,M (2703)-Howell,D (2696) London 2018}) 13. Nf3
(13. Re1 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 (15. Bf1 $2 Neg4 $17 {[%csl Rf2]}) 15... Re7)
13... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] reverts to stonewall style}) 11... O-O 12. Re1 (12.
a4 Ne4 13. Be3 f5 $5 $13 {1/2-1/2 (30) Yoo,C (2406)-Rozman,L (2387) New York
2019}) 12... Ne4 $1 {An important idea to avoid giving White a free hand with
a kingside attack} 13. Bd3 f5 {This stonewall style setup works well to get
active play and restrict the Bd3} 14. g3 Rae8 15. Nh4 e5 (15... Kh8 16. Ng2 e5
17. dxe5 Bc5 18. Be3 Nxe5 $36 {1/2-1/2 (78) Christiansen,J (2555)-Belozerov,A 
(2528) St Petersburg 2018}) 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bf1 Ng4 18. Qxd5+ Kh8 $19 19. Be3
Nxe3 20. Rxe3 Bc5 21. Rf3 Re5 {Stockfish displays some monsterously aggressive
ideas here:} (21... f4 $19 {1/2-1/2 (79) Christiansen,J (2558)-Oparin,G (2654)
chess24.com INT 2020}) 22. Qd1 g5 23. Ng2 f4 24. gxf4 g4 {Summary: The
"Pseudo-Exchange" aims for a quick Nf3-Ne5 in order to gain the bishop pair
advantage. A key idea we have studied is the stonewall style Ne4-f5 in
response. It is also possible to avoid White's main ideas with earlier a7-a6
pushes to prevent Bb5.} *

