1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 $5 {Aiming for a perfect
anti-Isolated pawn setup} (5... Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 {Is aggressive from White
to attack d5} Ne4 $5 {A rare idea to bother White's development} 7. Nxe4 (7.
cxd5 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qxd5 9. Nf3 Bg4) 7... dxe4 {[%csl Rd4]} 8. d5 (8. Ne2 Bg4 {
[%csl Rd4]}) 8... Ne5 9. Qd4 f6 $1 {Black's play looks nonsensically but
actually White's king is in danger in several lines.} 10. Qxe4 (10. Bf4 Ng4 $1
{[%cal Ge7e5]}) 10... Qb6 11. O-O-O Qxf2 $13 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8] Preparing Bf5/
Rc8 counters}) 6... Be6 $5 {A sideline to simultaneously support our center
while pressuring White's} 7. c5 {Logically releasing the tension} (7. cxd5 Bxd5
{[%cal Ge7e6] Great anti-IQP position}) (7. Bg5 g6 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) 7... g6 {
Black's plan if allowed is: Bg7, 0-0 and then Bg4 and Ne4/d7 to pressure d4 or
push e5} 8. Bb5 Bg7 9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge8g8,Ge7e5]}) 6. Qb3
$1 {The best and most active solution. We now gambit a pawn} (6. Nf3 Bg7 {
[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Gb7b6,Gd5c4] is easy for us after 0-0 Nc6. Then we will
usually throw in dxc4 once the Bf1 moves. Bg4 is often an option but I prefer
b6-bb7 w/Rc8 and Na5 or Nb4} 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 b6 $11)
(6. cxd5 Nxd5 {White tries to get an intiative against the Nd5 but we have
sufficient play for example} 7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb3 Bg7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5]}) 6...
Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O {[%csl Rd5] A big battle will rage around the d5 pawn. Our
usual idea will be Nd7-Nb6, Na6-Nc7, or even a radical sacrifice with e6!} 8.
Be2 (8. g3 $5 e6 $1) 8... Nbd7 9. Bf3 Nb6 10. Nge2 Bg4 $1 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 12. a4
Nf6 13. Nf4 a5 14. O-O {A key position for the line. White is doing his best
to save d5 but we have two interesting and rarer options} Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gc8c4,
Gc4b4] Aiming for Rc4-Rb4} (14... g5 $5 15. Nd3 h6 {[%csl Rd5] Picking up d5
next. The weaknesses of the kingside seems to be managable}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Panov-Botvinnik Attack "]
[Black "5..g6 6. Nf3?!"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D94"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 {The Panov Botvinnik Attack: White is
going for an Isolated Queens Pawn (IQP) position with active piece play} Nf6 5.
Nc3 g6 $5 {If we can get away with setting up a fianchetto system, then we are
going to be doing very well. First of all, our kingside will be very secure
against White's attacking attempts (usually done with a battery Bc2-Qd3) .
Second, our Bg7 will not only be a powerful defender but also will exert great
pressure against the d4 weakness. Finally, since we have not played e6 our Bc8
will be free to wander (although we can put it on b7 as well). Futhermore, I
am also a fan of this system since it is not well known by our opponents and
their usual plans don't work against it.} 6. Nf3 $6 {This perfectly natural
developing move is already a mistake. This move looks very natural...and it is
very popular! That is great news for us. The problem is that White isn't
putting any pressure on our position as we get developed and target the
isolated d4 pawn} Bg7 {White usually tries to develop his pieces normally here}
7. Be2 (7. cxd5 Nxd5 {Transposes to a position examined in the cxd5 file}) 7...
O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 {White's most popular option to prevent Bg4. Otherwise we
can play some kind of combo of Bg4 or dxc4 w/b6} (9. c5 {This is an important
move to have a look at because some players make this pawn push in some
positions. Here White doesn't get an IQP but the d4 pawn is still exposed.
Usually Black can play moves like Bg4 putting pressure on it and sometimes
striking in the center with e5. However almost always the key response is:} Ne4
$1 {Unleashing the Bg7! Here there are 2 cool ideas worth knowing.} 10. Be3
Nxc3 $1 {A great move with the idea:} (10... Nxc5 $5 {is a nice tactical shot
that is worth knowing} 11. dxc5 d4) 11. bxc3 b6 $1 12. cxb6 axb6 {White no
longer has an IQP but his c3 and a2 pawns are weak which is also a big problem.
On top of that, Black also has great control over the light squares (such as
c4).} 13. Qd2 Ba6 $1 $15) 9... dxc4 $1 10. Bxc4 {We have reached an IQP
position..... the type of pawn structure White is going for in the PBA. Except.
..this is the best possible version for Black! All our pieces will soon find
good squares and White will lack active play in return for his structural
concession (pawn on d4 is isolated). Black's main plans here a mix: pressure
the d4 pawn and play for the light squares on d5/c4. The games below are
important to study because they show how Black can slowly take over the game
and put White on the defensive. Here is Black's usual winning strategy:
develop pieces on influential squares (that control light squares) by playing
b6-Bb7-Na5-Rc8-Nc4 (Nd5) (usually), followed by some combo of Qd6+Rd8 
(pressure d4) pawn....followed by favorable trades and winning the d4 pawn and
then winning the endgame!} b6 $1 {I like this plan the best. Black is going to
place both bishops on the long diagonals, very influential} (10... Na5 {
This is another popular plan. I want you to pay attention how easily Black
wins:} 11. Be2 Be6 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 12. Ne5 Rc8 {Targetting the d5 and c4
squares, very juicy for our knights! If White wants to get rid of those pieces
he will have to make some trades (Not good for IQP).} 13. Re1 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5
15. b3 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 {Black is making some good trades. All that is left
on the board (pieces) are bishops and Black's dominate White. Next step is to
take over the open files and pressure the d4 pawn.} 17. Ba3 Bf6 18. Qd2 Qc7 19.
Rac1 Rd8 20. Bb5 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Qb8 22. Qe2 e6 23. Rd1 Qc7 24. Bc1 a6 25. Bd3
Bxd4 {White loses the pawn! A common story.} 26. Bg5 Qg3 $3 27. Qg4 Qxf2+ {
0-1 (27) Bolding,K (2290)-Ivkov,B (2470)/Lyon 1995/ A typical game. Black
develops his pieces on influential squares and ends up rounding up the d4 pawn.
}) 11. Be3 (11. Bg5 Bb7 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rad1 Na5 14. Be2 {[%cal Ga5c4,Gc8c4]
The standard setup for Black. Ready to invade d5 or c4.} Nc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 {
Now Black gets the 2 bishop advantage. The Bb7 is very nice.} 16. Ne5 $2 Rxc3
$3 {Very good calculation, a winning tactical shot!} 17. Qxc3 Ne4 18. Qe3 Nxg5
19. Qxg5 f6 {The point. Black gets 2 pieces vs rook. Not just any 2 pieces...
but 2 superpowerful bishops!: 0-1 (26) Menna Barreto,F (2247)-Santiago,Y (2422)
/Caleta ENG 2016/}) 11... Bb7 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Be2 Nb4 $5 {[%cal Gb4d5] In the
examples above we've seen plans with Na5-Nc4 but in this game Black solely
focuses on the d5 square. Let's see how this turns out} 14. Rac1 Nbd5 {A
common theme in these structures is that Black really enjoys using the outpost
in front of the IQP.} 15. Bh6 Nxc3 $1 {It looks like Black is helping White
remedy his IQP issue but actually he's prepared a nice tactic:} 16. bxc3 Ne4
17. Qe3 Rxc3 $1 18. Rxc3 Nxc3 $19 {0-1 (35) Orehek,S (2092)-Matlakov,M (2694)/
Tallinn EST 2016/   Summary: A long file but there is actually not a lot to
memorize....rather I wanted to show several very instructive games that
showcase Black's positional strategies in exploiting the IQP as well as the
light squares. The fianchetto option is very effective because it cuts across
White's standard ideas of a Kingside attack. On top of that many players play
the inspid Nf3 instead of Qb3 or cxd5. We have seen the ideas Black should
employ in the resulting IDEAL IQP: b6, Bb7, Na5/Nb4, Rc8 and make GOOD TRADES
w/PRESSURE AGAINST d4!} *

