[White "Panov-Botvinnik Attack "]
[Black "5.. g6 6. cd"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D94"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "68"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 {The Panov Botvinnik Attack: White is
going for an Isolated Queens Pawn (IQP) position with active piece play} Nf6 5.
Nc3 g6 $5 {If we can get away with setting up a fianchetto system, then we are
going to be doing very well. First of all, our kingside will be very secure
against White's attacking attempts (usually done with a battery Bc2-Qd3) .
Second, our Bg7 will not only be a powerful defender but also will exert great
pressure against the d4 weakness. Finally, since we have not played e6 our Bc8
will be free to wander (although we can put it on b7 as well). Futhermore, I
am also a fan of this system since it is not well known by our opponents and
their usual plans don't work against it.} 6. cxd5 $5 {A more confrontation
option than Nf3 but not as challenging as Qb3} Nxd5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8]
regains the pawn ASAP. I used to prefer 6.. Bg7 but after testing this move
out in practice I think it may be even easier as White's intiative isn't
serious enough to trouble us. Furthermore this avoids the 7. Bb5+ variation I
looked at below} (6... Bg7 7. Bb5+ $5 {A good line that looks to disrupt our
setup} (7. Qb3 {Transposes to Qb3.}) (7. Bc4 {White may try to hang onto his
extra pawn. This is of course the most critical concept in this line but it is
better to start with Qb3 and then Be2-Bf3 as we will see.} O-O 8. Nge2 {
[%cal Ge2f4] Planning to hold onto the pawn.} (8. Nf3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Our
goal is to pick up the d5 pawn and play vs the IQP} 9. O-O Nb6 10. Bb3 (10. Qb3
{Is a typical situation where Black's activity and better pieces will more
than counterbalance the pawn deficit} Bf5 11. Re1 Rc8 12. Bf1 Nfxd5 $1 13. Nxd5
Qxd5 14. Rxe7 Be6 $1 15. Qxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gc8c2,Rg7d4,Gd5f3,Gf8d8,Gb6c4] Black
is down a pawn but we have a multitude of active plans to choose from and the
d4 pawn is an easy target.}) 10... Nfxd5 $1 {[%cal Gg7d4,Rc8e6,Rb6c4] I've
always favored this rarer capture as it opens up my bishop and keeps the b6
knight close to the queenside (I want to install it on c4!)} 11. Ne5 {The
following is a perfect example of Black's plans:} Be6 12. Bd2 Rc8 13. Rc1 Nxc3
$1 14. bxc3 Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4] Blockading the hanging pawns is the most
effective idea!} 15. Nxc4 Bxc4 16. Re1 e6 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 18. Qb3 Qd5 $17 {
[%csl Gc4,Gd5] A beautiful lightsquare blockade in the spirit of the Caro-Kann:
0-1 (23) Marozzi,G (2041)-Cioara,A (2471)/Porto San Giorgio 2008/}) 8... Na6 $5
{[%cal Ga6c7] You will see that in most cases I prefer Nbd7-Nb6 to regain the
pawn but here I am favoring the other regrouping. The reason for this is that
I have a specific plan based on targetting the Bc4 (b5!)} 9. O-O (9. Bxa6 $6
bxa6 {[%cal Gc8b7] It is not worth it for White to damage our pawn structure
since we will have a powerful bishop pair in return.}) 9... Nc7 10. Nf4 b6 $1 {
[%cal Gc8b7] The start of our key plan:} 11. a4 {There are transpositions here
but White is already anticipating us playing b5.} Bb7 12. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5] The
fight is all about the d5 pawn. If White can keep it on the board, then it
will have a horrible cramping effect on our position.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b3]
x-raying the queen and preparing b5.} 13. Re1 a6 $1 {[%cal Rb6b5]} 14. Bd2 b5 {
Finally Black achieves his plan and gets a very satisfactory game. All our
pieces spring into action and the d5 pawn drops.} 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bf1 {
White decides to leave the b5 pawn alone in fear of the b-file pin. In any
case, Black is very comfortable and went on to win:} (16. Nxb5 Nxb5 17. Bxb5
Nxd5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8b2,Gb7g2]}) (16. Bxb5 Nfxd5 {[%cal Gg7d4,Rb8b3]})
16... Nfxd5 17. Ncxd5 Bxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 20. Ra5 Bxd4 21. b3 Rfc8
22. Rxb5 Rxb5 23. Bxb5 Rc2 {White's two bishops and passed pawn can become
very troublesome but Black's activity gives him the preferable game! White was
unable to cope with the pressure and blundered in 0-1 (30) Borge,N (2383)
-Svane,R (2506)/Copenhagen DEN 2014/}) 7... Nbd7 (7... Bd7 $6 {is a common
mistake!} 8. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Rd7] The Bd7 is actually misplaced since it
prevents Nd7 and blocks the Qd8 from attacking d5.}) 8. d6 $1 {This was
White's big idea. Otherwise the Bb5 is misplaced after a6-b5} O-O $5 {is an
interesting pawn sacrifice that avoids the endgame.} (8... exd6 9. Qe2+ Qe7 (
9... Kf8 $5 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf8g8,Gg8h7] is a very exotic idea where Black is
quite desperate to avoid the endgame! The idea is to walk the king over to h7
and try to utilize the d5 outpost for his knights. However if Black is this
desperate to avoid trading Queens why not play the more aggresive 0-0 gambit?
Here is a quick successful example though:} 10. Nf3 Nb6 11. O-O h6 12. Re1 Kg8
13. Bf4 Kh7 14. Ne4 Nbd5 15. Bg3 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Be6 $11 {0-1 (40) Leon Hoyos,M 
(2543) -Burmakin,V (2625)/Bratto 2008/}) 10. Bf4 (10. Qxe7+ {is imprecise
since White can reach the same endgame with an extra tempo} Kxe7 11. Nf3 a6 12.
Bd3 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 10... Qxe2+ 11. Ngxe2 (11. Bxe2 {This is actually more
common but I have only faced Ngxe2. Play here runs:} Ke7 12. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3b7]}
Nb6 {[%cal Gc8e6] It looks difficult for Black to develop here but they key
idea is to sacrifice the b7 pawn.} 13. Nge2 h6 $5 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gg5g4] Setting
up a sneaky trap to catch the Bf3! This move is also useful to control the g5
square.} 14. h3 Be6 $1 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Bf3 Nfd5 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1,Ge6a2,Gd5b4,
Gb8b2,Gh8c8] With strong queenside pressure for the pawn. Black eventually
prevailed: 0-1 (30) Bergstrom,R (2315)-Rogers,I (2580)/ Gausdal 1996/}) 11...
Ke7 12. O-O Nb6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf6d5,Ga7a6] White will try to get an intiative
in this endgame against the Ke7 but Black is actually very solid once we play
Be6. The key idea here is to occupy d5 with a knight and start queenside play
on the c-file and with a6-b5. Here is how one of my games went:} 13. Rfe1 Be6
14. Bg5 h6 $1 15. Bxf6+ (15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 a6 17. Bd3 Nfd5 {Black's plan is
well in motion}) 15... Bxf6 16. d5 Bd7 17. Ng3+ Kd8 18. Nge4 Be5 19. Bxd7 Kxd7
20. Rac1 Rac8 $17 {0-1 (51) Zarychta,K (2222) -Kaszowski,D (2327)/Lubniewice
2002/}) 9. dxe7 Qxe7+ 10. Nge2 {Black has obvious compensation in the form of
easy and quick development but White is also solid and has an extra pawn.} (10.
Be2 b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc8b7] Black's compensation lies in his currently
superior development and this ambitious move is the best way to make it count!}
11. Nxb5 (11. a3 {Was too meek and black got a great game with simple
development:} Bb7 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 a6 14. O-O Nb6 $44 {[%cal Gf6d5] 0-1 
(56) Kun,G (2336)-Chernyshov,K (2531)/Budapest 2005/}) 11... Nb6 12. Nf3 Re8
$44 {White's king is stuck in the center while our pieces are coming out to
fight.}) 10... a6 11. Bd3 (11. Bxd7 Qxd7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]} 12. O-O b5 $44
) 11... b5 $44 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf8e8,Ga8d8]}) 7. Bc4 {White plays actively in an
attempt to grab the intiative} (7. Qb3 {A common idea for White is some Bc4/
Qb3 tempo gainer but here we will see that the intiative can be defused} Nb6 8.
Bb5+ (8. Nf3 $6 {Too slow} Be6 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. Qd1 Bg7 $15 {0-1 (44)
Kosintseva,N (2483)-Rambaldi,F (2557) Dallas 2015}) (8. d5 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10.
Rd1 Na6 $1 11. Be2 Qd6 12. Nf3 Bd7 13. O-O Nc5 14. Qa3 Nca4 {0-1 (43)
Ibragimov,I (2637)-Kamsky,G (2671) New York 2006}) 8... Bd7 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Ne5
{White's most common try otherwise there is no compensation for the d4 pawn} (
10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bxb5 12. Nxb5 Nc6 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 Qd5 $15 {
0-1 (36) Pruijssers,R (2543)-Postny,E (2581) Groningen 2017}) 10... O-O 11.
Nxd7 N8xd7 (11... N6xd7 $5 12. O-O Nc6) 12. O-O Nf6 13. Rd1 e6 14. a4 Nbd5 {
1/2-1/2 (45) Novosadova,K (2209)-Lintchevski,D (2574) Pardubice 2015}) (7. Nf3
$6 {As often happens in these IQP positions simple development isn't enough
for White to pose any problems} Bg7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8c6]} 8. Qb3 (8. Bc4 Nxc3 9.
bxc3 Qc7 $1 10. Qb3 O-O {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5]} 11. Ng5 e6 12. Ba3 Rd8 13. O-O Nc6
14. Be2 b6 15. Bf3 Bb7 16. Qa4 h6 17. Ne4 Nxd4 18. cxd4 Rxd4 19. Qb3 Bxe4 20.
Bb2 Rd3 {0-1 (20) Charbonneau,P (2505)-So,W (2765) chess.com INT 2019}) (8. Be2
{is again way too slow} O-O $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gb7b6] Black has a comfortable
anti-iqp position. For similar types of positions see the 6. Nf3 file}) 8...
Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O {No more IQP but White now has the "hanging pawns" on c3-d4.
The Qb3 is vulnerable to both Be6 and Na5 ideas (which work to blockade on d5
and c4)} 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O b6 (11... Qc7 12. Rd1 Rd8 13. Bg5 Be6 14. Qa3 Rac8
$15 {[%cal Gc6a5] 0-1 (31) Khamrakulov,I (2496)-Ninov,N (2518) Pamplona 2011})
12. Be3 Na5 13. Qb4 Bb7 14. Rac1 Rc8 15. Rfd1 Qd6 $11 {0-1 (46) Nanu,C (2506)
-Navara,D (2638) Budva 2009}) 7... Nb6 8. Bb3 Bg7 9. Nf3 (9. d5 {Grabs space
at the cost of dark square control} O-O 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2 e6 $5 {An original
idea, Black will get enough piece activity in return for the pawn structure
deficit} 11. dxe6 Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1 Bxe6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6] 1/2-1/2 
(31) Sermek,D (2555)-Solak,D (2582) Sibenik 2005}) 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12.
Qxf3 N8d7 13. O-O Nc5 14. Bg5 (14. Rd1 Nxb3 15. axb3 Nc8 $5 16. Be3 a6 17. b4
Nd6 $11 {1-0 (68) Li,C (2750)-Ipatov,A (2619) Doha 2015}) 14... Nxb3 15. axb3
h6 16. Be3 Nc8 {A common regrouping to blockade the advanced isolated pawn} 17.
Rfd1 Nd6 18. Rxa7 Rxa7 19. Bxa7 Qa5 20. Bd4 Bxd4 21. Rxd4 Qa1+ 22. Rd1 Qxb2 $11
{1/2-1/2 (67) Frolyanov,D (2561)-Tomashevsky,E (2722) Loo 2013}) 9... O-O 10.
O-O Nc6 11. d5 (11. Be3 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4,Ga5b3,Gc8g4]}) 11... Na5 {Strong
queenside counterplay is coming with Nc4. White also needs to watch out for
Nxb3 and Bxc3 to pick up the d5 pawn} 12. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7]} (12. h3 {Prevents
Bg4 but we have Bf5 too} Bf5 13. Re1 Re8 14. Nd4 Nxb3 (14... Bd7 $11 {[%cal
Ga8c8]}) 15. axb3 Bd7 16. Bg5 Nc8 17. Ne4 h6 18. Bh4 g5 19. Bg3 Qb6 20. Nf3 f5
21. Ned2 f4 22. Nc4 Qc5 23. Bh2 {Black's inventive play would have been best
continued with} Nd6 (23... Nb6 $2 {0-1 (38) Harikrishna,P (2725)-Bocharov,D 
(2533) St Petersburg 2018}) 24. Nfe5 Bf5 $17) 12... Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3
Re8 15. Bg5 (15. Rd1 Nxb3 16. axb3 Nc8 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc8d6] An idea we've seen
earlier to reposition the knight into a blockading role: 1/2-1/2 (54)
Mamedyarov,S (2752)-Kamsky,G (2726) Baku 2008}) (15. Be3 Nxb3 (15... Rc8 {
keeps more tension on the board}) 16. axb3 Bxc3 17. Bxb6 Qxb6 18. bxc3 Qxb3 19.
Rab1 Qa3 20. Rxb7 Rac8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (26) Ehlvest,J (2598)-Kamsky,G (2702)
Philadelphia 2010}) 15... Nxb3 16. axb3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxd5 18. Rxe7 $2 (18.
Qxd5 $11 Nxd5 19. c4 f6 20. cxd5 fxg5 21. Rac1 Rad8 22. Rc7 Rxd5 23. Rxb7 a5
24. Rexe7 {1/2-1/2 (24) Fridman,D (2648)-Rodshtein,M (2638) Beersheba 2013})
18... Rxe7 19. Bxe7 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Nd5 21. Bc5 Nxc3 22. Rxa7 Rxa7 23. Bxa7 f5 $6
(23... Kf8 {[%cal Gf8e7]}) 24. Kf1 Kf7 25. Ke1 Nd5 26. Kf1 Ke6 27. Bb8 Nb4 28.
Ba7 Nc6 29. Bb6 Kd5 30. Ke2 Nd4+ 31. Ke3 Nxb3 32. Kf4 h6 33. h4 Nd4 34. Ke3 Ne6
{0-1 (34) El Debs,F (2525)-Lenderman,A (2619) Campinas 2013  Summary: 6. cxd5
is a confrontational approach that gives us two choices. With 6.. Bg7 we allow
the mini-gambit after Bc4+Ne2. Here we must remember the nice idea of Na6-Nc7
to attack d5 and prepare b5. However White also has the more annoying 7. Bb5+
after which I propose gambiting a pawn with 0-0 instead of going into the
endgame (which is also playable and fine). My main suggestion is to
immediaetly regain the pawn with 6..Nxd5 after which White must act fast with
Qb3 or Bc4. However after developing logically with Bg7/0-0/Nc6 we will get
pressure on the d4 pawn or queenside ideas of Na5-c4} *

