{We will devote our attention to the main line of the g6 panov: 6. Qb3. In
this variation there arises a tremendous battle for the d5 pawn. The game
turns quite dynamic and I have tried to showcase all the shocking ideas Black
has at his disposal to fight for the intiative. I have been very successful in
this variation over my career and I will show you all the analysis that
assisted me!} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Qb3 $1 {
White takes quick action and targets the center before we finish developing}
Bg7 7. cxd5 O-O {The fight will revolve around the d5 pawn. Is it an extra
central pawn for White or an isolater ripe for the picking for Black's pieces?}
8. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gg1e2,Ge2f4] White's main try to solidify d5.} (8. g3 {
[%cal Gf1g2] Looks like a logical counterpart to 8. Be2 but actually has a
downside: White is weakening some light squares!} e6 $1 (8... Re8 $5 {[%cal
Ge8e1]} 9. Nge2 e6 $1 {The big idea! We gambit a pawn while White's king is
stuck in the center} 10. Bg2 (10. dxe6 {Accepting the sacrifice is brave:} Bxe6
11. Qxb7 Nbd7 {White is up two pawns but is still lagging in development.
Worst of all, he still needs to castle} 12. Bg2 Rb8 13. Qxa7 {White is now up
three pawns!} (13. Qa6 $6 Nb6 {[%cal Ge6c4]} 14. b3 Nfd5 {[%cal Ge8e1,Gg7a1]})
13... Bc4 {Catching White's king in the center. All of our pieces are out and
exerting tremendous pressure against White's game. I would definitely prefer
Black here!!} 14. Bf3 Nd5 $3 15. O-O (15. Nxd5 $2 Rxe2+ 16. Bxe2 Bxd5 17. O-O
Ra8) 15... Nxc3 $1 (15... Ra8 16. Qb7 Rb8 $11 {Black can force a draw but
continues playing very energetically and is richly rewarded}) 16. Nxc3 Bxf1 17.
Kxf1 Nf8 {[%csl Rd4]} 18. Nd5 Ne6 19. Be3 Rxb2 $13 {0-1 (47) Hagesaether,H 
(2215)-Yevseev,D (2455)/Norway 1998/}) 10... exd5 (10... Nxd5 {[%cal Gg7a1]})
11. Be3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4] White's misplaced Qb3 gives Black a small
intiative in the symmetrical position. My opponent tries to justify his queen
position and grabs a hot pawn!} 12. Nxd5 $2 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Qa5+ 14. Kf1 Bh3+ 15.
Bg2 Bg4 16. Nc3 Nxd4 17. Qd5 Qa6+ 18. Kg1 Nc2 19. Rf1 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Be6 21. Qb5
Bc4 22. Qxa6 Bxa6 23. Re1 Bxc3 24. bxc3 Rac8 25. Bf1 Bxf1 26. Kxf1 Rxc3 27. Kf2
Re5 28. Re2 Ra3 29. Rc1 b6 30. Rcc2 Kg7 31. Rcd2 Rea5 32. Kg2 Kf6 33. Kf2 R5a4
34. Rc2 Ke5 35. Kf3 g5 36. Rcd2 h5 37. Rc2 f5 38. Kf2 Ke4 39. Rcd2 b5 40. Rc2
a6 41. Rcd2 Rd3 42. Rc2 Rc4 43. Rb2 b4 44. Rec2 Rdc3 45. Rd2 a5 46. Re2 Rd3 47.
h3 Rcc3 48. g4 fxg4 49. hxg4 h4 {0-1 (49) Kleinman,M (2298)-Ostrovskiy,A (2403)
/ Arlington USA 2013}) 9. Bg2 (9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qxb7 Re8 {TR}) 9... Nxd5 10.
Nge2 Nc6 11. O-O Nxc3 12. bxc3 Na5 13. Qd1 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) (8. Nge2 {
[%cal Ge2f4,Gg2g3] is flexible. White may play Nf4-Be2 or g3-Bg2. However we
have a powerful idea in any case:} a5 $1 (8... Na6 9. g3 (9. Nf4 Nc7 10. Be2 (
10. Bc4 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. a4 Rb8 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] transposes to an idea
from the cxd5 chapter}) 10... Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b3] The Nc7 is perfectly placed to
attack d5 and support queenside expansion} 11. O-O b5 12. a3 Bb7 13. Bf3 a5 14.
Re1 Re8 15. Bd2 b4 16. axb4 axb4 17. Ne4 Nfxd5 {0-1 (69) Cabezas Ayala,I (2374)
-Burmakin,V (2625)/Navalmoral 2008/}) 9... b5 $1 {White's development is a bit
slow and his king is stuck in the center. A perfect time to provoke a crisis}
10. Bg2 (10. a3 Nc7 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 11. Bg2 Bb7 (11... a5 $5 {is a surprising
trick} 12. d6 $6 exd6 13. Bxa8 Be6 $15 {[%cal Gd8a8] The light squares are
chronically weak in White's camp}) 12. Nf4 Rb8 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gd8d6,Gf8d8]}) (10.
Nxb5 Bb7 11. Bg2 Bxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. O-O Rb8 {A typical case: Black is down
a pawn but enjoys tremendous activity. White is having trouble developing and
has to defend his vulnerable IQP and queenside 1/2-1/2 (31) Karthikeyan,M 
(2435)-Zenzera,A (2387)/Kirishi RUS 2013/}) 10... b4 11. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3]} (
11. Na4 Bb7 12. Nf4 Qa5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8d8]}) 11... Nc7 $5 (11... Bb7 12.
Ne3 Rb8 13. O-O Nc7 14. Qxb4 Nfxd5 {[%cal Gg7a1,Gb8b1] 0-1 (25) Tsvetkov,A 
(2519) -Raykin,L/RCCA corr 2005/Corr 2008 (25)}) 12. d6 exd6 13. Bxa8 Be6 $44)
9. Nf4 g5 (9... a4 10. Nxa4 g5) 10. Nfe2 (10. Nd3 a4 11. Nxa4 Nxd5 $44 {
0-1 (44) Bakalchuk,J (2459)-Gorodetzky,D (2449) Petah Tikva 2019}) 10... a4 11.
Nxa4 Nxd5) (8. Bc4 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 9. Nge2 Nb6 10. O-O Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 12.
Bg5 Bb7 13. Bxf6 {White continues to make concessions to keep the pawn} exf6 $5
$15 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8c8,Gf8d8] Surprisingly may be a strong option as the pawns
control a lot of central squares while avoiding e7 becoming a target} (13...
Bxf6 {0-1 (21) Vasquez Schroder,R (2542)-Kamsky,G (2741) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013})
) 8... Nbd7 (8... a5 {This is a very rare move that I've played as a suprise a
couple of times. My examples:} 9. Bf3 (9. Nf3 $1 {This is a testing option,
but I had an idea:} a4 $5 10. Nxa4 Nxd5 {Down a pawn but good play on light
squares and against the IQP. There is certainly practical compensation.} 11.
Nc3 Nb6 12. O-O Be6 13. Qd1 Nc6 14. Be3 Qd7 $44 {[%cal Gf8d8] 1-0 (58) Li,R 
(2462)-Ostrovskiy,A (2396)/Linthicum USA 2016/}) 9... Na6 10. Nge2 Nb4 11. O-O
Bf5 $44 {0-1 (34) Yanovsky,V (2254)-Ostrovskiy,A (2490)/Internet Chess Club
2015}) 9. Bf3 Nb6 10. Nge2 {The main idea by far} (10. h3 {Prevented my main
plan of Bg4, but burns a valuble opening tempo. Anyway, the bishop has another
good spot} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gd3c4]} 11. a4 a5 12. Qb5 Ne8 $1 13. Nge2 Nd6 14.
Qb3 Bd3 15. Be3 Bc4 $15 {0-1 (40) Ng,A (2260)-Ostrovskiy,A (2353)/KCF Quads
2011/}) (10. Bg5 {Aims to eleminate the Nf6 to ease pressure off d5. However
Black gets 2 bishops} Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gd3c4]} 11. Rd1 a5 (11... Qc8 {[%cal
Gf8d8,Gc8c4,Gf5g4] was an interesting suggestion to me by GM Yasser Seriawan})
12. Nge2 (12. a4 Qd6 {[%cal Gd6b4]}) 12... a4 13. Qb5 h6 14. Bxf6 exf6 15. O-O
Re8 $44) (10. Bf4 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3,Gd3c4]} (10... Re8 $5 11. Nge2 Bg4 12. Bxg4
Nxg4 13. a4 Nf6) (10... e6 $5 {A borrowed idea from the g3 variation} 11. d6 (
11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Qd1 Nfd5 $44) 11... Nfd5 12. Be5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qg5 14. Nge2
Qxe5 15. O-O Qxd6 $44 {0-1 (54) Jedryczka,K (2440)-Ponomariov,R (2580)
Swidnica 1998}) 11. Rd1 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gf5g4]} 12. h3 h5 13. Nge2 Rfd8 14. d6
exd6 15. O-O d5 16. Be5 Bg4 $1 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. hxg4 hxg4 19. Be4 dxe4 20.
Nxe4 Bg7 $15 {0-1 (47) Mainka,R (2450)-Jadoul,M (2400)/ Luxembourg 1988/})
10... Bg4 {My favorite idea, eliminating the troublesome Bf3} 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 12.
a4 $1 (12. O-O Nf6 13. Nf4 Qd7 14. a4 {I don't have to weaken my queenside
with a5 anymore!} Rfd8 {[%csl Rd5] Once d5 falls I will have a perfect
anti-IQP game with great piece activity} 15. d6 Qxd6 16. Nb5 Qd7 (16... Qb8 $15
{[%cal Gb6d5,Ga7a6] Looked passive but is perfectly reasonable and avoids
sacrificing}) 17. Nxa7 Rxa7 18. Qxb6 Ra6 19. Qb4 Rd6 $44 {I was comfortable
sacrificing the pawn as I have tremendous pressure on his position. 1/2 (25)-1/
2 (25) Hunt,A (2512)-Ostrovskiy,A (2456)/ Washington International 2012}) 12...
Nf6 $1 {Not fearing a5} 13. O-O (13. a5 $6 Nbxd5 14. Qxb7 {White can grab the
queenside pawn but as is often the case in this variation, Black's development
and White's structure give Black the better game!} Qd6 15. Qb3 Rab8 16. Qd1 (
16. Qa3 {Was an example from my game. 0-1 (66) Qin,Z (2191)-Ostrovskiy,A (2422)
/ New York International 2012} Qa6 $1) 16... Rfc8 17. O-O Qa6 $1 {[%cal Gc8c1,
Gb8b1,Gd5b4,Gg7a1] 0-1 (64) Sanal,V (2487)-Tomashevsky,E (2744)/Doha QAT 2015/}
) 13... a5 14. Nf4 {A critical position and the ultimate main line of our
variation. I realized there is a problem with the "established main line"} Rc8
$1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8c4,Gc4b4] I had analyzed this very rare continuation
first in 2016. It has only been tested twice since. The idea is to go for the
active Rc4-Rb4 idea} (14... Qd6 $6 {This is played most often but after} 15.
Nb5 Qd7 16. d6 exd6 17. Be3 {[%csl Gb5,Gf4][%cal Gf4d5] White is scoring 90%
and has a great game. In the symmetrical structure he is controlling all the
key squares!}) (14... g5 $1 {weakens the king position to target the central
pawns better} 15. Nd3 h6 16. Nc5 (16. Bd2 Nfxd5 (16... Nbxd5 17. Rfe1 e6 18.
Nb5 Nc7 19. Nxc7 Qxc7 20. Ne5 Nd7 21. Rac1 Qb6 22. Qxb6 Nxb6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (50)
Pogosyan,G (2375)-Tishin,P (2423) Dubna 2016}) 17. Nb5 e6 18. Rae1 Ne7 19. Nc5
Nf5 20. Nxb7 Qd7 21. Nc5 Qc6 22. Rc1 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Bxd4 24. Qh3 Qd5 $11 {
0-1 (37) Kurilin,A (2335)-Tishin,P (2431) Rilsk 2017}) 16... Nbxd5 17. Nxb7 Rb8
18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Qb5 Qc7 20. Qxd5 Rxb7 21. Bd2 Rxb2 22. Bxa5 Qa7 23. Bc3 Rc2
24. Qb3 Rxc3 25. Qxc3 Bxd4 26. Qc6 Bxa1 27. Rxa1 Qd4 28. Rb1 Rd8 29. h3 Rd6 30.
Qe8+ Kg7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Stany,G (2494)-Macovei,A (2394) Arad 2018}) 15. Be3
{A very fresh position which I analyzed. I believe Black has practically equal
chances based on the following dynamic line:} (15. Qb5 {When this move was
played in 1963 White went after the a5 pawn which is critical} Rc4 16. Nd3 (16.
Qxa5 Nbxd5 $1 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 {[%csl Rd4] Black will regain d4 and have an
advantage due to the active pieces (a common theme)!}) 16... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6,
Rg7d4]} 17. Rd1 (17. Qxa5 Nd6 $146 {Improving the knight before collecting the
pawns. There is no rush as White can't defend them!} (17... Bxd4 18. Bh6 {
0-1 (36) Tukmakov,V-Lazarev,E/Kiev 1963/EXT 2003 (36)}) 18. Be3 Bxd4 19. Bxd4
Rxd4 {[%cal Gb6d5] White is powerless to stop the tactic Nxd5!}) 17... Nd6 18.
Qxa5 Bxd4 19. Be3 Qa8 20. Qxa8 Rxa8 21. a5 Nd7 22. Bxd4 Rxd4 23. f3 Nf6 24. b4
Rc8 25. Ne2 Rdc4 26. Kf2 Kf8 $5 (26... Rh4 {1/2-1/2 (68) Compagnone,G (2289)
-Krzyzanowski,A (2326) ICCF email 2013})) (15. Re1 Rc4 {[%cal Gc4b4]} 16. Be3
Rb4 17. Qa2 Rc4 18. Rac1 Qd7 19. b3 Rcc8 20. d6 Qxd6 21. Nb5 Qd7 22. Qd2 Nbd5
23. Qxa5 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Nxf4 25. Bxf4 Qe6 26. Qa7 Qxb3 27. Qxb7 Qxa4 {1/2-1/2 
(42) Jones,B (2134)-Zaas,P (2250) ICCF email 2014}) (15. h3 Rc4 16. Rd1 Rb4 17.
Qa2 Rc4 18. Be3 Qd7 19. Nd3 Nfxd5 20. Nc5 Qc6 21. Nxd5 Qxd5 {1/2-1/2 (32)
Clark,S (1791)-Grinkevicius,A (2186) ICCF email 2018}) 15... g5 $5 16. Nd3
Nbxd5 17. Rfe1 (17. Bxg5 $6 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Qd5 $1 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rc3] is
the point}) (17. Qxb7 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Nd5 19. Bxg5 Rb8 20. Qa7 (20. Qa6 Nxc3)
20... Ra8 $11) (17. Rae1 h6 18. Bd2 e6 19. Qxb7 Rb8 20. Qa6 Nb4 21. Nxb4 Rxb4 {
0-1 (94) Cross,G (2049)-Zaas,P ICCF email 2012}) 17... h6 {Black regains the
pawn but at a slight cost: the kingside is a bit weakened and White has
queenside pressure. However Black has a powerful central presence. Furthermore,
there are interesting tactics hidden in the position. For example:} 18. Rac1
Nxe3 $5 (18... Rc7 {is more solid}) 19. fxe3 Ng4 $5 {[%cal Gg4e3,Gg7d4] With
tactics in the air such as} 20. h3 $6 (20. Qxb7 $6 Bxd4 $1) 20... Nxe3 21. Rxe3
Bxd4 22. Rce1 Bxe3+ 23. Rxe3 Qd4 $15 {Summary: We have covered the critical 6.
Qb3 and the overarching theme has been piece activity. In many variations we
are down 1 or even 2 pawns but are not the underdogs as our pieces rampage and
stifle White's development. Against 8. g3 we have the powerful e6! gambit.
Against 8. Ne2 we play the aggressive 8..a5 or Na6 intending b5! Finally in
the main line with 8. Be2 I outlined a very precise move order to set White
the maximum difficulties and several hidden traps (such as 13. a5?!). We have
seen that the established main line with 14.. .Qd6 is in trouble, so my
recommended fix is the rare 14.. g5!? or 14...Rc8 intending Rc4-Rb4!} *

