1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {Developing quickly and
putting White's center under pressure. Great move!} 6. Nf3 {White mirrors our
development. This line is normally associated with the "Panov Endgame" which
is acceptable for Black but I have more combatative alternative in mind} Be6 $5
{[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] A rare move that I have used in the past! The idea is to
bolster the center in preparation for a Kingside fianchetto. If White isn't
accurate then his center will be under tremendous pressure.} (6... Bg4 7. cxd5
Nxd5 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nxd4 11. Bb5+ Nxb5 12. Qc6+ Ke7 13. Qxb5
Qd7 14. Nxd5+ Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Be3 Ke6 $11 {is the aforementioned Panov
Endgame}) 7. c5 {The most popular move and the move I've faced the most. White
gains space and moves the c4 pawn out of harms way} (7. cxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Ge7e6,
Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Rd8d4,Rc6d4,Rd5f3] Gives us a very comfortable IQP where we fully
control d5 and can develop with confidence. The IQP is also under pressure.} 8.
Be3 e6 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Qd6 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] 0-1 (31) Simacek,
P (2469)-Navara,D (2706)/ Ostrava CZE 2014/}) (7. Bg5 {This move is also
common and natural: White develops with purpose and fights for the center} g6 {
[%cal Gf8g7]} 8. Bxf6 (8. Be2 $6 {As often happens in the g6 vs IQP setups
slow developing moves are not troublesome as we complete our setup seamlessly}
Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 $2 h6 (10... dxc4 $1) 11. Bf4 dxc4 {Just a freebie! 0-1
(56) Haast,A (2381)-Schandorff,L (2500)/Amsterdam NED 2016/}) 8... exf6 {
White has succeeded in damaging our pawn structure. However we did gain the
advantage of the two bishops. White's most common plan here is to close the
game down with c5 to prevent the bishops from utilizing their power. Later he
may try a pawn storm on the queenside. White also has an argument that our Be6
is quite poor. However we will argue that the Be6 is a terrific defender of
the center and our two bishops is our longterm trump! We will make sure they
make their prescence felt with a kingside pawn storm!} 9. c5 (9. a3 {This
example of a kingside storm caught my eye:} Bg7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O f5 12. Rc1
Rc8 (12... dxc4 $17) 13. b4 a6 14. c5 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4]} 15. b5 axb5 16. Bxb5
g4 (16... f4) 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Ne5 f6 19. Nd3 Bh6 20. Ra1 Rb8 21. Ne2 Bc8 $1 {
[%cal Gc8a6,Gh6c1]} 22. Nef4 Re8 23. Re1 Re4 24. Nh5 Kf7 25. Nb4 Qe8 26. g3 Kg6
27. Nf4+ Bxf4 28. gxf4 Qd7 29. Qd2 Qc7 30. Rac1 Ra8 31. Rc3 Bd7 32. Rxe4 fxe4
33. Rb3 h5 {[%csl Ga8,Gc6,Gd5,Gd7,Ge4,Gg4,Gg6,Gh5]} 34. Nc2 h4 35. Kf1 Bc8 36.
Ke1 Ba6 37. h3 Bc4 38. Rc3 Rb8 39. Nb4 f5 40. Kd1 Kf6 41. Kc1 Rg8 42. Nc2 g3
43. fxg3 hxg3 44. Ne3 Bd3 45. Rb3 Ke6 46. Ng2 Bf1 47. Ne3 g2 {0-1 (47) Svidler,
P (2751)-Kulaots,K (2571)/Tallinn EST 2016/}) (9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Bb5 Bb4 (10...
Bh6 $5) 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Ba4 Rc8 14. Bb3 Na5 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Gb7b5] 0-1 (48) Ruck,R (2562)-Kreisl,R (2420) Zalakaros 2015}) (9. Qb3 Bb4 (
9... a6 $5 {[%cal Gc6a5]})) 9... a6 $5 {A rare idea but one we've seen before.
Black is fighting to keep the Nc6 alive!} (9... Bg7 {is the main line} 10. Bb5
(10. h3 O-O 11. Bb5 h5 $5 12. O-O g5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg5g4,Gf6f5] 1/2-1/2 (28)
Flores,D (2586)-Ortiz Suarez,I (2598) Cochabamba 2013}) 10... Bg4 $5 (10... O-O
{[%cal Ge6g4]} 11. h3) 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. Qe3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 f5 14. O-O-O Qh4 15.
f4 Rd8 16. Kb1 h5 17. Rd2 Bh6 18. Ne2 Kg7 19. Qg3 Qf6 20. Rhd1 Rhe8 21. Ba4 Re4
22. Bc2 h4 23. Qf3 Rxe2 24. Qxe2 Bxf4 25. Rd3 Bxh2 $44 {0-1 (38) Vayser,V 
(2580)-Zhak,B (2556) ICCF email 2009}) 10. Be2 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 f5 {
[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4,Gg7d4]} (12... g5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg5g4,Gf6f5]}) 13.
Qd2 h6 14. Rad1 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4] Blacks main plan is to disturb the Nf3 to
target d4 but sometimes it is even possible to play f4 to open up the Be6.} 15.
Rfe1 g4 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 d4 $1 {Making sure the open kingside is not a
problem as the queens come off} 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Bxe5 {[%cal Ge5b2,Ge6b3]
An exemplary showcase of Black's main ideas. The bishops are liberated and
White's center has fallen. Black ends up grinding away:} 20. Rb4 Bxc3 $5 21.
bxc3 Rfc8 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Rc5]} 22. Rxb7 Rxc5 23. Rc1 Rac8 24. Bxa6 Rxc3 25.
Rxc3 Rxc3 26. Rb1 Rxa3 27. Bf1 Kg7 {0-1 (46) Mchedlishvili,M (2639)-Dominguez
Perez,L (2726)/Leon 2012/}) (7. Ng5 $6 {Looks tempting but just misplaces the
Knight} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gh7h6]} 8. f3 Bc8 $1 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gh7h6] A clever
switchback. White's position is ruined because of the provoked f-pawn and he
now has to worry about h6 as well as the center collapsing} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. f4
e6 11. a3 Be7 12. Nf3 O-O 13. Bd3 Bf6 14. Bc2 {0-1 (44) Bakalchuk,J (2471)
-Serarols Mabras,B (2363) Skopje 2019} Qb6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) (7. Qb3 $5 {
A rare but challenging idea seen in GM games that is actually based on a queen
sacrifice. Black scores well here but the positions are underexplored} dxc4 (
7... Na5 8. Qb5+ $1 {is White's amazing idea after which we don't seem to get
enough compensation} Bd7 9. cxd5 $1 e6 (9... Bxb5 $6 10. Bxb5+ Nd7 11. Ne5) 10.
Qe2 Bb4 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Qb5+ Nc6) 8. Qxb7 Rc8 $5 (8... Na5 9. Qb5+ Bd7 10.
Qe5 Bc6 11. Be2 e6 12. Qg3 Be7 13. O-O O-O {1/2-1/2 (57) Kantans,T (2482)
-Fridman,D (2620) Riga 2016}) 9. Qb5 $146 a6 $5 10. Qxa6 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 {
[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] If we can successfully play g6-bg7 and castle White will
face trouble on the open queenside files}) 7... g6 {Our plan will be centered
around putting pressure on d4. This will be achieved by (hopefully) playing:
Bg7, Bg4, Ne4 or Nd7-e5!} (7... a6 $5 {A rare move designed to combat Bb5.
Play may proceed:} 8. h3 g6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Bc2 O-O 11. O-O b6 $5 {Challenging
the space advantage} 12. Ba4 Na5 13. b4 Nc4 14. Bc2 $6 a5 $1 $17 {[%csl Yc4]
[%cal Ga8a1,Gg7a1] 0-1 (23) Ootes,L (2315)-Pavlovic,M (2534)/Biel 2010/}) 8.
Bb5 {[%csl Rd4] The most popular idea. White puts pressure on the Nc6 in order
to safeguard d4.} (8. h3 {[%cal Re6g4] A logical idea to prevent a future Bg4.
However there are other plans to pressure the center} Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O
Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1] A key key key KEY idea to remember! The centralized
knight is powerful on it's own but also opens up the scope for the Bg7 as well
as potential f-pawn marches.} 11. Bb5 Qc7 12. Be3 Nxc3 $1 13. bxc3 b6 $1 14.
cxb6 axb6 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Ga8a1,Gc6a5,Ga5c4] A nice idea from Black. He
has allowed White to fortify the d4 pawn but in return gains the targets on c3
and a2 plus an outpost on c4.} 15. a4 Na5 16. Rc1 Nc4 $15 {0-1 (32) Stisis,Y 
(2370)-Navara,D (2725)/Tallinn EST 2016/}) 8... Bg7 9. O-O {A thematic example
on the effectiveness of an e5 pawn break:} (9. Ne5 $1 {White's most resolute
plan. He needs immediate action! His dream is to completely control the center
by shutting out the Bg7 and snuffing out the e5 break. However after doing
some analysis I realized it's very difficult for White to keep our potential
under wraps....even with best play} Bd7 10. Be3 (10. Nxd7 $6 {Grabbing the
bishop is senseless as we often want to play Bg4-Bxf3 to eliminate this knight
controlling the center!} Nxd7 {[%csl Rd4]} 11. Be3 (11. Nxd5 {collapses
white's center} O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nc3 e5 (13... Qa5 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal
Gf8d8,Ge7e5]})) 11... e6 12. Qa4 Ndb8 $5 (12... Qc7) 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1 Ne7
$1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6,Ge7f5]} 15. Bf4 Nf5 16. Ne2 a6 17. Rac1 Qh4 18. Bg3
Qg5 19. Bf4 Qh4 20. Bg3 Qg5 21. Rc3 Qh5 22. Rd2 Nxd4 $1 23. Nxd4 Bxd4 24. Rxd4
axb5 25. Qxa8 Nc6 26. Qxf8+ Kxf8 $19 {0-1 (39) Sermek,D (2520)-Cvorovic,D 
(2435)/ Makarska 1994/}) (10. Bxc6 Bxc6 $1 {[%cal Gf6d7] Necessary to setup
our resource of Nd7} 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Nd7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 14.
Qa4 e6 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. Rab1 Re8 17. Bd6 e5 18. Ne2 a5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nd4 Qg4
21. Qd1 Qxd4 22. Qxd4 Nf3+ 23. gxf3 Bxd4 $15 {0-1 (68) Brkic,A (2575)
-Lupulescu,C (2634)/Legnica POL 2013/}) (10. Qa4 {Adds pressure to the pin but
we can absorb it} Qc8 (10... Rc8 $5 {An interesting sacrifice} 11. Bxc6 Bxc6
12. Qxa7 (12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qxa7 Nd7 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5]}) 12... Nd7 $146 (
12... Ra8 13. Nxc6 Qc8 14. Qb6 bxc6 $44 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6d7,Ge8g8,Ge7e5]})
13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ne2 O-O 15. O-O e5 $44) 11. O-O a6 12. Nxd7 (12. Bxc6 Bxc6
13. Qb3 O-O 14. Re1 Re8 15. h3 Qf5 16. Re3 {1/2-1/2 (40) Lomineishvili,M (2366)
-Batsiashvili,N (2438) Anaklia 2012} Ne4 $1 17. Rf3 Qe6 18. Nxf7 Rf8 $44) 12...
Qxd7 13. Be2 O-O (13... Ng8 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg8h6,Gh6f5]}) 14. Rd1 Rad8 15.
Be3 Ng4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Potkin,V (2626)-Riazantsev,A (2682) Irkutsk 2010}) (
10. O-O Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne4 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Nxe4 (13. Nxd5 Rd8 $15) 13... dxe4
$11) 10... O-O 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Nxd5 Ndb8 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 13. Bc4 e6 14. Nc3
Nxd4 15. O-O Nbc6 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4][%cal Gg7a1] 0-1 (58) Shengelia,D (2573)
-Fridman,D (2661)/Aix-les-Bains 2011/}) 9... O-O 10. Re1 (10. h3 Ne4 $1 11. Be3
h6 $5 12. Rc1 g5 13. Qa4 Qc7 14. Rfd1 f5 $36 {0-1 (42) Stojanovski,D (2454)
-Sedlak,N (2547) Mali Losinj 2017}) 10... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {
[%csl Gc6,Gd5][%cal Ga8b8] White has alleviated some of the pressure against
d4 but in return granted us the open b-file and a bolstered center} 12. h3 Bxf3
13. Qxf3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gg7a1] Achieveing e5 will give Black a central
superiority, open up the Bg7, and weaken c5} 14. Bg5 Re8 15. Rad1 Rb8 16. Qe2
Qc8 17. Qd2 e5 18. Be3 Qb7 {Using the b-file combined with central
breakthroughs} 19. b3 exd4 20. Bxd4 Qb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d4,Gb4c5,Gb4e1]} 21. Rxe8+
Rxe8 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Na4 Qxd2 24. Rxd2 Re1+ 25. Kh2 a5 26. Nb6 Nf8 27. Rc2
Ne6 28. f3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black has the preferable structure and the more
active pieces.} 29. Kg3 Rf1 30. Nd7 g5 31. Kh2 h4 32. g3 Nd4 33. Rb2 hxg3+ 34.
Kxg3 Rxf3+ 35. Kg2 Rc3 {0-1 (35) Skawinski,A (2367) -Piorun,K (2676)/Poland
POL 2016/  Summary: 5..Nc6 can often lead to an endgame after 6. Nf3 but not
after our rarer idea of Be6!? White needs to decide how to handle the central
tension: Bg5!? is aggressive but after g6! White may find the bishop pair too
troublesome. The obvious cxd5 offers us an easy IQP after Bxd5 so therefore 7.
c5 is best. Now our best is to play with g6 and Bg7. Main ideas here are Bg4
and Ne4/Nd7 too break with e5 and pressure d4} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Panov Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "5...Nc6 6. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "40"]
[EventDate "2014.04.30"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {Developing quickly and
putting White's center under pressure. Great move!} 6. Bg5 {The modern
aggressive preference where White puts our center under counterpressure!} Ne4
$5 {A rare idea I had prepared for the US Junior Championship back in 2014.
With the incoming exchange on e4 the game will take a turn for the unusual as
we have nothing developed yet it is our opponent who will feel uncomfortable
with his naked king!} 7. Nxe4 {By far the most common} (7. cxd5 {Is natural
and should be checked as well} Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qxd5 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 9. Nf3 Bg4 10.
Qb3 Bxf3 (10... e6) 11. gxf3 O-O-O 12. Rb1 Rd7 $1 13. Qxd5 Rxd5 14. Be3 e6 {
A complex fight arises where White has two bishops and queenside prospects but
a tattered pawn structure.} 15. Bc4 Rh5 16. Ke2 Bd6 {0-1 (54) Tomczak,J (2561)
-Kovalenko,I (2653)/Wroclaw POL 2014/}) 7... dxe4 {[%csl Ge4] We now enter
fertile territory where at first glance our play looks completely ludicrous...
yet paradoxically brings success! For now it is worthwhile to take note of the
cramping effect of the e4 pawn which stymies Whites development. With the
kingside immobilized the Ke1 must stay in the center for a bit...and the
queenside, with the open files, is not welcoming either. Meanwhile our pieces
are surprisingly spry with ideas like Bf5 or Qb6/Qa5 and e6-Bb4 coming fast.}
8. d5 (8. Ne2 {Does not look tidy but resulted in an interesting and
well-played draw:} Bg4 9. Qc2 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Rc2a4,Gg4f5]} 10. a3 Bxe2 11.
Bxe2 Nxd4 12. Qxe4 f5 13. Qd3 e5 14. Rd1 g6 15. Bf3 h6 16. Bf6 Bg7 17. Bxg7
Qxg7 18. Bd5 O-O-O 19. f4 g5 20. fxe5 Qxe5+ 21. Kd2 Ne6 22. Qc3 Qxc3+ 23. Kxc3
Nf4 24. Rhe1 {1/2-1/2 (24) Dann,M (2482)-Braun,A (2585)/ Boeblingen GER 2016/})
(8. Be3 {is a prime example of how uninspired play can lead to supreme trouble
for White's king} e5 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4]} 9. d5 Nd4 10. Bxd4 $6 exd4 11. Qxd4 Bb4+
12. Kd1 O-O $17 {[%csl Rd1]}) 8... Ne5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Gd8b6,Gd8a5]
As outlined above, Black's game is shocking dynamic. Left alone we will aim
for developing moves such as Bf5 or g6-Bg7. White is well advised to act
quickly and try to deal with the annoying e4/Ne5 combo} 9. Qd4 {[%cal Rd4e5,
Rd4e4]} (9. Rc1 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] The following very impressive performance is
a great example of how to play when White isn't bothering us:} 10. c5 Bg7 11.
Qa4+ Bd7 12. c6 $6 {Very brave considering White isn't developed at all!
Foolish even} bxc6 13. dxc6 Nxc6 14. Rxc6 O-O 15. Qxe4 Bxc6 16. Qxc6 Qa5+ 17.
Bd2 Qxa2 18. Bd3 Rad8 19. Ke2 Rd6 20. Qc4 Qa1 21. Qc1 Re6+ 22. Kf3 Qa4 23. Qc4
Qd1+ {0-1 (23) Oral,T (2513)-Sjugirov,S (2664)/St Petersburg RUS 2014/}) 9...
f6 $1 {Very ugly but the position demands it! We maintain our central knight
and get some tempi out of the Bg5.} 10. Qxe4 {This was White's goal all along.
It turns out we are playing a gambit} (10. Bf4 Ng4 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] is a
shocking strike. White can't stop the liberating e5 which frees up our pieces
to attack!} 11. Qxe4 e5 12. dxe6 $2 (12. Bd2 Bc5 13. Nh3 Qb6 {[%csl Gb6,Gc5,
Gg4] With the e5 strike all of our pieces are quickly jumping into action and
in games White was completely unable to cope vs the activity.} 14. O-O-O Bxf2
15. Qf3 (15. b4 $2 {The position gives room to a lot of creativity but
weakening the queenside structure so much is still too much!} Qd4 16. Qxd4 Bxd4
17. Bd3 a5 18. Rhe1 axb4 19. Bxb4 Rxa2 $19 {0-1 (25) Degraeve,J (2555)-Le Roux,
J (2546)/ Montpellier FRA 2015/}) 15... Bd4 16. Bc3 {0-1 (51) Ter Sahakyan,S 
(2572)-Sjugirov,S (2643)/Martuni ARM 2014/} Bc5 $1 $17 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8d7,
Gf6f5]}) 12... Bb4+ 13. Ke2 Qb6 {[%csl Re2]}) (10. c5 {is an example of an
opening disaster from a Grandmaster:} Bf5 11. Bb5+ Kf7 12. Ne2 $4 a6 13. Bc4 (
13. Ba4 Nd3+ {[%cal Gf6g5]}) 13... Nxc4 14. Qxc4 fxg5 {0-1 (32) Sulskis,S 
(2550)-Kovalenko,I (2615) /Liepaja LAT 2014/}) (10. Bd2 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6]
Quiet play allows us to save the disruptive e4 pawn and poses an issue for
White's development}) 10... Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6f2,Re7e6]} 11. O-O-O {In an
effort to develop and safeguard the queenside White has been lured into
castling long. However the king will now face a vicious attack!} (11. b3 e6 {
[%cal Gf8b4]} 12. Bd2 (12. Be3 Bb4+ 13. Kd1 Bc5) 12... Bc5 13. O-O-O exd5 14.
cxd5 g6 $17 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ga8c8,Gc5a3]} (14... O-O $17)) (11. Bd2 Qxb2 12. Rb1
Qxa2 13. Rd1 g6 14. f4 Bf5 15. Qd4 Nd7 16. Nf3 {0-1 (50) Babikov,I (2259)
-Houska,J (2397) Stockholm 2017} e5 $1 {thematic} 17. dxe6 (17. fxe5 fxe5 18.
Nxe5 $4 Bg7) 17... Bxe6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd7c5,Ge8c8,Ge8f7]}) 11... Qxf2 $5 {
[%cal Gc8f5] greedy but also prepares Bf5} (11... g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Preparing
to station an absolute sniper on f5. However computer analysis shows White may
be doing well here} 12. Be3 (12. f4 $6 Bf5 13. Qd4 Nxc4 $3 {Is a key resource
in these lines! The slow sac provides us with the open c-file which will
ensure us regaining material} 14. Bxc4 Rc8 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc8c1]}) 12... Qa5
13. Nf3 $1 $146 {The computer screams for White to get his development going!
The position is very sharp and I tried to figure out what's happening here} (
13. f4 Bf5 $1 14. Qd4 Nxc4 $1 {They key follow up! Now this sac is even more
pleasing since we don't even gain the material back immediaetly} 15. Bxc4 Rc8 {
[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga5a2,Gb7b5,Yf5b1,Ya5e1]}) 13... Bf5 14. Qd4 Nxf3 15. gxf3 Qxa2
{[%cal Gf5b1,Ga2b1]} 16. Bd3 (16. c5 $5 {is also a problem}) 16... Rc8 17. Kd2
$3 {A fantastic idea to run the king away from the attack. Incredibly with a
series of only moves White is winning so Qxf2 should be preferred over g6} (17.
c5 e5 $1 $11 18. dxe6 Rxc5+ 19. Qxc5 Bxc5 20. Bb5+ Kf8 21. Bh6+ Ke7 22. Rd7+
Ke8 23. Rdd1+ Ke7 24. Rd7+ $11) (17. d6 $5 exd6 18. Qxf6 Bxd3 19. Rxd3 Rxc4+
20. Kd1 Qa1+ 21. Ke2 Rc2+ 22. Rd2 Qa6+ 23. Kd1 Rxd2+ 24. Bxd2 Qa1+ 25. Ke2 Qa6+
26. Kd1 Qa4+ $11) 17... Bxd3 (17... e5 18. Qc3) 18. Kxd3 $1 b5 19. c5 e5 20.
Qe4 Qxb2 21. Rd2 Qa3+ 22. Ke2 Bxc5 23. d6 $1 Bxd6 24. Qb7 $18) 12. Bf4 (12. Be3
Bf5 13. Bxf2 Bxe4 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8h6] 1/2-1/2 (40) Kroeze,F (2389)
-Schneider,I (2487) Germany 2020}) 12... g6 13. Nh3 (13. Bxe5 $4 Bh6+ $19 14.
Bf4 Bxf4+ 15. Kb1 Bf5 {0-1 (17) Van Foreest,J (2225)-Van Delft,M (2395)
Hoogeveen 2012}) (13. Ne2 $146 {Computer novelty and computer lines:} Bf5 14.
Qd4 Ng4 15. Qd2 (15. Qc3 e5 $1 16. h3 Bh6 $1 17. Bxh6 Nxh6 18. Ng3 Rc8 $13)
15... Rc8 16. Nc3 Qxd2+ 17. Rxd2 e5 18. dxe6 Bxe6 $11) 13... Qb6 14. Bxe5 (14.
Be3 $2 Qa5 15. c5 Bf5 16. Qd4 Qxa2 17. Bb5+ Kf7 18. Ng5+ fxg5 19. Rhf1 Bg7 20.
d6 Qa1+ 21. Kd2 Qa5+ 22. Kc1 Qxb5 23. dxe7 Nd3+ {0-1 (23) Richter,L (2020)
-Prohaszka,P (2567) Dresden 2013}) (14. Qe3 Bf5 15. Nf2 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 {1/2-1/2
(40) Babujian,L (2484)-Harutjunyan,G (2444) Yerevan 2014} Qxe3+ 17. Bxe3 Rc8
18. Rd4 b5 $15) 14... Bf5 15. Qe1 fxe5 16. Bd3 e4 17. Bc2 Bh6+ 18. Kb1 O-O 19.
Bxe4 Bg7 20. Rd2 {1/2-1/2 (52) Navara,D (2706)-Buhmann,R (2567) Belfort 2012}
Bc3 $17 {Summary: 6. Bg5 is an aggressive move that we will meet with the
equally rare and aggressive Ne4!? The idea is to get an annoying e4 thorn
after the knight trade. Often this pawn will be lost but give us important
tempi such as f6/Bf5. We have seen instances of opening disasters for White as
the position is very unusual and sharp, but the same may happen to us as well!
Some of these lines require memorization, such as the greedy 11..Qxf2!? idea.
However you will do well to know the key break of e5! and try to activate the
pieces with Bf5/Rc8} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pseudo-Panov"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B11"]
[Annotator "Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.05.09"]

1. e4 c6 2. c4 {This is called the "Pseudo-Panov" It can transpose into the
Panov but usually White will want to throw in a disruptive check} d5 3. cxd5 (
3. exd5 {a little inaccurate} Nf6 $1 4. dxc6 $2 (4. Nc3 cxd5 {This will lead
to transpositions seen below} 5. d4 (5. cxd5 Nxd5)) 4... Nxc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]
Our development and center more than compensate for the pawn! For example:} 5.
Nf3 e5 6. d3 e4 $1 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nxe4 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ge8c8,Gf8c5,Gc6b4]
Even though the queens are off our intiative is raging!}) 3... cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6
5. Qa4+ {Being disruptive is White's idea} (5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. Nc3 a6 7. Qa4 {
consistent. Otherwise come moves like b5-Bb7 and d5 falls.} Rb8 $1 8. Bxd7+
Qxd7 (8... Bxd7 {is also possible} 9. Qf4 (9. Qb3 e6 $5) 9... b5) 9. Qxd7+ (9.
Qf4 Ra8 $15 {[%cal Gf6d5]}) 9... Bxd7 {White is up a pawn but it will require
constant protection. Black has the two bishops and queenside play. This
position has been known to be good for Black based on the following older game:
} 10. d3 (10. d4 b5 11. a3 Bc8 $1 $44 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d8]}) 10... Bf5 11. Bg5
Rd8 12. Bxf6 exf6 13. O-O-O Bc5 14. d4 Bd6 15. Nge2 Rc8 16. Kd2 Kd7 17. Rc1 Rc4
$44 {The bishops on the open board in conjuction with the active rooks gives
Black plenty of compensation. The central extra pawns seem impressive but are
currently a liability that need constant defense} 18. h3 Re8 19. g3 h5 20. h4
Bg4 21. a3 b5 22. Kd3 g5 23. Rce1 Bf5+ 24. Kd2 b4 25. axb4 Rxb4 26. Kc1 Reb8
27. Nd1 Bg6 28. hxg5 fxg5 29. Nec3 Rxd4 30. Ne3 a5 31. Nc2 Rc4 32. Re3 a4 33.
Rd1 Bc5 34. Rf3 g4 35. Re3 Rb3 {0-1 (35) Lerner,K (2530) -Dreev,A (2560)/
Rostov on Don 1993/}) (5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 g6 $5 {is simplest to keep theme
with our Panov lines. The position transposes after d4 but White can try} 7.
Qb3 (7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb3 Bg7 9. d4 {TR to 6. cxd5 Panov}) 7... Nb6 8. Bb5+ $5 {
I faced this approach once, White is trying his best to create conflict before
Black castles} Bd7 9. Ne5 {White's threats look scary but we can absorb the
pressure and counter the isolani} e6 10. Ne4 (10. d4 Nc6) 10... Be7 11. O-O (
11. d4 Nc6 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Be3 O-O $11) 11... O-O 12. d3 Bxb5 13. Qxb5 Qd5
$15 {0-1 (58) Itkin, David (2243) -Ostrovskiy, Aleksandr (2401) Chicago Open
2018}) 5... Nbd7 (5... Bd7 $6 6. Qb3 {is worth avoiding. The bd7 is misplaced
as we can't develop or attack d5 so easily.}) 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 (7. Bc4 a6) 7...
Bg7 8. Bc4 (8. Qb3 {is a sideline I faced before. White wants to be able to
meet a6 with a4 and not lose time with Qa3 like in the main line. I managed to
show a very imaginative way to handle this:} O-O 9. Bc4 a6 10. a4 Qa5 $5 {
[%csl Ra1][%cal Gb7b5]} 11. Ra3 Nb6 12. O-O Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Bf5 14. Nd4 Rac8 15.
Qe2 Bg4 16. Qxe7 Qb6 17. Nc2 Rfe8 18. Qb4 Qxb4 19. Nxb4 Bf5 $44 {[%cal Ga6a5]
I had gone for this position down two pawns! However White is completely
bottled in and the threat is a5 to further crush his coordination. White
desperately tries to give up mateiral to develop:} 20. d6 Rcd8 21. d4 Rxd6 $15
{0-1 (30) Hua, D (2304)-Ostrovskiy, A (2410)/Rockville USA 2014/}) 8... O-O 9.
d3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 10. Qa3 (10. O-O $4 b5 11. Bxb5 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6a8]}) 10...
Nb6 $5 (10... b6 {The main line is also totally fine} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Re8 {
[%cal Gb6b5,Gd7b6] And practice has shown that White doesn't have anything
special to meet the obvious b5+Nb6}) 11. Qb3 Nxc4 12. dxc4 {This looks like it
makes no sense for Black since we just helped White's pawn structure. The
actual idea is to grab the pair of bishops and blow the board open!} b5 $1 13.
O-O (13. cxb5 $6 Nxd5 $1 {Gives the advantage to Black on the account of the
bishops and the immense pressure against White's queenside} 14. Nxd5 Be6 $15)
13... bxc4 14. Qxc4 e6 15. Bg5 (15. dxe6 Bxe6 16. Qh4 Nd5 (16... Nh5 $5 {
[%cal Rc1h6]}) 17. Bg5 Qb6) 15... h6 $1 (15... exd5 16. Qh4 {was how my game
went, but I would improve with 15..h6} Bb7 17. Rad1 Re8 18. Qb4 Qd7 $11 {
1-0 (50) Zherebukh,Y (2625)-Ostrovskiy,A (2410)/ Rockville USA 2014/}) 16. Bxf6
Qxf6 {The two bishops and queenside files compensate the pawn and give Black
positive chances.} 17. Rfe1 Rb8 {0-1 (49) Trent,L (2470)-Arkell,K (2506)/
Liverpool 2008/  Summary: The Pseudo-Panov is characterized by White's early
Bb5/Qa4 checks. Bb5 doesn't seem to be dangerous at all as White will often
give the bishop up and give us permanent compensation for the pawn. 5. Qa4+ is
more annoying and after we fianchetto with g6-Bg7 we can either choose my plan
of Nb6-Nxc4 b5!? or the slower main line of B6-Bb7-b5-Nb6 to regain the d5 pawn
} *

