1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8f6] A very classical Caro move,
bringing the bishop outside the pawn chain. However White plans to harrass it}
(3... a6 {A shortcut for an easy to play position} 4. d4 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 (5...
Bh5 6. g4 {is dangerous}) 6. Qxf3 e6 $14 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7] Very solid but
White does have the bishops and center. Black's play is fairly obvious though
and if White closes the center with e5 then c5/b5 ideas become stronger}) (3...
Nf6 {A more combatative line that is facing a big new challenge} 4. e5 Ne4 5.
Ne2 $1 (5. d4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 e6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gd8a5] damages White's structure
and leads to a good game}) 5... Qb6 6. d4 e6 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 Nxg3 9. fxg3 $1 {
This new aggressive idea is putting a lot of pressure on this variation. We
will examine if Black can hold the pressure after} cxd4 10. O-O $44 {[%cal
Gb8c6,Gc8d7,Gf8e7,Ga7a6,Gh7h6]}) (3... dxe4 {A good choice if you play the
tartakower vs the classical} 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 $1 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Nd7 {This move
used to be considered dubious since it leads to a "trap"} (6... Qa5 {[%cal
Gc8f5,Ga5f5]}) (6... Qd5) 7. Bc4 Nf6 8. Ne5 {A cool idea but after} e6 9. Qe2
b5 10. Bb3 Qc7 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8b7] Black gets a queenside intiative and can
develop while preparing a future c6-c5}) 4. h3 Bxf3 (4... Bh5 $5 {[%cal Ge7e6]
Trying to keep the bishop alive is ambitious. The plan is e6/Nf6 but White can
get aggressive} 5. g4 $1 Bg6 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Bb5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 10.
Qe2 $1 (10. h4 {is most popular but leads to a complex position after} f6 11.
Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qd3 Kf7 $44 {The king is actually pretty safe while the h and c
files offer us good play}) 10... Bb4 (10... Bd6 {Sacrifices the pawn for some
compensation} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Nxd5 $14) 11. h4 Nge7 {The position is sharp
but if Whtie knows all the right moves most likely we get an endgame} 12. h5
Be4 13. f3 O-O 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Be3 Qf6 16. fxe4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rd1
Bxc3+ 19. bxc3 Qxc3+ 20. Kf1 dxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxc2 22. Qxc2 Rxc2 $14 {Black can
draw by liquidating the queenside pawns and a pair of rooks. Then the kingside
can be fortressed}) 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2 (6. d3 g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8e7] same as
main line}) (6. d4 $5 {is ambitious and could be a sacrfice after} Nf6 7. Bd3
dxe4 8. Nxe4 Qxd4 $44 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5]}) 6... g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8e7,
Gb8d7] Setting up a super light square blockade and aiming for Bg7/Ne7/Nd7 and
later queenside play with b5 and/or d4} *

