1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {Nf6 has had a reputation as a fighting and
complex option for Black. However White has found a very challenging idea vs
Nf6 that puts this line under pressure} 4. e5 (4. exd5 $6 {is the type of move
a surprised or low rated opponent might favor but exchanging the central e4
pawn off the board can not be right. Now after} cxd5 5. d4 Bg4 {[%cal Gb8c6,
Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Ga8c8] Black's development is very simple and also very
solid. In the middle game we will likely focus on queenside play because we
have the semi-open c-file.}) 4... Ne4 5. Ne2 {This surprising retreat is
White's best option! The idea is to play d3 and chase it away....or trap it!} (
5. d3 {This option is rather meek. We will double White's pawns and have a
French Winawer type position without giving up our Bf8.} Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. d4
Nc6 (7... e6 {Showcases how Black play this position like French Winawer but
exploit the lack of trading his Bf8!} 8. Bd3 c4 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 9. Be2 Be7
10. O-O Nc6 11. Ne1 Qa5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga5a2,Ga5c3] A great spot for the
queen to target White's weak pawns.} 12. Bd2 Bd7 13. f4 O-O-O 14. a4 Kb8 15.
Nf3 f6 $1 {Black has locked up the queenside so that the king can rest easy
there and now he will attack on the kingside.} 16. Qe1 Qc7 17. Qg3 Rdg8 18. Kh1
Ka8 19. Rfe1 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 20. Bf1 f5 21. Qg6 Nd8 $1 22. Bc1 Be8 {The
flimsy bind is broke and after g5 Black's attack will be tremendous. Meanwhile
White has no play and the queenside pawns will be weak for eternity.} 23. Qg3
g5 {0-1 (47) Al Badani,A (2175)-Lupulescu,C (2660)/ Dubai UAE 2014/}) 8. Be2
Bg4 {It is possbile to also bring the bishop out.} 9. O-O e6 10. h3 Bh5 11. Be3
Be7 12. Nh2 Bg6 13. Bd3 Rc8 14. a3 a6 15. f4 Qa5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga5a3,Ga5c3]}
16. g4 c4 $1 {The position is too closed for White's attack to succeed... in
fact he is overextended. Meanwhile Black is easily targetting all White's pawn
weaknesses.} 17. Bxg6 hxg6 {[%cal Gh8h3,Ga5c3] 0-1 (36) Bengherabi,K (2170)
-Ragger,M (2644)/Tromso NOR 2014/The Week in Chess 1032 (36)}) (5. d4 {can be
similar to 5. d3 above} Nxc3 6. bxc3 e6 7. Bd3 c5 8. O-O c4 $5 9. Be2 Nc6 {
Compare to the Lupulescu game in the notes to 5. d3} (9... Be7) 10. g3 Qa5 {
[%cal Ga5c3]} 11. Qd2 Bd7 12. Nh4 O-O-O 13. f4 Be7 14. Ng2 f6 $1 15. exf6 gxf6
16. Bf3 f5 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gc6e7,Ge7g8,Gg8f6,Gf6e4] Although the game
was drawn here Black had a powerful position. White has queenside weaknesses
and no attack. Meanwhile Black wants to play h5-h4 and possibly later bring
the Nc6 to e4.1/2-1/2 (49) Szamoskozi,G (2322)-Kovacevic,B (2505)/Budapest HUN
2017/}) (5. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 6. Ng5 Qd5 {White is having trouble defending e5 here.
He has to sacrifice it:} 7. d4 (7. Qe2 Bf5) 7... exd3 8. Qxd3 Qxe5+ 9. Be2 {
White has a lead in development but we are very solid and have the extra pawn.
More than fair!} Qf5 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6]} (9... h6 $2 10. Qd8+ $1 {[%cal Gg5f7]
is a fancy trap to avoid})) 5... Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6f2]} 6. d4 {Now there is no
d3 to disturb our Knight.} e6 {[%cal Gc6c5] Left undisturbed we are planning
c5 and Nc6 to put pressure on White's center. However he will try to disturb
us!} 7. Ng3 {doesn't trouble us as it doesn't stop our queenside plan:} (7.
Nfg1 $5 {This wacky retreat tries to play f3 to win a piece} f6 {[%cal Ge4g5]
Preparing an escape square} 8. f3 Ng5 9. exf6 (9. h4 $6 {Was how one of my
games went here:} Nf7 10. f4 {White is trying to build a massive space
advantage with his pawns but this is too ambitious.... it is difficult to
maintain an empire all over the board!} c5 11. c3 Nc6 12. Nf3 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,
Gd7b5]} 13. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White is trying to gain even more space, but each
pawn move weakens a square} Be7 14. g4 cxd4 15. cxd4 Na5 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4]} 16.
b4 Nc4 17. Nc3 Rc8 18. Na4 Qa6 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. bxc5 fxe5 $1 {Time to open up
files and expose the weak squares in White's camp.} 21. fxe5 O-O 22. Qd3 b6 $1
23. cxb6 Qxb6 24. Rb1 Nfxe5 $3 25. dxe5 Nxe5 26. Rxb6 Nxd3+ 27. Bxd3 Rxc1+ 28.
Ke2 Rxh1 {0-1 (40) Proleiko, J (2126)-Ostrovskiy, A (2390)/ Philadelphia USA
2016/}) 9... gxf6 10. f4 Nf7 11. Nf3 e5 $5 {This break leads to very dynamic
play as both kings will be exposed} 12. fxe5 fxe5 13. Ng3 (13. dxe5 {Accepting
the pawn has led to good results for White over a small sample, but the
resulting position is fine for Black:} Bg7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7e5]} 14. Qd4 Qxd4 (
14... Nd7) 15. Nexd4 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. c3 Bg4 (17... O-O {[%cal Gb8d7]})
18. Bh6 Nd7 19. h3 Bh5 20. g4 Bg6 21. Nf5 Bxf5 22. gxf5 Kf7 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gh8g8]
1-0 (69) Rathnakaran,K (2407)-Risting,E (2268)/Graz AUT 2017/}) 13... Be6 (
13... Bg4 $6 14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 (16. Qe2 $1 $16) 16... exd4
17. Nf5 Bb4+ 18. Bd2 Na6 19. O-O-O Bxd2+ 20. Rxd2 O-O 21. Re1 Ng5 22. Nxd4 Nxf3
23. Nxf3 Nc5 {1/2-1/2 (23) Poetsch,H (2484)-Fridman,D (2637) Karlsruhe 2018})
14. dxe5 (14. Be2 Nd7 15. Ng5 Nxg5 16. Bxg5 Be7 17. Bh5+ Kd8 18. Qd2 Qxb2 19.
Bxe7+ Kxe7 20. Qg5+ Kd6 21. dxe5+ Qxe5+ 22. Qxe5+ Nxe5 $19 {0-1 (60)
Dolzhikova,O (2123)-Haug,J (2407) Caleta 2020}) 14... Bc5 15. Nh5 Bf2+ 16. Ke2
Kd8 (16... Nd7 $146 17. Ng7+ Ke7 18. Nxe6 Kxe6 $13) 17. Ng7 Bg4 18. Qd2 Nd7 19.
h3 Bxf3+ 20. gxf3 Rg8 21. Nf5 Ndxe5 22. Kd1 Kd7 23. f4 Nf3 $3 $146 {In this
wild position the computer points out a winning continuation for Black} (23...
Ng6 {1/2 (46)-1/2 (46) Ragger,M (2701)-Moranda,W (2599) Germany 2019}) 24. Qe2
Rae8 25. Qxf3 Re1+ 26. Kd2 Nd6 27. Nxd6 Rg3 $1) 7... c5 8. Bd3 (8. c3 Nc6 9.
Bd3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bd7 12. Kf1 Be7 13. a3 Na5 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4]} 14.
Rb1 Bb5 $1 15. b3 Rc8 16. a4 Bxd3+ 17. Qxd3 h6 18. Bd2 Bb4 19. Qb5+ Qxb5+ 20.
axb5 Bxd2 21. Nxd2 Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c7,Gc7b6]} 22. Ke2 Kc7 23. b4 Nc4 24. Nxc4
dxc4 25. Kd2 Kb6 26. Kc3 Rhd8 27. f4 Rd5 {0-1 (48) Narayanan,S (2474)-Fedoseev,
V (2658)/Moscow RUS 2017/}) 8... Nxg3 9. fxg3 $1 {This modern idea has been a
huge headache for Caro players! White breaks positional rules by capturing
away from the center and looking to use the f-file to launch a huge attack} (9.
hxg3 cxd4 {This gambit is not dangerous. A fun variation here is} 10. Ng5 Nc6
11. Nxh7 Bd7 12. Nf6+ gxf6 13. Rxh8 O-O-O $44 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gf6e5] Where Black
gets huge compensation for the exchange}) 9... cxd4 (9... Nc6 {Unfortunately
for me I was a victim of this fxg3 idea and got completely obliterated!} 10.
O-O h6 11. Kh1 (11. dxc5 Bxc5+ 12. Kh1 $40) 11... cxd4 12. a3 a5 13. g4 Bd7 14.
Qe2 Be7 15. Bd2 O-O-O $4 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Rfb1 Qc5 19. Bxb4 Nxb4
20. Qe1 Nxd3 21. cxd3 Kb8 22. Qf2 Rc8 23. Nxd4 f6 24. Qb2 {1-0 (24) Jacobson,B
(2418)-Ostrovskiy,A (2450) New York 2019}) 10. O-O Nc6 {Black is up a pawn but
behind in development has has a tough task with king safety. The viability of
this variation hinges on if Black can find a good reorganization here} (10...
h6 {I tried this idea in a blitz tournament and later it was also played by
the top Chinese GM Wei Yi. However a very powerful move here completely
refutes Black's concept} 11. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gd1h5] The engine gives White a +4.
5 edge after the coming onslaught of Qh5} (11. a3 Nc6 12. g4 a5 13. h3 Bd7 14.
Kh1 Be7 15. Qe1 O-O-O 16. Bd2 f6 17. b4 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 fxe5 19. Qxe5 Bd6 20. Qe2
a4 {0-1 (22) Van Foreest,J (2601)-Wei,Y (2736) chess.com INT 2019})) 11. Qe2 (
11. a3 {is liable to transpose to Qe2. Some potential move orders:} h6 12. Nh4
$6 {Doesn't work here} (12. b4 a6 (12... Bd7)) 12... Bd7 13. Qh5 O-O-O $1 $17)
11... h6 12. a3 a6 (12... Bd7 13. b4 Be7 14. g4 O-O-O {is a relatively typical
position if Black commits to long castling. In practice he survived but it
still feels very unpleasant} 15. b5 (15. Kh1 $146 {a prophylactic novelty
proposed by the engine} Kb8 16. Bd2 (16. Bb2 Rc8) 16... f6) 15... Na5 16. Bd2
Nc4 17. a4 f6 {A key source of counterplay to distract White and make use of
the (extra) central pawn} 18. Rfb1 Nxd2 19. Qxd2 fxe5 $146 (19... Rhf8 {
0-1 (57) Galperin,P (2462)-Rudolf,M (2328) Zadar 2019}) 20. Nxe5 Be8 {Planning
Qd6/Bf6 and e5}) 13. b4 Be7 {Black will play Be7/Bd7 and see What White's
setup is. White usually goes for a3-b4, Kh1, g4} 14. g4 Bd7 15. Bf4 (15. g5 $1
$36 {is tough to meet} O-O-O (15... hxg5 16. Nxg5) 16. gxh6 f5 $5 (16... gxh6
17. Bd2 {White's attack is dangerous}) 17. hxg7 (17. exf6 $6 gxf6) 17... Rh7 {
Tries to open up some files and gain time and space} 18. Qf2 (18. Bd2 $6 Rxg7
$13 {[%cal Gd8g8]}) 18... Rxg7 19. c3 Rdg8 20. g3 Bd8 (20... Kb8) 21. cxd4 Be8
$44 {[%cal Ge8h5,Gg7c7]}) (15. Rb1 Na7 $5 (15... Rc8) 16. Bb2 Nb5 17. Qf2 Rc8
$146 (17... Qc7 {1/2-1/2 (59) Vachier Lagrave,M (2778)-Nakamura,H (2743) Saint
Louis 2019}) 18. Nxd4 O-O) 15... Na7 16. Qf2 $6 (16. g5) 16... Bb5 17. Nxd4
Bxd3 18. cxd3 O-O 19. Rac1 f6 20. Qe3 Rae8 21. Nf3 Qxe3+ 22. Bxe3 Nc6 23. exf6
Bxf6 $11 {0-1 (66) Patel,A (2478)-Khamrakulov,D (2496) Saint Louis 2018 
Summary: 3..Nf6 can lead to some very complex positions. After the critical e5
Ne4 Ne2 (d3 or d4 lead to improved French type positions for Black) White has
two key ideas: the old idea of 7. Nfg1 which leads to a dynamically balanced
game or 7. Ng3 w/fxg3! Which is very critical. As we saw in the analysis,
White has a strong intiative but perhaps Black can hold solid with a Bd7/Be7/
a6 setup} *

