1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 {This is the most popular and solid response
Black has. I want to show you a new and rare setup in this variation} 4. h3 {
By far White's main idea which strives for the bishop pair} (4. Be2 {If White
tries to develop normally we can continue development with Nf6/e6 and enjoy a
very solid light square structure with the bishop secure outside the pawn
chain. For example:} e6 5. d4 Be7 6. h3 Bh5 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Nd2 Bg6 9. e5 Nfd7 {
A very comfortable structure for Black and after c6-c5 we will have our usual
queenside play following Nc6/Rc8 ideas} 10. O-O c5 {0-1 (37) Stefanovski,D 
(2324)-Tomashevsky,E (2745) Struga 2015}) (4. d4 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h3 Bxf3 7.
Qxf3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] with c5 coming next we have no complaints in this
French like structure}) 4... Bxf3 {Giving up the bishop for solidity. The
riskier Bh5 is also possible} 5. Qxf3 {White gains the 2 bishops but Black is
super solid.} (5. gxf3 $5 {Was made famous by Tal in his match vs Botvinnik.
White aims for an original game as objectively there is no gain to doubling
the pawns (White does wish to use the g-file later however)} e6 6. d4 Nd7 7.
Be3 Ne7 8. Qd2 Ng6 9. O-O-O Be7 10. Bd3 $13 {Bishops vs Knights+structure.
White has gotten an unbalanced and interesting positiong! I found a game where
Black played extremely creatively to get the win} Nh4 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rhg1 Kh8
13. f4 f5 {[%csl Gb7,Gc6,Gd5,Ge6,Gf5]} 14. f3 b5 15. Qf2 Rf7 16. Ne2 Nb6 17.
Kb1 Nc4 18. Bc1 a5 19. Ng3 a4 20. Rde1 a3 21. b3 Bb4 22. Ref1 Nb2 23. Ne2 Be7
24. Qe3 b4 25. Bxb2 axb2 26. Kxb2 c5 27. a4 bxa3+ 28. Ka2 Qb6 29. c3 Ng6 30.
Rb1 cxd4 31. cxd4 Bf8 32. exd5 exd5 33. Nc3 Qd6 34. Rge1 Nxf4 35. Bf1 Re7 36.
Qd2 Qb4 37. Rec1 Rc7 38. Ne4 Qxd2+ 39. Nxd2 Rac8 40. Rxc7 Rxc7 {0-1 (40) Ter
Sahakyan,S (2480)-Berkes,F (2647) Martuni 2009}) 5... e6 6. Be2 {This simple
developing move has been recommended in various recent repertoire works and is
also commonly used by the main practioner of the two knights, Maxime
Vachier-Lagrave} (6. g3 g6 $5 {My proposed setup for Black!} 7. Bg2 (7. d4 {
makes sense to take the center before Bg7} Bg7 8. Be3 Nf6 9. Bg2 (9. e5 Nfd7 {
We will be able to play c6-c5 here}) 9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4 Nd7 $14 {
A common structure that White aims for in the two knights. He has the bishop
pair and more space but Black is solid.} 12. O-O Nf6 13. Qd3 Nd5 14. Bd2 O-O
15. Rfe1 Re8 16. c4 $2 {an instructive mistake that leaves d4 too weak.} Ne7
17. Bc3 Qb6 18. Rad1 Red8 19. Re2 Rd7 20. Red2 Rad8 21. g4 {White tries to
stop Nf5 but allows} Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Rxd4 23. Qxd4 Rxd4 24. Rxd4 {and now Black
plays a key move to gain a large advantage and juicy outposts for the knight}
g5 $1 $19 {0-1 (59) Kurmann,O (2481)-Macovei,A (2328) Heraklion 2017}) 7... Bg7
8. O-O Ne7 9. d3 O-O 10. Bg5 Nd7 11. Rae1 {We will see this flexible setup
from Black in the main line too. Here the idea can be to expand on the center/
queenside} d4 12. Nb1 h6 13. Bc1 c5 14. Qe2 Rc8 15. h4 h5 16. Nd2 b5 17. Bh3 c4
18. Nf3 Qa5 19. a3 Qa4 20. Bg5 Nc6 21. Rc1 c3 22. bxc3 dxc3 23. Ra1 Nde5 24.
Rfc1 Nxf3+ 25. Qxf3 Kh7 26. Be3 a6 27. Kh2 f5 $15 {0-1 (54) Howell,D (2644)
-Mamedyarov,S (2768) Doha 2016}) (6. d4 $5 {Taking the center immediaetly is
actually proposing a pawn sacrifice} Nf6 (6... a6 {Transposes to the chapter
on a6 vs two knights but in the present position we can do better}) 7. Bd3 (7.
e5 Nfd7 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 7... dxe4 {accepting the pawn! We do need to be
careful though} (7... Be7 {declines the gambit to complete development}) 8.
Nxe4 Qxd4 9. Be3 {most common and best scoring} (9. c3 Qd8 10. O-O Nxe4 11.
Bxe4 Bd6 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Qd3 Be5 14. Bxh7 Nd7 15. Be4 O-O-O 16. Qf3 Nf6 $11 {
0-1 (64) Yilmazyerli,M (2491)-Svane,R (2595) Heraklion 2017}) (9. O-O Nbd7 {
[%cal Gd7e5]} 10. Be3 Qd5 11. Rfd1 Be7 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. Qg3 Bd6 14. Qh4 Qe5
15. g3 Bc5 16. Bd2 O-O-O $17 {0-1 (35) Vakhlamov,I (2413)-Yuffa,D (2577) Sochi
2019}) 9... Bb4+ $5 {develops and prevents White from castling but also helps
his rooks get in the game} 10. Ke2 Qe5 $5 $146 {a computer novelty to keep the
queen active} (10... Qd8 $44 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) 11. Bf4 Qd5 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 12.
Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Be4 Qc4+ 14. Bd3 Qd5 $11) (6. d3 {may transpose to g3 but also
doesn't stop our setup idea} g6 $5 7. Bd2 (7. g3 Bg7) 7... Bg7 8. g4 Nd7 9. h4
h5 10. g5 Ne7 11. Bh3 b5 $15 {0-1 (36) Tomb,M (2182)-Nyzhnyk,I (2599) chess.
com INT 2018}) 6... g6 $5 {Looking to position the bishop on the influential
long diagonal while erecting a light square barrier} 7. O-O (7. d4 {takes the
center before Bg7 arrives} Bg7 8. Be3 Nf6 9. O-O (9. e5 Nfd7 10. Bd3 c5 $1 $15
{A case where we actually don't need to prevent Nb5} (10... a6 {0-1 (110) Can,
E (2487)-Lenic,L (2623) Aix les Bains 2011}) 11. Nb5 O-O) 9... O-O 10. Rfd1
Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 {We saw this structure after 6. g3 in the notes
above} Nd7 13. c4 {Again this is a common and obvious idea from White to take
space and the center but it also allows us to target the d4 pawn, something
the Bg7 is destined for!} Re8 14. Rac1 Qe7 15. g3 Rad8 16. h4 h5 17. Qc2 Nf6
18. Bf3 Rd7 19. Qe2 Red8 20. Rd2 Qf8 21. Rcd1 Bh6 22. Bxh6 Qxh6 23. Qe5 Qg7 24.
Qg5 Ne8 25. d5 {White panics before Nd6-Nf5 arrives} exd5 26. cxd5 Qf6 27. Qe3
c5 28. d6 Ng7 29. Bg2 b6 30. Qa3 a5 31. Qb3 Rxd6 32. Rxd6 Rxd6 33. Rxd6 Qxd6
34. Bd5 Qf6 35. Qb5 Nf5 36. Qd7 Kg7 37. Qc7 Nh6 38. Kg2 Qxb2 39. a4 Qd4 {
0-1 (39) Ganguly,S (2642)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2624) Dubai 2018}) 7... Bg7 8.
Rd1 (8. d3 Nd7 9. Qg3 Ne7 10. Bd2 O-O 11. Qh4 f5 12. Bg5 Rf7 13. exf5 exf5 14.
Rfe1 Qf8 15. Bf1 Re8 $11 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ge7d5] 0-1 (92) Jones,G (2575)-Ivanchuk,
V (2764) Warsaw 2010}) 8... d4 {This position has been reached 6 times so far
with Black crushing with 5.5/6! Let's see how one of the world's best handles
this structure with Black} 9. Nb1 Ne7 10. d3 c5 11. a4 Nbc6 12. Na3 O-O 13. Qg3
{Black will aim to expand on the queenside and White pins his hopes on some
kingside intiative} a6 14. Bf4 e5 15. Bd2 Rb8 16. Rf1 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. f4
Bh6 (18... f5 $5) 19. Qh4 Bxf4 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Rxf4 Ne5 $17 22. Raf1 N7c6 23.
Qf2 b4 24. Nb1 b3 25. c4 Nb4 26. Qg3 f6 27. Kh2 Qd6 28. Na3 Nc2 29. Nb5 Qe7 30.
R4f2 Ra8 31. Rb1 Ne3 32. Na3 Rf7 33. Re1 Kh8 34. Bf1 Re8 35. Nb1 f5 36. Nd2 Qc7
37. Kg1 f4 {A beautiful case of dark square domination} 38. Qh4 Ref8 39. Be2
Qa5 40. Qg5 Qxd2 41. Qxe5+ Kg8 42. Rb1 Qc2 43. Rbf1 Nxf1 44. Bxf1 Qc1 45. Qxc5
f3 46. g3 Qe3 47. Qd5 h5 48. h4 Kh7 49. Qg5 Ra7 50. Qc5 Ra1 51. Qe7+ Kg8 52.
Qe6+ Kg7 53. Qe7+ Rf7 {0-1 (53) Perez Ponsa,F (2553)-Nakamura,H (2781) Caleta
2018  Summary: 3..Bg4 is the most popular and solid continuation at Black's
disposal but we have added a modern twist with the fianchetto setup. If White
doesn't hunt down our Bishop then we have a very pleasant setup with an
improved French structure and the potential for a future c5 break. We have
also analyzed the riskier 4..Bh5!? which forces White to be very well prepared
to punish us; although some of the resulting complicated positions will still
give us chances} *

