1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 {By far White's main idea which strives
for the bishop pair} (4. Be2 {If White tries to develop normally we can
continue development with Nf6/e6 and enjoy a very solid light square structure
with the bishop secure outside the pawn chain. For example:} e6 5. d4 Be7 6. h3
Bh5 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Nd2 Bg6 9. e5 Nfd7 {A very comfortable structure for Black
and after c6-c5 we will have our usual queenside play following Nc6/Rc8 ideas}
10. O-O c5 {0-1 (37) Stefanovski,D (2324)-Tomashevsky,E (2745) Struga 2015}) (
4. d4 Nf6 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] with c5 coming
next we have no complaints in this French like structure}) 4... Bh5 $5 {
I looked into this more aggressive continuation where we aim to keep the
bishop. Now unless white plays aggressively with g2-g4 we will be completely
ok with e6-Nf6/Nd7 development. Let's have a look at the critical lines} 5.
exd5 (5. d4 dxe4 (5... e6) 6. Nxe4 Nf6 {is Tartakower-esque}) (5. d3 $5 e6 6.
g4 $5 {is a spin-off on the main line} (6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 $11) 6... Bg6 7.
Qe2 d4 8. Nb1 h5 (8... c5 9. h4 {1/2-1/2 (45) Giri,A (2779)-Nepomniachtchi,I 
(2774) Amsterdam 2019})) 5... cxd5 6. g4 $1 (6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. g4 {TR}) 6... Bg6
7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne5 {White has to play aggressively to punish this variation}
Rc8 9. d4 (9. h4 f6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. d4 e6 $44 {TR}) 9... e6 10. Qe2 $1 {
This is a very important move although it is not the most popular} (10. h4 {
This move looks very obvious and is the most popular but actually leads to an
unclear position} f6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qd3 Kf7 {We've lost castling rights but
the pawn shield and queenside play give us good play} 13. Bxc6 (13. h5 gxh5 14.
gxh5 Nge7 $13 15. Be3 Nf5 16. O-O-O $2 {Is an example of White's natural moves
stumbinlig into a vicious attack} Nb4 17. Qe2 Rxc3 $1 $19 (17... Qa5 $19) 18.
bxc3 Nxa2+ 19. Kb2 Nxc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3e2,Gc3d1,Gc3b5]} 20. Kxc3 Qa5+ 21. Kd3
Qxb5+ 22. Kd2 Bb4+ 23. c3 Bxc3+ 24. Kxc3 Rc8+ 25. Kd2 Qb4+ 26. Kd3 Qc3#) 13...
Rxc6 14. Bd2 (14. h5 gxh5 15. gxh5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf8b4]}) 14... Bb4 15. a3 (
15. O-O-O Ne7 (15... Qa5 16. Kb1 (16. h5 gxh5 17. Rxh5 Rxh5 18. gxh5 Ne7) 16...
Ra6 $13)) 15... Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Qc7 17. h5 Ne7 18. hxg6+ Nxg6 19. Rxh8 Nxh8 20.
g5 f5 21. O-O-O Qf4+ 22. Qd2 Ng6 23. Bb4 b6 24. Re1 Rc4 25. Qxf4 Nxf4 26. Bd6
Nd3+ {0-1 (26) Vovk,I (2299) -Lintchevski,D (2541) Tallinn 2014}) (10. O-O $2 {
I faced this move when I tried out the variation online. However castling
after h3-g4 is very dangerous} Bd6 $17 {0-1 (45) Landaw,J (2318)-Ostrovskiy,A 
(2425) chess.com INT 2020}) 10... Bb4 {The most popular option but with strong
preparation White will be happy to play this line} (10... Bd6 $5 {Since Bb4
leads to a difficult endgame I looked into this pawn sacrifice. It's not fully
sound but Black has had some wins here} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Nxd5 Kf8 (12... Nge7
$5 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. c3 Qd5 15. f3 Bh4+ 16. Kf1 O-O 17. Bxc6 $2 Rxc6 18. Qe4 f5
19. Qxd5 exd5 20. g5 Re6 21. Bf4 Rfe8 22. Be5 Bxg5 23. h4 Bf6 $15 {0-1 (44)
Srbis,J (2425)-Zelcic,R (2509) Split 2018}) 13. Bxc6 Rxc6 14. Ne3 Nf6 15. c3
Bb8 16. Qf3 e5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Qd5 Qe8 19. b3 $2 Bxe5 20. Ba3+ Kg8 21. Rd1 Nf6
22. Qf3 Ne4 23. Kf1 Nxf2 $1 24. Kxf2 Rf6 25. Nf5 gxf5 $17 {0-1 (46) Venkatesh,
M (2517)-Ding,L (2679) Ho Chi Minh City 2012}) 11. h4 Nge7 12. h5 Be4 13. f3
O-O 14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Be3 (15. Bxc6 $6 {Leads to way more complications for
White than the main line} Rxc6 16. fxe4 $2 {This is the wrong way to collect
the bishop} (16. O-O Bxc3 17. bxc3 Rxc3 18. Bd2 (18. fxe4 $2 Rg3+ 19. Kf2 Qh4
20. Bg5 Qh3 21. Ke1 Rxg4) 18... Rxc2 $13) (16. Kd1 Qb6 17. Be3 Ba5 $1 18. Kc1
Bxc2 {[%cal Gf8c8]} 19. Kxc2 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Rxc3+ 21. Kxc3 Rc8+ 22. Kd2 Qb2+ 23.
Ke1 Qxa1+ 24. Qd1 Qxa2 $44) (16. Kf1 f5 $1) (16. Kf2 f5 $1) 16... Rxc3 17. Kf2
Rc6 18. c3 Be7 19. Kg2 $2 (19. e5 f6 $36) 19... dxe4 20. Qxe4 f5 $1 21. gxf5
exf5 22. Qf3 f4 23. Re1 Bd6 24. Re2 Rf5 25. Kf1 Qh4 $19 {0-1 (32) Gabuzyan,H 
(2404)-Harutjunyan,G (2464) Kajaran 2011}) 15... Qf6 (15... e5 $5 {Trying to
confuse the issue but White still comes out on top} 16. Bxc6 Rxc6 17. fxe4 Rxc3
18. bxc3 (18. O-O-O $5 Qa5 $5 (18... Rc4 {Surprisingly leads to material
balance but the open kingside files spell danger for our king} 19. exd5 Qxd5
20. dxe5 Qe4 $14 21. Qd3 Qxg4) 19. bxc3 Bxc3 20. Rd3 Qa3+ 21. Kd1 dxe4 22. Rxc3
Qxc3 $16 {With practical chances for the piece due to White's open king
although White should consolidate the advantage with precise play}) 18... Bxc3+
19. Kf2 exd4 20. Bf4 Bxa1 21. Rxa1 d3 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gf6f4,Gf6a1]} 22. Qe3 dxe4
$16 {Again Black has practical chances due to the exposed White king but the
extra piece is more than worth it}) 16. fxe4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rd1 Bxc3+
19. bxc3 Qxc3+ 20. Kf1 dxe4 {This position has been reached in 30+ games.
White is up a piece for three pawns and has a weak king. At first this looks
pretty good for Black but unfortunately it seems the piece will outweigh the
pawns} 21. Qxe4 Qxc2 (21... f5 {Tries to attack but fails after} 22. Qxe6+ Kh8
23. Kg2 Qxc2+ 24. Qe2 $18) 22. Qxc2 (22. Qe2 $146 Qc5 (22... Rc7)) 22... Rxc2
23. a4 $14 {White has won some and drawn some but never lost. Therefore we can
say that 10.. Bb4 leads to sharp play but with good preparation White can
achieve an endgame where he plays for two results} a6 24. Be2 Ra2 25. Rd7 Rxa4
26. Rxb7 Ra1+ 27. Kg2 Rxh1 28. Kxh1 h6 29. Bxa6 {This type of endgame has been
reached a couple of times in practice and White was unable to breach it.} Ra8
30. Bc4 Rc8 31. Bb3 Kf8 32. Kg2 Rc3 33. Bd1 Rd3 34. Be2 Rc3 35. Bf3 Ra3 36. Kg3
Ra4 37. Kf2 Ra3 38. Rc7 Rb3 39. Ra7 Rc3 40. Ke2 Rb3 41. Be4 Rc3 42. Bd3 Rc5 43.
Ke3 Re5+ 44. Kf4 Rd5 45. Be4 Rc5 46. Bh7 Rc4+ 47. Kg3 Rc3+ 48. Kh2 Rc8 49. Kg2
Rb8 50. Kf2 Rb2+ 51. Ke3 Rb3+ 52. Kd2 Rb4 53. Ra8+ Ke7 54. Bg8 Rb7 55. Ke3 Kf6
56. Kf4 g5+ 57. hxg6 Kxg6 58. Re8 Rb4+ 59. Kg3 Kg7 60. Kf3 Ra4 {½-½ (60)
Solodovnichenko,Y (2587)-Magalashvili,D (2488) Konya 2016  Conclusion: 4..Bh5
is ambitious since we want avoid giving up the bishop pair. White must play
actively to punish us with the key idea being g2-g4! On move 10 we have a
diversion: 10. h4 is more popular historically but leads to a complex fight
while 10. Qe2! is more problematic where White saves h4 for a better moment.
Now our choice is either to speculatively gambit a pawn with 10.. Bd6 or go
for the main line with 10.. Bb4 where White must play accurately to collect
the piece. However the resulting endgame gives us drawing chances, although
defending will be a long and tortorous ordeal.} *

