1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 a6 $5 {Black continues setting up on the light
squares with the pawns. This is sort of a useful waiting move, on one had we
wait for White to show his setup but we also take the b5 square under control.}
4. d4 (4. h3 {cutting out Bg4} d4 $1 {The inclusion of a6 and h3 is in Black's
favor here.} 5. Ne2 c5 {Not only does a6 cover against potential Bb5 moves,
but we can also harrass the Bc4 with b5 ourselves} 6. c3 (6. b4 $5 {is logical
but after} Nc6 7. bxc5 e5 8. Ng3 Be6 $1 {[%cal Rf1c4] Against Bc4} 9. Bd3 (9.
Ba3 b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 9... Bxc5 {Black is doing well with the extra space.}
10. O-O h5 $5 (10... f6 {w/Nge7 is more solid and natural}) 11. c3 g5 $40 {
Black starting going all-in in this GM battle: 1/2-1/2 (45) Mastrovasilis,D 
(2606)-Tomczak,J (2588) Lublin 2016}) (6. Ng3 Nc6 7. Bc4 e6 8. a4 Nf6 9. O-O
Bd6 {Looking to complete development with 0-0, Qc7, b6 (or Rb8-b5) bb7} (9...
b6)) 6... Nc6 7. cxd4 (7. Ng3 $2 d3 $1 $17 {White's development is completely
restricted} 8. b3 h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 7... cxd4 8. Ng3 e6) 4... Bg4 {Very
similar to the immediate Bg4 variation but the inclusion of a6 and d4 gives us
information about White's setup while cutting out potential Bb5 idea from White
} 5. h3 (5. Be2 {This is actually White's most common reply and it's worth
familiarizing ourselves with the resulting position. Black scores a very
healthy positive score against this quiet developing move since White isn't
doing anything to trouble our setup} e6 {Solidly applying our light square
strategy without locking in the bishop} 6. O-O Nf6 7. e5 (7. exd5 cxd5 {
This structure is harmless for Black. Our plan will be to play on the
queenside and utilize the semi-open c-file while preparing a minority attack}
8. h3 Bxf3 (8... Bh5 {makes sense too} 9. Bg5 Nc6 10. Ne5 Bxe2 11. Nxe2 Be7 {
0-1 (60) Klabis,R (2355)-Laurusas,T (2409) Panevezys 2017}) 9. Bxf3 Nc6 10. Ne2
Bd6 11. c3 O-O 12. Bf4 Qc7 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nc1 b5 15. Nd3 b4 16. Nxb4 Nxb4
17. cxb4 {a textbook example of a sucessful minority attack. White is now
saddled with a isolated d-pawn and has to defend against the heavy piece
pressure on the queenside} Qxb4 $15 {0-1 (60) Halfhide,S (2151)-Laurusas,T 
(2421) Panevezys 2015}) 7... Nfd7 {In general this type of French position
with an active bishop is exactly our wish in the a6 variation. The plan is to
continue with moves like c5/nc6 (b5) and of course developing with Be7 and 0-0.
} (7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nfd7 {some strong players prefered to play without the
bishop and perhaps avoid the Ng5 idea}) 8. Be3 (8. Ng5 $1 {White goes
aggressive mode to try to justify the space and development edge} Bxe2 9. Qxe2
(9. Nxe2 Be7 10. f4 (10. Nh3 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 10... c5 11. c3 Nc6 12. Nf3 O-O
13. Be3 Rc8) 9... h6 10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh3 Qe7 12. f4 Bg7 13. Nf3 c5 14. Ne2 Nc6)
(8. Ne1 {is a quieter version of Ng5} Bxe2 9. Nxe2 c5 10. c3 Nc6 11. Nd3 c4
$146 12. Ne1 b5 13. f4 g6 {With a light square blockade and an eventual a5-b4
plan}) 8... Be7 9. Re1 O-O 10. a3 c5 $15 {0-1 (41) Kenneskog,T (2270)-Laurusas,
T (2431) Al Ain 2013}) 5... Bxf3 {is the safest way to play and avoiding the
gamble of Bh5} (5... Bh5 $5 {The desired move but punishable by aggresive play}
6. exd5 (6. g4 $1 {The energy White needs here} Bg6 7. Ne5 (7. exd5 cxd5 {TR ML
}) 7... e6 (7... Bxe4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. c3 e6 $14 {White has the two bishops and
should be better with precise play}) 8. exd5 cxd5 9. h4 {is very critical here.
Black's position gets ugly but he was able to hold in} f6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3
Kf7 12. Ne2 Bd6 13. Nf4 Ne7 14. h5 Bxf4 15. Bxf4 Nbc6 16. g5 gxh5 17. gxf6 gxf6
18. c3 Ng6 19. Bxg6+ Kxg6 20. Qe2 Kf7 {1/2-1/2 (20) Safarli,E (2660)
-Mchedlishvili,M (2637) Denizli 2013}) (6. Be2 {is harmless and we achieve our
setup} e6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Ne5 (8. e5 Nfd7 9. Nh2 Bg6 10. Nb1 c5 11. c3 Nc6 12.
Be3 Qb6 $15 {0-1 (68) Rogic,D (2566)-Shengelia,D (2529) Austria 2013}) 8... Bg6
(8... Bxe2 $11) 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Ne2 Bd6 13. c3 Qc7
14. Be3 Ng4 15. Qd2 Nh2 16. Rfe1 Rxh3 17. Bf4 Rh4 18. Bg3 Bxg3 19. Nxg3 O-O-O
20. Qe2 Rdh8 21. Rac1 Ng4 22. Qf3 Rh1+ {0-1 (22) Zelbel,P (2448)-Wojtaszek,R 
(2749) Tallinn 2016} 23. Nxh1 Rxh1+ 24. Kxh1 Qh2#) 6... cxd5 7. g4 $1 Bg6 8.
Ne5 (8. h4 h6 $5 (8... f6 9. h5 Bf7) 9. Ne5 Bh7 10. g5 $1 {[%cal Rg5g6] A very
strong idea} (10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 e6 {seems tenable after developing further
with Nc6}) 10... e6 11. g6 Bxg6 12. Nxg6 fxg6 13. Qg4 Qf6 14. Bh3 Kf7 $16 {
[%cal Gb8c6,Gg8e7,Ge7f5] Black could survive if the Knights get mobilized but
White's intiative here is very potent}) 8... Nc6 (8... e6 {looks like the best
Black can do here} 9. h4 f6 (9... Bb4 $5 {goes for a mess} 10. h5 Be4 11. f3 f6
12. fxe4 fxe5 13. Bg2 $16) 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {TR 6. g4}) 9. h4 Nxe5 10. dxe5 d4 (
10... h5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Nxd5 O-O-O {gambits a pawn for activity and held on
after} 13. Nb6+ Kc7 14. Nc4 e6 15. Bg5 $2 (15. Be3 Rd7 16. g5 Ne7 $16) 15...
Rd7 16. gxh5 Bxh5 $44 {1/2-1/2 (56) Zhao,J (2589)-Zhou,W (2590) Xinghua 2013})
11. h5 {Although Black has even won some games here objectively this is not
working out}) 6. Qxf3 e6 {This gives Black a very solid game although
objectively White's space and bishops should be a long term edge. Nevertheless
Black has done alright here. Some examples:} 7. Be3 (7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9.
exd5 $6 cxd5 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. c3 O-O 12. Bf4 b5 13. a3 Na5 14. Qg3 Nc4 15. b3
Nh5 $15 {0-1 (67) Volovich,V (2062)-Kokarev,D (2640) Voronezh 2017}) (7. Bf4
Nf6 8. e5 $6 {I think closing the position favors Black since it will be
easier to achieve queenside play with c5/b5} Nfd7 9. O-O-O b5 {1/2-1/2 (44)
Robson,R (2567)-Jobava,B (2696) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009} (9... c5)) 7... Nf6 8. e5
(8. Bd3 $14 dxe4 (8... Be7) 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nd7) 8... Nfd7 9. Qg3 c5 10.
dxc5 Nc6 11. O-O-O Qa5 12. f4 g6 13. Qh4 h5 (13... Bxc5 $15) 14. Be2 Be7 15.
Qf2 Bxc5 16. Bxc5 Qxc5 17. Qh4 Qe7 18. Qf2 h4 19. Bf3 O-O-O 20. Ne2 Qc5 21.
Qxc5 Nxc5 22. Nd4 Ne7 23. Rhf1 Kc7 {This type of Endgame is very good for
Black as the knights have good perches and the rooks can pressurize the
queenside} 24. Be2 b5 25. Bd3 Kb6 26. Nf3 Rd7 27. Ng5 Nxd3+ 28. Rxd3 Nf5 29.
Rc3 a5 30. a3 Ra7 31. Kd2 Rb8 32. b4 axb4 33. axb4 d4 34. Rd3 Rc8 35. Rc1 Rc4
$19 {0-1 (59) Kukas,O (2085)-Doric,D (2467) Hum na Sutli 2019  Summary: 3...
a6 is a rare waiting move where we aim for a typical light square setup and
take White out of book. If White tries the clever 4. h3 we have the strong 4..
d4! retort. Meanwhile after 4. d4 we play Bg4 and try to build a light square
formation without our bishop getting in the way. Unfortunately it looks like
playing for Bh5 after h3 can be too dangerous (or a gamble) but taking on f3
gives us a solid flexible position, although White has good chances as well} *

