1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 {The Fantasy Variation. White wants to keep a perfect
pawn center and hopes to use it as a basis to start an attack.} e6 $5 {We
won't take on e4! Now f3 looks out of place since it blocks White's natural
development. This option keeps the game more stable and potentially denies
White the attacking positions he desires. The position resembles a Caro/French
hybrid. I have a rare but well scoring option to show you here...} 4. Nc3 (4.
Be3 {White can play this option to avoid Bb4 after Nc3, but this leaves b2
weak.} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6d4]} (4... dxe4 {it's possible to accept the
gambit pawn although this is the type of play White wants} 5. Nd2 (5. fxe4 Qh4+
6. g3 Qxe4 7. Qe2 Nf6 $44 8. Bg2 Qg4) 5... exf3 6. Ngxf3 Nf6 {White scores
pretty reasonably here}) 5. Nd2 $5 {White tries to play a gambit since
protecting b2 would lose time and allow black a quick center strike.} (5. b3 c5
{[%cal Gb8c6]}) (5. Qc1 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 5... Qxb2 6. Bd3 Qa3 7. Ne2 {
White has a nice lead in development but the closed nature of the position
allows Black to develop soundly. For example:} b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 8. O-O Ba6
{trading a passive piece for a potential attacker} 9. Nb3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Qa6 11.
Qd2 Ba3 12. Ng3 Nd7 13. Nc1 Ne7 {Black is now fully developed, up a pawn, and
getting castled.} 14. Nd3 O-O {0-1 (31) Mitkov,N (2532)-Dreev,A (2676)/Neum
2000/}) 4... Qb6 $5 {[%cal Gb6b2,Gb6d4] This rarer move makes it hard for
White to develop.} (4... Bb4 {This is the main line after} 5. Bf4 (5. a3 $5 {
another gambit idea after} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 dxe4 7. Qe2 {Black's main option has
been to capture on f3 which gives White great compensation and a 67% score in
practice. However the rarer} c5 $1 $15 {counter attacks the center and
prepares a quick Nc6}) (5. Nge2 Ne7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Can be similar to Bf4}) 5...
Ne7 6. Qd3 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 7. Nge2 Ba6 8. Qe3 O-O 9. O-O-O c5 10. a3 Bxc3
11. Qxc3 (11. Nxc3 Bxf1 12. Rhxf1 Nbc6) 11... Nd7 12. Bd6 Rc8 13. Nf4 Bxf1 14.
Rhxf1 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Nc5 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Qa4 d4 $17 {1/2-1/2 (40)
Nepomniachtchi,I (2658)-Shimanov,A (2535) Dagomys 2010}) 5. a3 {White most
popular choice here, the idea is to make b2 poisoned.} (5. Nge2 {is clumsy
development. Simple play is good:} Nf6 6. Ng3 (6. Bg5 $2 {Happened in my
recent online test of this variation} Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qa3 8. Qd3 Qa5 9. Bxf6 gxf6
10. Ng3 h5 $19 {0-1 (27) Agrest,I (2284)-Ostrovskiy,A (2425) chess.com INT 2020
}) 6... c5 $5 (6... Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8]})) 5... Nd7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc6c5]} 6. Be3
Ngf6 {Black is planning a timely e5 or c5 break here. Example game:} (6... Qxb2
$4 7. Na4) 7. Rb1 dxe4 8. fxe4 e5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Qd2 Qc7 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O
exd4 (12... Ng4 $5) 13. Bxd4 Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 {White is simply
saddled with an isolated central pawn and Black has powerful control of the
dark squares (especially e5) . The finish:} 16. Kh1 Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Qf4
Qxf4 19. Rxf4 Rad8 20. Rf2 Ng4 21. Re2 Rf2 22. Rxf2 Nxf2+ 23. Kg1 Rd2 24. Rf1
Ng4 25. h3 Ne3 26. Rf2 Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Nxc2 28. e5 Ne1 29. Ne4 Nd3 30. Nd6 b5 31.
Nc8 Kf7 32. Nxa7 Nxe5 33. Nc8 Ke8 34. Nd6+ Ke7 35. Ne4 Nc4 36. b3 Nxa3 37. Kf2
Nc2 38. Nc5 Kd6 39. Ne4+ {0-1 (39) Das,A (2485)-Roiz,M (2615)/Biel 2012/} *

