1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 e5 {This is a violent reaction that takes the fight
straight to White's face! The point of this sacrifice is to gain rapid
development and access to the dark sqaures weakened by the f2-f3 push. Overall
I don't think this is a fully sound gambit but definitely worth a look as
White can really suffer in case of imprecise play} 4. dxe5 {The acid test} (4.
exd5 {This leads to a good IQP situation for Black} exd4 5. Qxd4 cxd5 {The f3
pawn is in the way of White's development (not to mention the dark square
tenderness) and the Qd4 is going to be hit} 6. Nc3 Be6 (6... Nf6) 7. Bb5+ Nc6)
4... Bc5 {White will not castle for the foreseeable future} 5. Nc3 (5. Bd3 Qb6
(5... dxe4 6. Bxe4 Qh4+ {It will be hard to tell if g3 will inconvenience
White but it does seem reasonable to create more potential weaknesses} (6...
Qe7) 7. g3 Qe7 8. f4 Nf6 9. Bf3 O-O 10. Nc3 Bf5 $44) 6. Ne2 Nd7 7. f4 dxe4 8.
Bxe4 f6 $44 (8... Ngf6 $6 {is probably too fancy but possible} 9. exf6 Nxf6 10.
Nbc3 O-O) (8... Nh6)) 5... Ne7 (5... Qb6 {is tempting but I couldn't fully
make it work in the resulting positions} 6. Na4 $1 {only move} Bf2+ 7. Ke2 Qd4
{Unfortunately we need to trade queens here which makes it harder to attack
White's king} 8. Qxd4 Bxd4 9. f4 {[%cal Gg1f3]} (9. Bf4 dxe4 (9... b5 10. Nc3 (
10. Rd1 $2 Bxg1) 10... Ne7 11. Kd3 Bb6 $16 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc8a6]}) 10. fxe4 Bg4+
11. Nf3 Nd7) 9... dxe4 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Kxe3 f6 (11... f5) 12. Kxe4 fxe5 13.
fxe5 Ne7 {There are some strange positions in these lines where White's king
takes a stroll. The engine evaluates the positions as good for White due to
the material edge but I can see practical compensation for Black}) 6. f4 {
This is very ambitious, White wants to hold the material and develop with Nf3}
(6. Bd3 O-O 7. f4 {is the computer approved response. While I do not dispute
that White may weather the intiative it is also clear that practically
speaking the Ke1 will give Black long term compensation. Here is a sample game
between 2 GMs that ended in a rout} (7. Bg5 $6 {has been played before} Nd7 8.
f4 Qb6 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. c3 Ng6 $15 {[%cal Gh7h6] Black keeps developing and
White's king is stuck in the center...}) 7... Na6 8. Qf3 Qb6 9. Nge2 Nb4 10. g4
$2 Be6 11. Kf1 Nxd3 12. cxd3 Rad8 13. Na4 Qa5 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 15. Nc3 b5 16. Qf2
Qb4 17. f5 dxe4 18. a3 Qb3 19. dxe4 Rd3 20. Bg5 Bc4 21. Kg2 Ng6 22. Ne2 Qxb2
23. Nc1 Nh4+ {0-1 (23) Mitkov,N (2470)-Kallai,G (2490) France 1994}) (6. exd5
$6 {is White's most popular move here but I don't understand the point of
opening the position and helping us develop with Nc6} cxd5 $44) 6... Qb6 7. Nf3
Bf2+ 8. Ke2 a5 $1 {A clever idea, opening the a7 square for the queen in case
of Na4} 9. exd5 $2 {As I mentioned before I'm not sure why White players make
this trade as it just helps us develop} cxd5 10. Qd3 Nbc6 11. Nd1 Bc5 12. Qb3
Nb4 13. a4 d4 14. Ke1 Bf5 15. Bb5+ Nec6 {Incredibly White simply resigned in
0-1 (15) Di Nicolantonio,L (2408)-Loiseau,Q (2470) Paris 2019 as the computer
rates the position as -5 for Black!   Summary: e5!? is a very aggressive
gambit that seeks to refute the fantasy variation outright. Objectively
White's opening play is not refuted but if you are seeking a surprise weapon
or just prefer active play this variation is valid. After Bc5 White's stuck
Ke1 will give Black practical and attacking chances for the middlegame} *

